<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0822 06-10 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0822,0395</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Falk and Wood; An AMs separate moved as a0666 on Duggan.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Duggan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Duggan, a broadway dancer,
died Tuesday of cancer at the age of 56.
   Mrs Duggan began her career at age 17 after studying at the
Professional Children's School in New York City. Her Broadway
credits included ``Brigadoon,'' ``Flahooley,'' ``Month of
Sundays,'' and ``New Faces of '52.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Howard Applegate</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard Applegate, whose career as a United
Press International newsman spanned 40 years, died Thursday of
cancer at age 65.
   Applegate joined United Press in June 1947 after graduating from
the University of Oregon, where he earned a degree in journalism.
After a brief stint in Portland, he was named bureau manager in
Tacoma, Wash., and later worked in the Seattle bureau before he
returned to Portland in 1951.
   Applegate held several posts in Portland and was assistant
bureau manager and sports editor when he retired a year ago.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Leon Falk</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leon Falk Jr., a leading Pittsburgh
industrialist and philanthropist in medicine, politics, social
programs, died Thursday of a stroke. He was 86.
   The Falk family fortune was founded on steel. In 1929 Falk and
his uncle established the Maurice and Laura Falk Foundation. In the
late 1930s he became active in helping Jews escape Nazi Germany.
Falk established an agricultural colony for Jewish immigrants in
the Dominican Republic and sponsored an extensive study into
Israel's agriculture and economy, which helped establish the
fledgling nation's economic ties with foreign lands.
   In the 1960s he urged that the Maurice Falk Medical Fund, which
he created in 1960, concentrate on programs about race relations
and minority affairs.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Wood</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EASTON, MD. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William H. Wood, a retired army brigadier
general an All America football player and one-time head football
coach at the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y., died
Tuesday at age 87.
   Wood attended Johns Hopkins University before moving to West
Point, where he was an All America football player while collecting
12 varsity letters. He served as head football coach at West Point
from 1938 until 1940.
   During World War II, Wood served in China and Europe, becoming
chief of staff of the 13th Armored Division.
</TEXT>
