<HEAD>Minister Acquitted Of Three Counts Of Vehicular Homicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister who drove a truck that lurched into a
crowd during a religious parade last year, killing a pregnant woman
and a 10-year-old girl from his church, has been acquitted of three
charges of vehicular homicide.
   The Rev. Etanislao Gonzales, 47, was found innocent Thursday by
Municipal Court Judge Herbert Hershfang of charges connected with
the August accident, which also left 29 people injured.
   The accident occurred as Gonzales was driving a year-old,
half-ton pickup bedecked with flowers down a narrow street packed
with about 2,000 spectators during the Children and Youth Christian
Parade.
   Idalia Cruz, 10, and Maria Otero Reyes, 21, were killed in the
accident. They were members of Gonzales' small congregation at the
Doors of Salvation Pentacostal Church.
   Because Reyes was seven months pregnant, a third count of motor
vehicle homicide was filed against Gonzales.
