<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Abortion-Liability     06-10 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion-Liability,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abortion Foes Claim Victory in House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion foes are claiming victory from a
House committee vote to exempt abortion-inducing drugs and
contraceptive devices from a proposed shield against punitive
damages in liability lawsuits.
   The proposal was tacked onto a controversial product liability
bill by the House Energy and Commerce Committee on a 21-19 vote
Thursday, shortly after the panel had rejected a much broader
anti-abortion amendment.
   The amendment, sponsored by Rep. Thomas J. Tauke, R-Iowa, would
deny manufacturers of abortion-causing drugs and devices the same
protection against punitive damages that the bill would extend to
other drugs approved by the Food and Drug Administration.
   The Tauke amendment would affect oral contraceptives,
intrauterine devices and new, experimental abortion pills now
marketed in several foreign countries. It would not cover such
contraceptive barriers as condoms, spermicides or cervical caps.
   Douglas Johnson, legislative director of the National Right to
Life Committee, hailed the committee's approval of the Tauke
amendment as ``the most important pro-life victory in Congress in
the past two years.''
   Johnson said the vote ``sends a crystal-clear message to the
pharmaceutical industry that developing and marketing
abortion-causing drugs will be a risky and unprofitable business''
because Congress won't shield them from liability suits.
   But Bill Hamilton, chief lobbyist for Planned Parenthood Inc.,
predicted the anti-abortion provision will be stripped from the
bill by the House Judiciary Committee, which will consider the
measure next if the Energy and Commerce Committee approves it.
   In any case, Hamilton said, the bill has no chance of passing
Congress in this election year _ an assessment shared by Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the Energy and Commerce panel.
   Approval of the Tauke amendment came as Dingell's committee
neared the end of drafting the compromise bill, which is intended
to pre-empt conflicting state liability standards with a uniform
but limited set of federal standards opposed by consumer groups.
   Pro-consumer lobbyists say the measure will make it harder for
victims of unsafe products to recover damages from manufacturers.
Business supporters of the bill say it will help ease the costly
burden of liability suits and make American products more
competitive on foreign trade markets.
   Hamilton scoffed at Johnson's claim that the Tauke amendment
effectively places abortion-inducing drugs and devices in the same
category with alcohol, tobacco and asbestos as dangerous products
under the bill.
   ``We think it's outrageous,'' Hamilton said. ``Basically,
contraceptives are a great deal safer than many other products
protected by that legislation, safer than penicillin, safer even
than driving a car.''
   The Tauke amendment, eagerly sought by anti-abortion lobbyists,
would cover any drug or device that interferes with the implanting
of a human embryo in the uterus, or subsequently aborts a pregnancy.
   The committee rejected on a 21-21 tie vote a broader proposal by
Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., that would have exempted all drugs
that might cause abortions or threaten a man or woman's ability to
produce children.
   Dingell, who opposed both amendments, protested that Sikorski's
proposal would unfairly penalize such necessary products as
aspirin, heating pads, eye drops and drugs necessary for treating
cancer and the AIDS virus.
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said the real purpose of Tauke's
amendment was ``to drive contraceptive manufacturers out of
business.'' He and Dingell noted that such drugs must pass FDA
clearance procedures that are far stricter than those required for
other drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
