<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HastingsImpeach     06-10 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings Impeach,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami Judge Vows ``Donnybrook'' If He Is Impeached</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings of Miami
says a House subcommittee will overwhelmingly exonerate him of
bribery charges and predicts ``a donnybrook of a trial'' in the
Senate if he is impeached.
   ``We have seen a substantial amount of history made,'' Hastings
said Thursday after the House judicial subcommittee on criminal
justice ended its public hearings. ``I am personally relieved and
prepared to go forward if articles of impeachment are approved
against me.''
   The subcommittee will make a recommendation to the full House
Judiciary Committee on whether Hastings, who still sits on the
federal bench, should be impeached. If Hastings is impeached by the
House, the Senate will conduct a trial to determine whether he
should be removed from office.
   ``It will be a donnybrook of a trial,'' Hastings said. ``When
the dust settles, I'll be standing.''
   He said his best estimate is that the subcommittee will vote 7-1
against recommending that he be impeached, with Rep. Patrick L.
Swindall, R-Ga., probably casting the only negative vote against
him.
   He said, however, that ``the vote may go against me because
we're in a political situation here.''
   Chairman John Conyers, D-Mich., said the panel's record would
remain open for another week for additional comments by Hastings'
attorneys. Conyers declined to predict when the subcommittee would
act, saying it depended on what Hastings' lawyers submitted.
   Conyers ended the public hearings after permitting Hastings to
call two witnesses against allegations he conspired to take a bribe
in exchange for modifying the sentences of two racketeers. Hastings
had requested that the panel hear more than 100 witnesses.
   Florreyn Joyette ``Joy'' Royals, a member of the Metro Miami
Action Plan, a civil rights organization, contradicted testimony
from Dade County Mayor Steve Clark that Hastings gave him
information which FBI agents have said caused them to stop three
major investigations because a wiretap had been compromised.
   Clark testified before the subcommittee that he talked to
Hastings after a speech on Sept. 6, 1985, and the judge told him to
stay away from Kevin ``Waxy'' Gordon, against whom Hastings had
approved an FBI wiretap. Gordon was the target of an FBI corruption
investigation.
   Miss Royals told the subcommittee that Hastings left the hotel
ballroom as soon as he completed making his speech and did not talk
to the mayor.
   The Rev. Bryan O. Walsh, a Catholic priest in the Miami diocese,
testified that he talked briefly with Hastings and Clark together
before the breakfast meeting.
   Hastings declined to testify before the subcommittee.
   In addition to the charge that he compromised the three
investigations by leaking the fact that the FBI had a wiretap,
Hastings also is accused of conspiring with Washington lawyer
William Borders to receive a bribe in exchange for modifying the
sentences of two convicted racketeers.
   Borders, convicted in 1982 of arranging a $150,000 bribe for
Hastings, was sentenced to five years in prison and fined $35,000.
In a separate trial, Hastings was acquitted of the bribery
conspiracy charges.
</TEXT>
