<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     06-10 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estimated Winter Wheat Production Down Amid Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's estimated winter wheat harvest
will be down 3 percent from last month's forecast because of
drought and disease, Agriculture Department economists say.
   ``Inadequate moisture and disease plagued winter wheat in the
central and northern Great Plains during May,'' the department's
Agricultural Statistics Board said in its report released Thursday.
   It estimated winter wheat production at 1.57 billion bushels,
slightly more than last year but still 3 percent below May's
forecast of 1.62 billion bushels. Last year's output was 1.56
billion bushels.
   Satellite photos reportedly show disease is taking a toll on
soft red winter wheat in Kansas and some USDA officials think that
drought could worsen the situation. But they say a healthy rainfall
could ease the problem considerably over much of the country.
   The report put this year's average yield at 39.4 bushels an
acre, down 0.4 bushels from the 1987 level and 1.3 bushels an acre
below the May estimate.
   The report said crop conditions vary through most of the country
but are mostly fair to good except in the Plains where they are
fair.
   Development of the crop was average or better except in the
Pacific Northwest and Colorado, it said. It said the wheat was
turning color in Illinois, Kansas and Missouri and that the harvest
had moved into Oklahoma and expanded across the Delta and Southeast.
   Harvested acres are expected to be 39.8 million acres this year,
the same same estimate that the department issued last month and 1
percent above the level for last season.
   Winter wheat is planted in the fall and harvested the following
summer. It makes up about three-fourths of total U.S. wheat
production.
   The report did not include 1988 production estimates for spring
wheat, corn and other spring-planted crops. The department will
make those forecasts later in the growing season.
   A separate supply and demand report from the Economic Research
Service said that flour and related food production would be lower
by perhaps 35 million bushels and the reduction should offset
somewhat the reduced supply of winter wheat. Thus it projected only
a slight reduction in the nation's wheat stockpile.
   The Kansas winter wheat crop, as usual the largest by far, was
estimated at 329 million bushels, down from 366.3 million in 1987.
The yield was put at 35 bushels per acre compared with 37 bushels
last year. The state's farmers also trimmed their acreage to 9.4
million acres from 9.9 million in 1987.
   Indicated production of winter wheat and average yields in 1988
by major producing states, based on June 1 prospects, included:
   Arkansas, 41,800,000 bushels and an average yield of 44 bushels
per acre; California, 35,640,000 and 81; Colorado, 86,950,000 and
37; Georgia, 19,780,000 and 43; Idaho, 56,880,000 and 72; Illinois,
61,600,000 and 55; Indiana, 34,300,000 and 49; Kansas, 329,000,000
and 35; Kentucky, 15,990,000 and 41; Michigan, 29,140,000 and 47;
Missouri, 65,800,000 and 47; Montana, 52,800,000 and 24; Nebraska,
86,100,000 and 42; North Carolina, 18,900,000 and 42; Ohio,
49,920,000 and 48; Oklahoma, 176,400,000 and 36; Oregon, 42,900,000
and 66; South Dakota, 46,500,000 and 30; Tennessee, 14,820,000 and
39; Texas, 92,800,000 and 29; Washington, 89,100,000 and 54.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Department economists are
estimating Soviet wheat imports for 1987-88 at 21.5 million tons,
down 500,000 from last month's forecast but still the second
highest on record.
   The department said Thursday that the pace of that nation's
imports has slowed in recent weeks, possibly a reaction to higher
wheat prices combined with the healthy outlook for the estimated 92
million-ton Soviet crop.
   The United States, with wheat sales of over 12 million tons thus
far this year, will account for more than 50 percent of the Soviet
market for foreign wheat, followed by Canada and the European
Community, the report said.
   It said the United States also is expected to be the largest
supplier of coarse grains to the Soviets, with 40 percent of this
year's market. Nearly three-fourths of the imports are expected to
be corn.
   Most of the remainder will be barley, primarily from Canada and
Western Europe, the report said.
</TEXT>
