<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MurderContract     06-10 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder Contract,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guilty Verdicts In Murder Conspiracy Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jordanian couple were convicted
Thursday of plotting to murder their unwanted son-in-law and two of
his relatives and have their bodies mutilated to avenge the family
honor.
   A Broward Circuit Court jury deliberated six hours before
finding Saud Tarawneh guilty of three counts of conspiracy to
commit murder and one count of solicitation to commit first-degree
murder.
   His wife Ghada was convicted of the three conspiracy counts but
was acquitted of solicitation. No one was injured in the alleged
plot.
   ``I love my daughter,'' Mrs. Tarawneh, 44, said after the
verdicts were announced.
   The prosecution contended during the weeklong trial that the
plot was hatched because the Tarawnehs were angered that their
daughter Raniah had married her Syrian cousin in 1986 over their
objections and moved to Tamarac.
   The Tarawnehs, who left Jordan 18 years ago and live in Toledo,
Ohio, were arrested last February. Prosecutors said Tarawneh, a
gynecologist, and his wife, a nurse, plotted the murder of Mouataz
Abdulsamad, his sister and mother to avenge the elopement.
   The prosecution also argued Tarawneh believed the killings,
along with the preservation of certain body parts and color photos
of the corpses, would enable him to restore the family's honor in
his native Jordan.
   The Tarawnehs' plans allegedly included instructions for the
killer to hang all three people, take photographs of the bodies and
mutilate them.
   The defense portrayed Tarawneh, 46, as a paranoid alcoholic,
easily manipulated and sometimes out of touch with reality. His
wife is a borderline psychotic, according to a clinical
psychologist called by the defense.
   Defense lawyer Barry Roderman said the Tarawnehs were exploited
and deceived by Ron Petrillo, a private investigator who uncovered
the alleged plot.
</TEXT>
