<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SexScandals Bjt   06-10 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Scandals, Bjt,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Even Genteel World of Cricket Rocked by Sex Scandals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sex for sale at Harrods? Prince Charles's polo
manager in a massage parlor? Sex frolics in a parliamentary shower
room? England's cricket captain fired for having female company in
his hotel room?
   Recent weeks have yielded an unusually rich harvest of lurid
tales for London's anything-goes tabloid newspapers. With the
firing of captain Michael Gatting on Thursday, it seems that not
even the genteel world of cricket is being spared.
   Gatting, 31, was summoned by the team selectors to answer
newspaper allegations that two of his players had sex on a lawn
outside their hotel Sunday night, and that he took a woman to his
room for sex.
   The alleged offense, as far as the selectors were concerned, was
that it happened while a five-day game, or test, was in progress
against the West Indies in Nottinghamshire.
   ``Warnings had previously been issued to all England players
concerning the standard of behavior expected of them at all times,
both on and off the field, and these had been ignored,'' said a
statement by the Test and County Cricket Board, the game's
governing body.
   Gatting, who is married and has two children, issued a statement
saying: ``I categorically deny allegations of sexual impropriety
which have been made against me by certain newspapers,'' and said
he would sue them. The allegations appeared Wednesday and Thursday
in the Sun, Today and the Daily Mirror.
   The cricket board said the selectors believed Gatting's account.
   So why fire him?
   Because, the statement said, ``Gatting behaved irresponsibly
during a test match by inviting female company to his room for a
drink in the late evening.''
   Therefore, it added, in the genteel language that still governs
the cricketing world, ``the invitation to Mike Gatting to captain
the England team ... has been withdrawn,'' and Gatting ``did not
wish to be considered for selection'' for the team for the second
game, starting June 16.
   The other three scheduled games were not mentioned, and Gatting
brushed reporters aside as he left.
   ``You've got to be extra careful for the good name of cricket,''
former captain Ted Dexter said in a TV interview. ``At the same
time it's a pretty sad day if a young man can't meet a nice girl
and spend a happy evening with her without being accused of frolics
and romps.''
   Today editor David Montgomery told the same interviewer:
``Perhaps the selectors should have more of a sense of humor about
lively behavior off the pitch.''
   But team manager Micky Stewart told a news conference ``cricket
has been let down by it, English cricket.''
   The scandal isn't yet over. Four other players will be
questioned about sex allegations today, Stewart said.
   Gatting, a stocky, bearded Londoner, did not attend an
upper-crust school like most previous captains, and his appointment
as captain in 1986 was greeted by the Observer newspaper as
``another step ... toward the classless society.''
   But although Gatting was decorated by Queen Elizabeth II for his
cricketing prowess, his captaincy has been lackluster. He has won
only two of his 23 international games as captain, and the West
Indies match ended Tuesday in a draw. Last year he was officially
censured for having a foul-mouthed shouting match with a Pakistani
umpire during a match in Faisalabad.
   Gatting got into further trouble for writing a book giving his
version of the Faisalabad incident, and had to promise the cricket
board he would withdraw the relevant chapter.
   Cricket is not the only English institution to take a tarnishing
in recent weeks.
   Ronald Ferguson, father of Sarah, the Duchess of York and polo
manager of Prince Charles, narrowly escaped expulsion from his polo
club last month after the tabloid Sunday People photographed him
leaving a London massage parlor.
   Two weeks ago a lawmaker for the opposition Labor Party publicly
denied newspaper allegations that he frolicked with a secretary in
a House of Commons shower room, and on Wednesday the Mirror claimed
saleswomen at the Harrods department store were selling sexual
favors to customers.
   Harrods said the women worked for perfume sellers using space in
the department store, and were not Harrods employees, but added an
investigation was under way.
</TEXT>
