<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeaverBattle     06-10 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beaver Battle,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Official Finds Beaver A Dam Nuisance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHELMSFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Each night she builds a dam. Each
morning he breaks it down.
   This frustrating relationship has been going on since last month
between a beaver just doing what comes naturally and a town
official just doing his job.
   ``We haven't come up with a name for her yet,'' said
Conservation Commission Chairman James McBride. ``But you should
hear some of the names I call her when I'm out there in the morning
knocking down the dam.''
   The beaver bedevilment began for McBride in late May, when a dam
built by the animals on Deep Brook caused flooding on nearby
streets. Snares were placed around the stream to catch the pair of
beavers alive, but only the male beaver was nabbed and released in
a 330-acre bog across town last week.
   Attempts to apprehend the beaver's mate have been unsuccessful.
   ``She's a shrewd one,'' said McBride. ``She hasn't come near the
traps ... but don't worry, we'll catch her.''
   McBride, who theorizes the female beaver may have become
familiar with the traps' appearance, pulled the snares on Thursday.
   ``We'll put them back on Monday and maybe we'll catch her off
guard,'' said McBride. ``Maybe she'll get careless.''
   McBride also has hopes that the urge to mate may deflect some of
the beaver's attention from her dam-building mission.
   ``It's mating season, so we want to get them together,'' he
said. ``Right now, the mate is out in the bog by himself eating
poplar trees _ their favorite thing to eat.''
   Despite McBride's matchmaking aspirations, the beaver may yet
get to keep her dam after all. If the beaver is found to be
nursing, she will be returned to the brook.
   ``If she's already given birth, then we'll put her back for the
summer,'' said McBride. ``There's nothing else we can do. She would
win.''
   Meanwhile, the commission has delayed installation of a
state-ordered pipe system to regulate water flow through the brook.
   He said the pipes could kill any beavers in the brook by
lowering the water depth to a point where it would freeze solid to
the bottom in winter.
   ``One way or another we'll get the flooding problem figured
out,'' said McBride. ``The first thing on my mind at this point is
catching that beaver.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
