<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NicaraguaChronology     06-10 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua Chronology,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Look At How The Nicaraguan Peace Process Evolved</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The negotiations to end Nicaragua's
six-year civil war between the leftist Sandinista government and
the U.S.-backed Contra rebels stem from the regional peace plan
signed by the presidents of five Central American nations.
   Here is a chronology detailing Nicaragua's participation in the
peace-seeking process:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   AUG. 7 _ Presidents of Costa Rica, Honduras, El Salvador,
Guatemala and Nicaragua sign peace plan sponsored by Costa Rican
President Oscar Arias. It includes amnesties for political
prisoners, democratic reforms, an end to foreign aid for rebel
armies, and a prohibition against one country's allowing guerrillas
to use its territory to attack another.
   NOV. 6 _ President Daniel Ortega asks Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo, archbishop of Managua, to mediate indirect cease-fire talks
between Sandinistas and Contras.
   NOV. 19-23 _ Nicaragua's National Assembly approves bills to
lift state of emergency and grant amnesty to some prisoners when
U.S. aid to Contras ends and other nations comply with regional
peace plan. Government frees 985 political prisoners in show of
compliance with plan.
   DEC. 3 _ Indirect talks between Sandinista government and
Contras begin in Dominican Republic, mediated by Obando y Bravo. No
progress in first round.
   DEC. 22 _ Second round of talks breaks off after Contras insist
on meeting face to face with Sandinistas. Both sides participate in
a two-day Christmas cease-fire, but there are many reports of
violence.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 16 _ Responding to pressure from other Central American
nations at meeting in Costa Rica, Ortega agrees to open direct
talks with Contras mediated by Obando y Bravo.
   JAN. 19 _ Nicaragua lifts six-year-old state of emergency in
Nicaragua.
   JAN. 28 _ First direct talks between Sandinistas and Contras
begin in Costa Rica.
   FEB. 18 _ Second round of talks lasts only one day and is broken
off by Obando y Bravo, who cites inflexibility on both sides.
Cardinal calls for talks to include democratic reforms.
   MAR. 2 _ After series of letters between Obando y Bravo and
Ortega, Ortega calls for face-to-face talks.
   MAR. 8 _ Contras back out of talks set for next day, citing lack
of preparation.
   MAR. 17 _ American troops arrive in Honduras as show of force
against Nicaragua, whose forces reportedly have crossed the
Honduran border in offensive against Contra rebels.
   MAR. 21 _ Contras and Sandinistas meet face-to-face for first
time in Nicaraguan territory at southern border post Sapoa. Each
announces halt to offensive military operations.
   MAR. 23 _ Sandinista leaders and Contra representatives announce
cease-fire plan that would end war by May 31.
   MAR. 27 _ Sandinistas free 100 political prisoners.
   MAR. 28 _ Technical teams meet at Sapoa again to discuss
mechanics of cease-fire.
   APR. 1 _ Formal truce begans.
   APR. 4 _ Second round of unsuccessful technical talks at Sapoa.
   APR. 14 _ Third round of technical talks begins.
   APR. 15 _ Contra leaders come to Managua for first time to hold
three days of high-level talks with Sandinistas.
   APR. 28 _ Second round of talks in Managua.
   MAY 26 _ Three days of meetings in Managua. Sandinistas offer
proposal following Contra demand for democratic reforms.
   MAY 31 _ Truce ends. Sandinistas extend it to June 30, Contras
agree to prolong cease-fire until June 9.
   JUNE 7 _ Two sides attempt talks for fourth time. Contras say
they will not resume meetings if no agreement is reached.
Sandinistas offer compromise plan calling for democratic reforms
before full disarmament by Oct. 10.
   JUNE 9 _ Contras reject Nicaraguan compromise plan. No new talks
scheduled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ArabSummit     06-10 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arab Summit,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Greatly Strengthened By Unrestricted Arab Backing</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat and the PLO emerged from
the Arab summit meeting greatly strengthened for their
confrontation with Israel by the unqualified material and moral
support of the Arab leaders.
   Saudi Arabia and the other oil-rich Persian Gulf states for the
first time agreed to pay the Palestine Liberation Organization a
substantial subsidy to intensify the 6-month-old Palestinian
uprising in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   The amount of the subsidy officially was kept secret to avoid
showing the Arab hand to the Israelis. But delegates said it was
set at $118 million for the first year.
   This fell short of the $600 million a year Arafat said he needed
to keep the full heat of the revolt on the Israelis, but it meant a
solid boost to what the Palestinian leader has described as the
``stone-throwing revolution.''
   The oil-exporting states told the PLO they could not meet its
full financial needs because their income has been hurt by an
unstable world oil market and by the effects of the Iran-Iraq war.
Arafat was widely believed to have overstated his real needs in the
expectation that his demands would not be fully met.
   Arafat's associates made no secret that he was overjoyed with
the outcome of the summit.
   The PLO leader said the money would be used to pay relief and
medical treatment for injured rioters, help the families of those
killed or injured and compensate strikers for lost wages.
   Arafat did not specify what other uses he had in mind for the
windfall, but it was clear the subsidy could also allow the PLO to
step up its efforts to smuggle small arms and communications and
sabotage equipment to the rioters.
   ``The conference stresses its full commitment to extend all the
support needed to secure the continuation and escalation of the
uprising under the leadership of the PLO,'' the summit's final
communique declared.
   However tightly Israel tries to keep the 1.5 million
Palestinians in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip sealed off from
the outside world, never an easy task at best of times, the PLO's
riot fund will not make it any easier.
   The Arab leaders made a further significant gesture in Arafat's
favor by deciding the PLO henceforth should be the sole master of
the insurgency fund. This meant Arafat will no longer have to share
any part of his funds with Jordan or with a joint PLO-Jordanian
support committee.
   The summit also endorsed previous Arab decisions to recognize
the PLO as the ``sole and legitimate representative of the
Palestinian people,'' automatically branding non-PLO Palestinians
who choose to work with the Israelis in the occupied territories as
traitors.
   It reiterated Arafat's earlier scornful dismissal of U.S.
Secretary of State George P. Shultz's latest peace plan and
insisted that the PLO must participate with full delegation status
in any international peace conference.
   The United States and Israel regard the PLO as a terrorist
organization and refuse to envisage any role for it in the peace
process.
   The Arab leaders went beyond previous summits by endorsing more
strongly than ever the Palestinians' right to set up a sovereign
state in the West Bank and east Jerusalem, captured by Israel in
the 1967 war. Israel has proclaimed the reunited holy city as its
capital and is unlikely to relinquish its control of it.
   Nonetheless, the summit's endorsement in effect strengthened
Arafat's status as a full-fledged head of state in Arab eyes. It
was likely to boost him even further in the eyes of Soviet leaders
who have long supported him.
   Arafat also strengthened his position against his more militant
rivals within the PLO by apparently achieving a full reconciliation
with Syria's Soviet-backed president, Hafez Assad. Their relations
seemed to have warmed considerably since they met in Damascus in
April following five years of open hostility.
   Assad conferred privately with Arafat for more than two hours
shortly before the final session.
   On the strength of what he believes is a new relationship with
Assad, Arafat soon may be in a position to beat down his rivals in
the Palestinian camp. These include the Syrian-backed Abu Moussa,
who has led several armed revolts against the PLO chairman in
recent years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Goldsmith, North Africa correspondent
for The Associated Press, has been reporting on Middle East affairs
for 30 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
