<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Women     06-10 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Women,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sociologist Says Soviets Need Full-Time Mothers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The working Soviet mother spends no more than 30
minutes a week raising her children, and her mate spends only six
minutes, a sociologist said in a plea for mothers to make children
their prime mission.
   ``Such negative phenomena as juvenile delinquency are largely
explained by the inadequate attention shown to children by their
parents,'' Tatyana Zaslavskaya told the official Tass news agency
in an interview published Thursday.
   The remarks of the prominent sociologist, one of the
theoreticians of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's drive for economic and
social change, clash with longstanding Soviet orthodoxy.
   The government has maintained for decades that its network of
day-care centers, kindergartens and schools could raise children
while both parents occupy full-time jobs.
   But Ms. Zaslavskaya, who conducted a poll of Soviet parents,
rejected that logic.
   ``The time spent by working mothers on spiritual communication
with their children, that is, directly on their upbringing, does
not exceed, according to our poll findings, a weekly 30 minutes,''
she said.
   ``The figure for men is even lower, or six minutes a week,'' the
Soviet sociologist said.
   Ms. Zaslavskaya's conclusion: ``The high rate of employment
among working-age women _ 94 percent _ tells especially adversely
on their prime mission _ the upbringing of children.''
   The recent Western phenomenon of the ``Super Mom'' has been
known for years in the Soviet Union, where it is wryly referred to
as ``the problem of two jobs.''
   After a typical Soviet woman finishes her job at the factory,
shop or office, she heads home, where shopping, cooking, cleaning
and keeping house await her.
   Her husband traditionally feels it is beneath him to help,
either with the housework or the children.
   A 1987 report to a Soviet national conference on women said that
because of the lack of home appliances and the need to spend hours
in lines while shopping, ``the time expended on housework by a
woman is almost equal to the length of another entire working day.''
   Ms. Zaslavskaya, the president of the Soviet Sociological
Association, proposed that more Soviet women stay home and rear
their children full-time.
   So far, that has not been possible in the Soviet Union because
of economics, she said. ``Most men won't be able to ensure a
dignified life for their families if their wives don't work and
earn money, too.''
   The average Soviet industrial wage is now only about 200 rubles,
or the equivalent of about $330 a month.
   But Ms. Zaslavskaya said that as economic reforms instituted by
Gorbachev begin to bear fruit, wages will be pegged to individual
job performance, or the output of a given work collective, and two
incomes will not be needed to keep a family financially afloat.
   ``The choice between having a job and being a housewife is thus
going to become a reality,'' Tass quoted her as saying.
   Ms. Zaslavskaya said surveys show that 40 percent of Soviet
women with children would like to be homemakers if the wages of
their husbands were ``at least equal to the current combined
earnings of man and wife.''
   She called on a nationwide conference of the Communist Party
convening June 28 to discuss ways ``to reduce excessively high
employment levels among women.''
   But that seems doubtful as the Kremlin leadership tries to
mobilize all the country's economic resources behind Gorbachev's
restructuring campaign.
   Women now constitute 51 percent of the nation's 130
million-member labor force and often perform exacting and delicate
work that managers say would be more poorly done by men.
   The Soviet Union remains a resolutely male-dominated society,
although the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution proclaimed the equality of
the sexes. Only one woman, Aleksandra P. Biryukova, serves on the
powerful Communist Party Secretariat, and all 13 voting members of
the ruling Politburo are men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
