<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Suspect     06-10 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Suspect,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Records Say Colorado Man Allegedly Awaited Orders to Kill Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal court records show an informant told
authorities a Colorado man charged last month with threatening the
life of Jesse Jackson was awaiting orders to kill the Democratic
presidential candidate.
   The informant alleged in federal court records that Leland
Bowden, 33, has ``a strong hatred for blacks and Jews,'' and was
expecting the orders from a group called the Christian Patriots
Defense League.
   Bowden, a stockyard worker in La Junta, Colo., was arrested May
14 and charged with making a ``threat against a person protected by
the Secret Service.'' He was released two days later on $5,000
unsecured bond.
   The complaint against Bowden was sealed May 13 at the request of
Assistant U.S. Attorney Joe Mackey, who said he feared Bowden might
flee if the warrant against him were made public before he was
arrested.
   Mackey filed a motion to unseal the complaint June 2, and it was
made public this week.
   On Thursday, Bowden told The Pueblo Chieftain in a telephone
interview that his attorney, a federal public defender, advised him
against discussing the case.
   Asked about the Christian Patriots Defense League, Bowden told
the newspaper, ``I don't have any information about (it).''
   According to the U.S. Secret Service complaint, Bowden told one
witness ``it was biblically and personally right to kill persons
that were destroying America.''
   Bowden came under suspicion April 25 when an informant contacted
Police Detective John Spencer in La Junta about Bowden. The
informant was interviewed the next day by Secret Service Special
Agent Robert Hislop and Denver Police Detective Billy Carter.
   Hislop said Bowden told the informant he would kill Jackson. The
court file described the distance from which Bowden would shoot
Jackson.
   Secret Service and FBI agents placed Bowden under surveillance
on May 6. According to Hislop, the federal agents overheard him
saying he was waiting for orders to kill Jackson.
   ``Bowden stated that if he was ordered, he would blow up the
White House, but that he had not been told to do it,'' Hislop's
report said.
   It also said Bowden was prepared to plead insanity if he were
arrested for shooting Jackson.
   One witness, John O'Connor of the Sacramento, Calif., area, told
federal agents that Bowden discussed killing Jackson and Henry
Kissinger and appeared mentally unbalanced.
   O'Connor told the agents he had several conversations with
Bowden in La Junta in December and January.
   The complaint, in U.S. District Court in Denver, said Bowden
told O'Connor that Jackson, Kissinger and others ``were destroying
America and it was his duty to kill them in order to save the
country.''
</TEXT>
