<HEAD>Dukakis Looks To Tough Race With Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after pvs penultimate graf bgng ``Next week
...'' to include possible endorsement by Gore; picks up pvs last
graf bgng ``The governor...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, the Democratic nominee-apparent,
looked ahead to a ``tough and competitive'' race with George Bush
in November.
   Dukakis warned backers at a victory bash on Thursday night not
to get overconfident now that he has clinched the nomination. He
also told them to ignore polls indicating he has a lead over Bush.
   The Massachusetts governor promised to campaign aggressively,
but joked that a break from the campaign trail would be welcome
after the grueling primary campaign, which ended with four races on
Tuesday.
   ``My tomato plants need cultivating, my house needs work and I'd
love to have a day off,'' he said.
   Dukakis was devoting the day to Statehouse business today, and
had a meeting set with Azores President Mota B. Amaral. A day
earier, he met with Costa Rican President Oscar Arias.
   The governor did not directly respond to remarks made about him
by Bush earlier Thursday. The vice president told Republicans in
Houston that Dukakis' views are ``out of the mainstream'' and
attacked his positions on a variety of issues.
   Dukakis said only: ``It's going to be a tough, competitive
race.''
   His spokesman, Leslie Dach, called Bush's remarks
``mudslinging,'' and added: ``It's clear that the vice president
doesn't think that his own record or vision can bring him the votes
he needs in November.''
   Thursday night's celebration raised nearly $500,000, said
campaign fund-raiser Robert Farmer. That money will go toward a $2
million fund campaign officials want to raise for post-primary
legal and administrative costs.
   The campaign already has raised the maximum $27.6 million
allowed to be spent during the primary season.
   Dukakis' campaign, meanwhile, continued its survey of potential
running mates, and worked on getting ready for July's Democratic
National Convention.
   The governor told backers Thursday night he was happy to have
his wife Kitty home again. Mrs. Dukakis, 51, was released from
Massachusetts General Hospital on Thursday, six days after
underdoing spinal surgery.
   ``You're looking at the luckiest guy on the face of the earth,''
Dukakis said.
   Next week, Dukakis will head to the South for three days of
campaigning. He is also expected to receive visits from several
members of Congress.
   The Atlanta Constitution reported in today's editions that one
endorsement Dukakis is likely to pick up during his swing South
would be from former rival Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
   ``It's really just a matter of time before there is an
announcement by Senator Gore on what his plans are with respect to
an endorsement and possibly releasing delegates,'' Mike Kopp,
Gore's press secretary, told the newspaper.
   The newspaper quoted sources in both campaigns as saying they
are examining the logistics of an announcement in Tennessee next
Thursday, the first day of Dukakis' three-day swing through the
South.
   The governor was attending the Massachusetts Democratic
Convention on Saturday, and on Sunday he was to address the
nation's mayors at a national conference in Salt Lake City.
</TEXT>
