<1ST_LINE>r r PM-Panama     06-10 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Firms Caught Between U.S., Panamanian Obligations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sanctions designed to push Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega from power are hurting American companies in
Panama and could force some of them to close, businessmen say.
   American companies are caught between their obligations to
Panama and to the United States, which has ordered them not to pay
taxes to their host country.
   Under a complex, 52-page U.S. Treasury Department order, signed
in April by President Reagan as part of the economic sanctions
aimed at overthrowing Noriega, the companies face fines or
imprisonment if they pay taxes, services or duties to Panama. In
addition, they are prohibited from contributing to the Panamanian
Social Security Institute.
   ``They are shooting at the wrong target,'' said Federico Denton,
executive director of the Panamanian-American Chamber of Commerce,
in a recent interview.
   ``You could not even buy a Panamanian air mail stamp if you were
an American company operating here when this was first announced,''
said Denton, who added that some exceptions were made later when
U.S. companies protested.
   Noriega, who has been indicted in the United States on drug
trafficking charges, heads the Panamanian Defense Forces and is the
power behind Panama's goverment.
   When President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire him in
February, Noriega had him ousted. Delvalle is now in hiding.
   There are more than 60 U.S. subsidiaries here with a total
investment in plant and inventory of more than $2 billion.
   ``The sanctions practically keep us from operating here,'' said
Carlos Rodriguez, manager of Colgate-Palmolive. ``It is a Catch-22
situation. We abide by U.S. law and we violate Panamanian law, or
vice versa.''
   The Panamanian government has been very flexible and has not
demanded payments or taken over any of the companies, company
managers say.
   ``The government does not want the U.S. companies to leave and
knows that it is not their fault,'' Rodriguez said.
   Denton said that to keep their employees covered under the
Panamanian Social Security system, some of the companies simply
hand over the money to the employee to pay into the system
directly. Others have expanded their own private medical plans for
the employees.
   Companies like Texaco had to collect a gasoline sales tax and
turn it over to the government every month. To avoid U.S. penalties
Texaco now does not collect the tax, but at the moment of purchase
the buyer separates the tax and hands it over directly to a
government collector.
   ``Now the government gets the tax money every day instead of
once a month,'' said a U.S. businessman who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Meanwhile, tons of supplies stack up in Panamanian customs
because the companies cannot get them out without paying taxes.
   The companies also cannot repatriate dividends because they must
first pay taxes.
   ``We told them in Washington that they were hurting the wrong
people, that we would have to dismiss Panamanian workers, someone
there detached from reality told us that `there is a sacrifice
quota that must be paid,''' Rodriguez said.
   U.S. businessmen believe the measures are not going to overthrow
Noriega and his regime.
   ``But they are going to affect U.S. international
competitiveness,'' Rodriguez said. ``U.S. companies should not be
used as tools of U.S. policy.''
   Colgate-Palmolive has not dismissed any employees but has
reduced working hours by 50 percent.
   Danilo Gutierrez, sale manager for Alambres y Cables de Panama,
a subsidiary of Phelps-Dodge, said the company is about four weeks
away from using up all its inventory. It manufactures cable and
telephone wires for local markets and exports to the Caribbean
including Puerto Rico.
   ``Our sales to U.S. markets were also reduced considerably
becasue we were removed from the preferential treatment system,''
said Gutierrez.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
