<DOCNO> AP880610-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Europe-Cocaine     06-10 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Europe-Cocaine,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say Cocaine Use Increasing In Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL CIRULLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe could be heading for a cocaine epidemic as
drug dealers search for new markets to replace dwindling demand in
the United States, experts at an international conference on drug
abuse said.
   Researchers at the four-day International Drug Abuse
Epidemiology Conference in Rome said Thursday there are signs that
cocaine use is increasing in Europe, especially among users of
heroin and amphetamines.
   Nicholas Kozel, an official with the U.S.-based National
Institute on Drug Abuse, a sponsor of the conference, said cocaine
traffickers have moved into Europe because use of the drug has
leveled off in the United States.
   The weak U.S. dollar has contributed to the spread because the
drug has become more affordable to Europeans, he said.
   ``The economic conditions really influence (the spread of drugs)
because the bottom line of drug trafficking is dollars and very big
dollars,'' Kozel said in an interview.
   Cocaine use in Europe is expected to follow patterns set in the
United States in the last three to five years, said Christopher
Luckett, secretary to the Pompidou Group, a France-based drug
research organization representing 19 European countries.
   ``We've learned that cocaine use booms, it peaks and then it
drops. And we know we have to go through this in Europe. The
question is how big is this boom going to be,'' Luckett said.
   Heroin currently is the most abused drug in Europe, followed by
amphetamines, he said.
   In the United States, a 1985 survey by the National Institute on
Drug Abuse showed that 22 million people over the age of 11 had
used cocaine at least once, Kozel said.
   More recent surveys show cocaine use is tapering off among the
general U.S. population because there is a growing awareness of the
drug's dangers, Kozel said. But cocaine use has spread into the
inner city areas as the drug has become more affordable, he said.
</TEXT>
