<HEAD>South Korean Army Activates Olympic Support Command</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army today activated a special
unit to help with security at the upcoming Olympic Games and guard
against terrorist attacks.
   The Olympic support command was formally put into action in a
ceremony attended by generals and sports officials at a military
camp near the capital.
   Army Chief of Staff Park Hee-do said the army will provide
maximum support to ensure a successful Olympics by fully utilizing
its manpower, equipment and other resources.
   The support covers security against possible terrorist attack,
protection of athletes and team officials, transportation, and
manpower assistance for Games officials, the Seoul Olympic
Organizing Committee said. Committee officials said the army will
make available aircraft and other equipment, blankets, vehicles and
supplies worth a total of $28 million.
   The Yonhap News Agency said 9,000 officers and men will be
assigned to the special unit, led by a major general, during the
Games, to be held Sept 17-Oct. 2.
   Police also have formed an anti-terrorist command group to guard
against possible terrorist attacks, particularly from Communist
North Korea.
