<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-USMilitary     06-10 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-US Military,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Asks U.S. Navy to Move Night Practice Flights to Iwo Jima</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has asked the U.S. Navy to move its night
practice landings from a densely populated area to the remote
island of Iwo Jima, site of one of the fiercest U.S.-Japanese
battles in World War II.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Koichi Haraguchi said Thursday that
U.S. officials have not yet responded to a suggestion that they
move the practice flights from Atsugi Air Base in the Tokyo area to
Iwo Jima, about 750 miles to the south.
   Haraguchi said the Japanese government proposed the temporary
move to counter mounting complaints from Atsugi residents about
noise.
   In addition, strong opposition from citizens of Miyake Island,
selected by the government as the site of a new permanent night
landing strip, has slowed construction plans there.
   ``The Japanese government position is still the same regarding
Miyake,'' Haraguchi told reporters at a regular news briefing.
   Defense administration officials selected Miyake Island, 115
miles from Tokyo, as the most suitable site for a new night landing
airstrip for U.S. planes from the carrier Midway, based in Japan.
   But 85 percent of the island's 4,300 residents have signed
petitions against the planned air strip.
   Miyake village head Haruo Terasawa, elected in 1984 on an
anti-airstrip platform, welcomed the Iwo Jima proposal as ``one
fruitful outcome'' of the islanders' opposition movement.
   ``But we will not give up on our fight against a permanent air
strip here until the government completely abandons its plan,'' he
told The Associated Press.
   Setsuko Sakuraba, spokeswoman for the Defense Facilities
Administration Agency, said a temporary site was necessary
``because construction of the landing strip on Miyake will take a
long time due to the opposition movement.''
   The agency handles all construction projects designed to support
U.S. military needs in accordance with the U.S.-Japan Security
Treaty, implemented in 1952 and revised in 1960.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Haruguchi said Iwo Jima was only one
proposed landing site, but he did not name any other possible
locations.
   Tiny Iwo Jima was the site of a February 1945 battle that
claimed the lives of 6,800 Americans and 20,000 Japanese. The
United States maintained jurisdiction over the island from 1945
until 1968, when control passed over to Japan.
   Off-limits to ordinary tourists, it is now used only by the
Japanese Self Defense Forces as a practice ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
