<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BishopExecution 3rdLd-Writethru a0483 06-10 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop Execution, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0483, a0485, a0487,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bishop Executed By Injection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines urgent series, restores byline, LEADS with 4 grafs
to UPDATE with quote from official and details of execution. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT OF THE MOUNTAIN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Gary Bishop was put to
death by injection early Friday for the sex-related murders of five
boys, an execution he sought hoping to bring peace to his victims'
families.
   ``There was nothing unusual. He went peacefully to the execution
chamber,'' Myron March, Department of Corrections director of field
operations, said after Bishop was pronounced dead at 12:16 a.m. He
said a statement from Bishop would be released later.
   Bishop, 36, was the 99th person to be executed in this country
and the third in Utah since a 1976 U.S. Supreme Court ruling ended
a nationwide moratorium on capital punishment and convicted killer
Gary Gilmore, demanding death, was executed by a Utah firing squad
in early 1977.
   In the hours before three drugs in succession _ sodium
pentothal, the muscle relaxant Pavulon and potassium chloride _
were dripped by IV into his right arm, Bishop was low-key and
contemplative.
   ``It's unbelievable how calm and cool he is. Even the guards
can't understand it,'' said Mormon Bishop Heber Geurts, a volunteer
chaplain at Utah State Prison who counseled Bishop in his final
days. ``I've dealt with thousands of inmates in 33 years, and he's
the most sorrowful and repentent and remorseful man I've ever dealt
with.''
   An excommunicated Mormon, Eagle Scout and bookkeeper, Bishop
spent Thursday in a 10-by-15 holding cell in the prison's
maximum-security section. His only reading materials were three
issues of ``Ensign'' magazine, a publication of The Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   Because Bishop shunned further appeals, civil rights groups did
not plan to intervene to try to halt the execution.
   Prison chaplain Jay Lowe said Bishop, during a Thursday
afternoon visit, said he felt at peace and was not afraid to die.
   Prison psychologist Al Carlisle said Bishop was a man with
religious feelings who read the Book of Mormon 10 times during his
fours year in prison and used television earphones to block out
inmates' swearing, but is afraid that if he were to go back on the
streets, ``his old impulses would come back.''
   ``I've seen remorse in him from the beginning,'' Carlisle told a
news conference. Bishop ``believes he will be going into the spirit
world, that it will be more peaceful than here. He doesn't believe
he's been forgiven. ...
   ``He believes he can continue to work on the other side on these
problems.''
   Bishop saw his parents for the last time on Tuesday, and prison
officials suspended their usual no-contact policy, removing
Bishop's handcuffs so he could embrace them.
   ``It was a good visit; sorrowful. They hugged each other,''
Geurts said.
   Geurts said Bishop generally was in good spirits Wednesday, but
wept when they prayed together following a long discussion of
spiritual matters.
   Geurts was one of three people Bishop asked to witness the
execution, along with L. Kay Gillespie, a Weber State College
professor studying the death penalty in Utah, and Kathy Luck,
Bishop's biographer.
   Bishop was convicted in 1984 of the murders of Alonzo Daniels,
4; Kim Peterson, 11; Danny Davis, 4; Troy Ward, 6; and Graeme
Cunningham, 13.
   Bishop fired his attorneys in February and said he wanted to die
after the Utah Supreme Court rejected his initial appeal.
   Bishop murdered his first victim, Daniels, on Oct. 16, 1979.
Bishop lured the boy into his apartment with an offer of candy.
When Bishop tried to fondle the boy, the child cried and threatened
to tell his mother.
   Panicking, Bishop struck Daniels on the head with a hammer. The
boy fell to the floor crying, and Bishop drowned him in the
bathtub. He carried the body out in a box past a woman, apparently
the boy's mother, who was frantically calling his name.
   In the months that followed, he relived the experience by
killing 15 or 20 puppies the same way he killed four of his five
victims.
   ``It was so stimulating,'' he said. ``A puppy whines just like
Alonzo did. I would get frustrated at the whining. I would hit them
with hammers or drown them or strangle them.''
   In Utah's last execution, Pierre Dale Selby was executed by
injection last August for the 1974 torture-murders of three people.
People on death row in Utah choose between lethal injection and
firing squad.
</TEXT>
