<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Terrorists     06-10 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Terrorists,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans in Beijing on Alert for Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITING to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western hotels heightened security today and
children were told not to talk to strangers because of a warning
from the U.S. Embassy that Americans may become targets of
terrorist attacks.
   ``We are on the alert for all unusual occurrences and have added
a few more people to our security staff,'' said Max Wilhelm,
manager of the Sheraton Great Wall Hotel. ``But it's hard to say
where to look and what to look for.''
   The embassy sent out an ``urgent notice to American citizens''
Thursday, saying Chinese authorities told the embassy ``nationals
of a third country may be planning a terrorist attack on Americans
in Beijing.''
   Embassy officials in Beijing said the Chinese reported there was
Middle East involvement, but provided no details. They said
high-level Chinese public security officers informed the embassy of
the threat on Wednesday.
   There are approximately 1,500 American businessmen, diplomats,
students, teachers and their families in Beijing.
   Scott Chambers, principal of the International School of
Beijing, said the school blocked off the road leading to the school
building, locked the back doors and notified security officers to
increase their vigilance.
   ``Our security perimeter is pretty vulnerable,'' he said.
   Chambers said children were told of the warning at a morning
assembly and that teachers will stress to their students not to
talk to strangers.
   ``We're trying to keep it below the panic stage. It's a fine
line,'' he said. The school is supported by the governments of the
United States, Britain, Australia, Canada and New Zealand.
   Embassy officials said they were taking ordinary precautions and
few signs emerged of an increase in already tight security around
embassy buildings.
   Solitary Chinese guards continued to man posts outside the
buildings, and, as usual, young Chinese hoping to receive a visa to
go to the United States milled around the outside of the consular
affairs building.
   The embassy on Thursday circulated to staff members and some
American business people a 15-point list of security tips. It
advised people to vary their activities and travel routes, avoid
wearing clothes and carrying bags which identify one as an
American, and stay away from restaurants and bars which are popular
hangouts for Americans.
   ``Don't be embarrassed or afraid to seek help if you note
unusual activity or believe you are being followed,'' it said.
   It urged people to be alert and ``don't daydream while traveling
to and from work.''
   The notice sent out to American residents said, ``The embassy
believes that this warning reflects a genuine threat and that
American citizens in the Beijing area should take appropriate steps
to protect themselves.''
   It recommended that people steer clear of popular gathering
points and asked that suspicious activity be reported to the
embassy immediately.
   The notice also went to Americans in the port city of Tianjin,
60 miles to the southeast.
   Embassy spokeswoman Sylvia Rifkin said the U.S. Mission in
Beijing sent out warnings before to Americans based on worldwide
alerts against terrorists, but this was the first time the warning
specifically concerned China.
   No past incidents have arisen of terrorist attacks in China
against Chinese or foreign residents. China also has good relations
with Mideast nations which have been accused of fostering terrorist
activities.
   China deals harshly with Chinese caught stealing or committing
other crimes against foreigners, and foreigners in Beijing and
other cities generally have little concern over their personal
safety.
   ``I'm bewildered like everyone else,'' said an American lawyer
when asked how she planned to respond to the terrorist threat.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
