<HEAD>Dukakis To Hold Meeting on Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Likely Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis is planning a meeting with Florida Attorney General
Bob Butterworth and about a half-dozen state and federal officials
next week in Boston to discuss ways to battle the nation's drug
problems.
   Dukakis, who already has won enough delegates to capture his
party's nomination during first-round convention balloting, is
calling on Butterworth for advice partly because of his early
campaign support and because Florida is the top port for the
nation's illegal drug imports.
   ``The only way we're going to resolve this drug problem is for
the federal government to work with the state government and local
officials. Having been a sheriff, I can say ... the federal
government has never been known for its efforts to work with local
officials,'' said Butterworth.
   Also planning to attend the policymaking sessions from Florida
are Rep. Larry Smith, D-Hollywood, and Janet Reno, chief prosecutor
in the state's drug-ridden Dade County. Reps. Charles Rangel,
D-N.Y.; Glenn English, D-Okla.; Thomas Foley, D-Wash.; and Sen.
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz. also are expected to attend.
