<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PublisherFired     06-10 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Publisher Fired,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious, Conservative Groups Back Fired Publisher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious and conservative groups organized
a rally today at the Dayton Daily News to protest the firing of its
publisher over his rejection of advertisements by two homosexual
groups.
   Dennis Shere, 47, was fired Wednesday by David Easterly,
president of Cox Newspapers, after Shere said his religious beliefs
did not allow him to compromise on the matter. Atlanta-based Cox
owns Dayton Newspapers Inc., publisher of the paper.
   ``I really think that it's a sad day,'' said the Rev. Paul
Dixon, president of Cedarville College, a nearby Baptist school
that helped organize the protest set for this afternoon.
   ``I don't think that this is as liberal a community as they
perceive,'' Dixon said. ``We have strong concerns for family, for
morality, for Biblical values, and I think they're going to begin
to see that.''
   The college staff was rounding up signatures for a full-page
advertisement backing Shere to be published in Sunday's Daily News,
he said.
   The new publisher, J. Bradford Tillson, said the newspaper on
Thursday accepted a classified advertisement from one of the
homosexual groups, The Dayton Lesbian and Gay Center. He said he
was unsure when the ad would appear.
   Leon Bey, program chairman for the center, said the ad reads:
``Summer '88 program guide for the Dayton Lesbian and Gay Center
available now. Write (box number).''
   ``It's not the same ad ... but it is an ad with the `g' and `l'
words,'' Bey said.
   Bey said he was mystified by Shere's position because the
newspaper had accepted a similar program guide ad in the fall of
1986. Shere had been publisher since 1984.
   Shere rejected ads for a health lecture series sponsored by The
Dayton Lesbian and Gay Center and for a gay-rights group, Serenity
Inc., said James McCarthy, Serenity's executive director.
   McCarthy, who led two days of recent picketing at the newspaper
protesting rejection of the ads, said he was shocked at the firing.
Serenity wanted to meet with the publisher to explain its position,
but Shere refused, McCarthy said.
   ``I would support any effort to get Mr. Shere's job back if once
he came back we would have access to the paper,'' McCarthy said.
   Shere said in a statement that he had tried ``to be obedient to
God, my Christian convictions and my belief that to publish these
ads is not in the bests interests of this newspaper or community.''
   He said homosexuality ``is responsible for helping to spread a
virus considered by many to be a virtual plague,'' an apparent
reference to AIDS. He called it ``tantamount to moral suicide.''
   Easterly said Shere was given several chances to resign but
refused. ``Personal feelings, religious or otherwise, cannot be
allowed to override our obligation to treat people fairly,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
