<DOCNO> AP880610-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC--Rabies-Australia     06-10 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC--Rabies-Australia,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australia Reports First Rabies Case; Came From India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia's first confirmed case of rabies in man
or animal most likely came into the country from Asia, according to
U.S. health officials.
   The death of a 10-year-old Australian boy was confirmed last
November as rabies, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control said
Thursday. It was the first laboratory-confirmed case of rabies ever
reported from Australia.
   The patient had been scratched by a neighbor's dog two months
before becoming sick, the Atlanta-based CDC said, but the animal
showed no signs of rabies when tested last December.
   However, the child had been bitten on the finger by a wild
monkey at a marketplace in India 16 months before becoming ill, the
CDC said.
   ``All available data indicate that this was an imported case,''
the CDC said, adding that the patient might also have received
other animal bites while traveling in Asia.
   Australia is considered rabies-free; animals there are not
vaccinated, and those that bite people are not quarantined. If the
fatal disease were to become endemic in Australia, the CDC said,
about 38,000 people a year there might have to undergo
post-exposure preventive treatment, and millions of dollars would
have to be spent on vaccine and quarantine programs.
   A limited survey of bats in Queensland, Australia, is now under
way to check for any signs of rabies.
</TEXT>
