<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Rambo,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stallone Denied Permission To Enter East Berlin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armies of communists couldn't stop Sylvester
Stallone's movie character Rambo from rampaging through Vietnam and
Afghanistan, but it took only a few border guards to keep Stallone
himself from entering East Berlin.
   ``I was just going there to look at a museum, and they look at
me like the enemy,'' Stallone's publicist, John Bloch, quoted him
as saying after the actor was refused entry Thursday.
   Communist border guards gave no explanation for refusing entry
to Stallone, said his spokeswoman, Ana Weinert.
   ``(President) Reagan called them the `evil empire' yet they let
him in. I told it the way it is in movies. So much for glasnost,''
Stallone was quoted as saying in reference to the Soviet policy of
openness.
   Stallone, in West Berlin to promote his new movie, ``Rambo
III,'' wanted to tour the Pergamon Musuem in East Berlin.
   The latest installment of Stallone's Rambo series pits his hero
against Soviet troops in Afghanistan.
   Earlier Thursday, the 43-year-old film star arrived at the
Berlin Wall Haus am Checkpoint Charlie museum just as West Berlin
resident Johannes Georg Ehret and his East German girlfriend were
demonstrating how he smuggled her out of East Berlin on May 27.
   Ehret, 35, said he had met Liane Suendermann, a 22-year-old East
Berlin nurse, through broadcasts on an illegal private radio
station.
   He explained how he drove regularly to East Berlin and
eventually hatched the plan to smuggle Ms. Suenderman out in his
car.
   After the re-enactment of the escape, Stallone paused to have
his picture taken with Ms. Suendermann and said: ``It just goes to
show how important human rights are, and what people will go
through to be free.''
</TEXT>
