<HEAD>Three-alarm Fire Forces Evacuation Of Dozens of Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 patients were hurriedly
evacuated from their rooms when a fire damaged a second-floor room
and spread smoke into two floors of the 12-story Santa Rosa
Hospital, authorities said.
   No injuries were reported, and officials said the patients would
be returned to their rooms after the smoke cleared.
   It took more than 80 firefighters about 20 to 25 minutes to
bring the fire at the downtown hospital under control Thursday
night, but smoke and water damage appeared extensive, officials
said.
   ``I didn't panic till I smelled smoke,'' said one patient,
Carmen Velasco. ``Then I started to run. I had to carry my own IV
unit. One of the firemen stepped on it.''
   The cause of the blaze was not immediately determined and arson
investigators were called to the scene early today. Santa Rosa
Health Care Corp. Chief Executive Officer Michael White said no
damage estimate was available.
