<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Soviets     06-10 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Soviets,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Emissary Who Once Was Expelled From Egypt Back In Cairo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Soviet diplomat once expelled from
Egypt by presidential order arrived in Cairo today as a special
envoy from Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The three-day visit by Vladimir Polyakov, director of the
Foreign Ministry's Near East and North Africa Department, reflected
greatly improved Cairo-Moscow relations since President Hosni
Mubarak took office in 1981.
   Polyakov told reporters on arrival that he had been assigned by
Gorbachev ``to convey to President Mubarak details of the results
of the recent American-Soviet summit.''
   Gorbachev and President Reagan met in Moscow May 29-June 2.
   ``Good relations now exist between Egypt and the Soviet Union,''
Polyakov said, speaking in Russian through an Arabic interpreter.
He added that last month's visit to Moscow by Egyptian Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid, the first of its kind in 14 years,
further improved bilateral ties.
   During his visit, Polyakov is to meet with Mubarak and State
Minister for Foreign Affairs Butros Ghali.
   Polyakov was ambassador in Cairo in 1981 when then-President
Anwar Sadat launched a massive crackdown on domestic opponents. It
included the expulsion of Polyakov and six other Soviet dipolomats
whom Sadat accused of meddling in internal affairs and fomenting
Moslem-Christian sectarian friction..
   The bilateral crisis continued until Sadat was assassinated by
Moslem extremists at a Cairo military parade in October 1981.
   Relations improved under Mubarak and diplomatic representation
was restored to the ambassadorial level in 1984.
</TEXT>
