<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KidneyOdyssey     06-10 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidney Odyssey,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidney Donor Finishes 800-Mile Walk</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brian Sullivan finished his 42-day, 800-mile
hike from Chicago to Philadelphia in a steady rain. He did it on
two pairs of running shoes, almost 30 spaghetti dinners and one
kidney.
   His brother Kevin has the other one.
   The two wet men, followed by relatives and well-wishers, walked
with their arms around each other Thursday to the Philadelphia
hospital where nearly four years ago Brian donated the kidney that
saved his brother's life.
   Brian, a 31-year-old recreation supervisor from Carol Stream,
Ill., walked most of the distance by himself to emphasize the need
for organ donation and demonstrate that he has suffered no ill
effects from donating one of his kidneys.
    ``You don't have to do something this stupid or crazy
obviously, but it's nice to know if you wanted to you could,'' he
said.
   His brother Kevin, 36, developed kidney failure in 1984 and
needed a transplant. Two brothers and a sister were eligible
donors, but after a family discussion it was decided that Brian was
in the best shape to give a kidney.
   The experience taught him that organs of all types are in scarce
supply, whether they come from living or dead donors.
   He decided on the walk as a way to bring attention to the
importance of organ donation and set a goal of signing up 100,000
people to organ donor cards. Brian said he has personally signed as
a witness on 561 donor cards during the walk.
   He and officials with organ donor networks estimate he spoke to
more than 10,000 people during the trip, and that many more were
reached through the publicity surrounding the walk.
   Brian, who began the trip on April 24 in Chicago, averaged about
20 miles a day, walking from Chicago, through Indiana to Cleveland,
through the mountains of Pennsylvania to Philadelphia.
   On Thursday he wended his way through downtown Philadelphia to
Thomas Jefferson University Hospital, where the transplant was
performed. A crowd of about 30 hospital staff members and
transplant recipients waited to welcome him.
   ``It's really unbelievable. I find it hard to believe. God, did
six weeks go by?'' he said.
   Brian insisted that the trip proved there are no physical
limitations for donors. He did drop 12 pounds from of his
5-foot-11-inch frame, though he remains solid at 198 pounds, due in
large part to a steady diet of high-carbohydrate, high-calorie food
along the way.
   ``I must have had 28 spaghetti dinners,'' Brian said of the meal
he grew most tired of eating. ``That and oatmeal in the morning.''
   ``Yeah, and what did you have the first night you got to our
house?,'' his brother Kevin asked, grinning. ``Spaghetti.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0073 </DOCNO>
