<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Douglas     06-10 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Douglas,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Movie Star Michael Douglas Testifies at Murder Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie star Michael Douglas, who gained
early fame as a police officer in the Streets of San Francisco
television series, got a taste of real-life court action on
Thursday.
   Douglas was called as a character witness at the murder trial of
David P. Thompson, a beer importer accused of killing his landlord
with a .357 caliber Magnum.
   Douglas, who received an Oscar for his portrayal of a greedy
tycoon in the movie ``Wall Street,'' testified he met Thompson six
times in 1986 when he was considering investing in Thompson's firm.
He said he never saw Thompson show signs of a hot temper.
   The star later spent about a half hour watching the trial. He
told reporters it was the first time he'd ever appeared as a court
witness.
   ``He (Thompson) had the best qualities of a professional,''
Douglas said during his time on the stand. ``Good business acumen
and good marketing skills.''
   Thompson, 38, is charged with the murder of Raymond McCoy, 40.
   Defense attorney Douglas Schmidt contends McCoy had previously
threatened Thompson. He said Thompson secured a court order the day
before the shooting to force McCoy to stay away.
   When McCoy came to Thompson's office, Schmidt said, Thompson
thought he was armed and fired his handgun, hitting the victim in
the chest and killing him.
   Prosecutor Robert Gordon told jurors the shooting was not in
self-defense because McCoy was unarmed when he came to collect the
rent.
</TEXT>
