<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Fiji-Weapons     06-10 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji-Weapons,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Reports that Fiji Weapons Came From India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper today said India's
intelligence service tried to overthrow Fiji's Melanesian-dominated
government by smuggling tons of weapons to its Indian community.
   The report in the Australian drew a quick denial from Australian
Prime Minister Bob Hawke, who said he would have known of such
shipments. The Indian embassy in Canberra also issued a vigorous
denial.
   The Australian, the country's only national broadsheet, said in
its leading story that Western intelligence services blamed the
Indian government for recent arms shipments to the volatile South
Pacific nation of Fiji, a former British colony 1,860 miles
northeast of Sydney.
   It said the Soviet-made arms, which included rockets launchers,
anti-tank mines, automatic rifles and grenades, were part of a plan
to overthrow the nominally civilian, Melanesian-dominated
government, which came to power after two coups last year.
   The newspaper quoted Australian intelligence sources and a U.S.
government official in Washington. It did not identify them.
   Fiji's security forces this week seized two large caches of arms
from two Indian-owned sugar cane farms. Authorities followed with a
roundup of Indian businessmen.
   On Thursday, police detained two former Cabinet ministers in the
ousted Indian-dominated government of Timoci Bavadra.
   Bavadra's government was overthrown by Lt. Col. Sitiveni Rabuka
one month after it was elected. Rabuka said he mounted the May 14,
1987, coup to protect political rights of ethnic Fijians, who are
outnumbered by Indians in the 715,000 population. Rabuka carried
out a second coup four months later, citing the same reason.
   Rabuka has since handed power to the nominally civilian
government and appointed himself head of the army and home affairs
minister in charge of internal security.
   He has said the arms shipments were part of a foreign plot to
destabilize the nation but he did not specifically accuse any
particular group.
</TEXT>
