<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Army-Gays     06-10 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Army-Gays,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Agrees to Reconsider Landmark Gay-Rights Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court decision to
reconsider a landmark ruling striking down the Army's ban on
homosexual soldiers was a setback but not a reason to despair, says
a homosexual-rights group's lawyer.
   ``The struggle for equal rights for lesbians and gay men is a
long-term struggle,'' Leonard Graff, legal director of National Gay
Rights Advocates, said following Thursday's decision.
``Realistically we have to expect some setbacks. That doesn't mean
we give up,''
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed to reconsider a
Feb. 10 ruling in the case of a discharged soldier from the Seattle
area.
   A panel of the court ruled 2-1 at the time that 1981 Army
regulations providing for discharge on the grounds of homosexual
orientation were unconstitutional.
   The panel had said homosexuals, as victims of historic
mistreatment, deserved the same protections from discrimination as
racial minorities. It was the first time an appellate court reached
that conclusion.
   The latest ruling, which granted a Reagan administration request
that the case be referred to an 11-member panel for a new hearing,
cancelled the earlier order's legal effect.
   The 25-judge appeals court gave no reason for its decision or
details of its vote. No date has been set for the new hearing.
   The government had contended the ruling failed to defer to the
Army's judgment in matters of discipline and morale and also was
inconsistent with the Supreme Court's 1986 ruling upholding an
anti-sodomy law in Georgia.
   A lawyer for Perry Watkins, the former solider, said he was not
surprised by the decision and expected the case to end up in the
Supreme Court if he wins the next round.
   ``That's why I did not advise homosexual members of the Army
(after the February decision) to come out of the closet and say,
`Here I am, you can't touch me,' '' said attorney James Lobsenz.
   Watkins, now 39, enlisted in the Army in 1967 at age 19,
admitting at the time that he had homosexual tendencies. The man,
who had been supervisor of the Fort Lewis personnel administration
center and had high job ratings, was discharged in May 1984.
   Before 1981, the Army discharged soldiers for sodomy and other
specific acts, but not for homosexuality itself. But that year,
homosexual orientation was declared to be grounds for discharge.
   Nearly 1,400 people were discharged from all branches of the
armed services for homosexuality in the fiscal year that ended last
Sept. 30, the government said.
   In the Feb. 10 ruling, the three-judge panel said the Army must
reconsider Watkins' application for re-enlistment without regard to
his sexual orientation.
   Writing for the majority, Judge William Norris likened laws
limiting the ``acceptable focus'' of sexual desire to members of
the opposite sex to laws limiting the choice of a spouse or sex
partner to members of the same race. Such laws, he said, are
unconstitutional discrimination in the absence of ``compelling
governmental justification.''
   Norris rejected Army arguments that the ban was justified by
widely shared moral standards and by military morale and
discipline. The claim that homosexuals would hurt morale and
discipline was an attempt to ``illegitimately cater to private
biases,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
