<HEAD>Evangelist To Crusade in Indianapolis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defrocked evangelist Jimmy Swaggart plans to
preach in Indianapolis next month, delivering his first sermon
outside his home base of Louisiana since being dismissed from the
Assemblies of God.
   An Indiana Assemblies of God official said Thursday the local
denomination will not take part in Swaggart's free crusade in
Market Square Arena July 22, 23 and 24.
   The evangelist's visit was scheduled before he was defrocked,
said Fred Leader, secretary-treasurer of the denomination's Indiana
district.
   ``At that time, we were going to cooperate with him,'' he said.
   The Executive Presbytery dismissed Swaggart from the pulpit
April 8 for refusing to accept a year's punishment for an
unspecified sin.
   A New Orleans prostitute, Debra Murphree, 28, has claimed the
preacher paid her to pose nude in a motel room. She later claimed
to have had sex with Swaggart on at least one occasion.
   ``We like Indianapolis. We have a lot of people up there that
love Jimmy Swaggart, and so we're coming back up there,'' said the
Rev. John A. Jendresen, arrangements director of Swaggart's crusade.
   Swaggart returned to preaching May 22, but has not preached
outside Louisiana, where his headquarters is based.
   The Assemblies of God, the nation's largest Pentecostal
denomination, announced Tuesday that ministers associated with
Swaggart as of Oct. 1 will lose their own credentials. Assemblies
spokeswoman Juleen Turnage estimated 80 or 90 ministers would be
affected.
   Swaggart also is scheduled to preach at Oakland, Calif., and
Houston in September, the Rev. Jendresen said.
