<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Students     06-10 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Students,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Charged In Student Slaying That Touched Off Pro-Democracy
Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities filed charges today against five
young men and a woman in the slaying of a university student whose
death prompted his classmates to agitate first for tighter security
and then for democracy.
   Two of the suspects, unemployed young men with criminal records,
were charged with murder and hooliganism, according to the official
Legal Daily. If convicted, they could receive the death penalty _ a
bullet in the back of the head.
   The four others were charged with hooliganism and face terms of
up to seven years in prison. Three of them were unemployed and two,
including a 22-year-old woman, previously served terms in labor
camps for theft, the Beijing Daily said.
   The six allegedly picked a fight with two Beijing University
students at a snackshop and liquor store late on June 1. Geophysics
graduate student Cai Qingfeng, 22, went to the students' aid but
was shot in the head with a B-B gun pellet and beaten with a shovel.
   Cai died of his wounds June 2 in a hospital. Late that night,
about 1,000 students marched from Beijing University to central
Beijing's Tiananmen Square to demonstrate their sorrow and anger
and demand better security for students.
   The high emotions quickly switched channel, however, and in the
next few days students put up dozens of posters attacking
government corruption and demanding democracy and greater press
freedom.
   The unrest peaked Wednesday when police sealed off Tiananmen
Square and intimidated the students into canceling plans for a
pro-democracy march.
   The mood on Beijing University campus was subdued today with
fewer and fewer students crowding around the weather-tattered
posters that advocated protest.
   About 850 students gathered late Thursday night near the
bulletin boards for an impromptu rally, but only half a dozen
students stepped forward to speak and their message was restrained.
   ``We students talk about democracy but we don't understand it
ourselves, so how can we preach it to society?'' one asked,
eliciting applause.
   Another said, ``We students and the government leaders are not
at odds. Our goals are the same. We are all Chinese.''
   No one suggested further protest, and the rally broke up shortly
after midnight. By contrast, hundreds of students rallied until 1
and 2 a.m. each night earlier in the week, cheering speakers who
suggested that they boycott classes, hold protest marches and take
over the campus radio station. None of the suggestions were acted
on.
   By sealing off Tiananmen Square on Wednesday, the government
made it clear it would not tolerate a repeat of the massive student
pro-democracy protests that took place in the winter of 1986-87.
Those protests ended with a conservative crackdown, including the
ouster of relatively liberal Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
