<DOCNO> AP880610-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz-NATO     06-10 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-NATO,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Winds Up Its Spring Meeting, Calls For Negotiations For
Disarmament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO foreign ministers today called for
early negotiations to reduce troops in Europe and promised to
consider a more equitable sharing of defense costs between the
United States and its allies.
   In a joint declaration, the 16 foreign ministers said successful
negotiations with the Soviet bloc depended on ``substantial and
balanced'' results on human rights.
   The statement, issued at the end of NATO's spring meeting,
attempted to prod the Soviets to improve their human rights record
before the North Atlantic Treaty organization would undertake
negotiations with the Warsaw Pact.
   The goal, the statment said, was a substantial and balanced
reduction of non-nuclear forces in Europe.
   Negotiations dealing only with troop reductions in Central
Europe have limped along for 15 years without any results. The new
negotiations between NATO and the seven-nation Communist bloc are
more ambitious, seeking to reduce tensions from the Atlantic to the
Ural Mountains.
   There was no specific promise in the declaration that the
Western Europeans and Canada will contribute a larger share to
NATO's defenses. The United States currently shoulders about 70
percent of the financial burden.
   But the statement cited a ``ontinuing commitment to share
equitably the risks, burdens and responsibilities as well as the
benefits of our common endeavor.''
   A hard decision on defense costs was not expected until the
winter NATO meeting in December.
   On another point, the declaration said the ministers had
discussed the ripening situation in Eastern Europe in light of the
economic and political reforms under way in the Soviet Union.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz and other U.S. officials
have stressed that the West should provide economic assistance to
Eastern European nations only if there is political reform.
   The ministers also welcomed the results of the recent May 29
-June 2 summit in Moscow between President Reagan and General
Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev, ``both for their substance and as a
portent for the future development of East-West relations.''
   ``We welcome the unprecedented prominence accorded to human
rights in the joint statement of the summit and hope that a more
forthcoming Soviet attitude will also be reflected'' in the
concluding document of the current session of the Conference on
Security and Cooperation in Europe in Vienna.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
