<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HostageAnniversary     06-10 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage Anniversary,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage's Anniversary Noted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family and friends of kidnapped
Professor Thomas Sutherland marked the start of his fourth year in
captivity by adorning trees on campus with new yellow ribbons.
   Sutherland's daughters, Kit and Joan, were on hand Thursday to
repeat the now-familiar ritual.
   ``Every year we have to do it,'' said Kit Sutherland, 27. ``It's
very symbolic that we have to retie and make the knot maybe that
much stronger or use better ribbon simply so that it will stand up.
   ``It's symbolic of what Dad has to do every single day,'' she
said. ``He has to regroup, and retie and restrengthen his ways.''
   Sutherland, 57, was kidnapped June 9, 1985, as he was returning
to Beirut, Lebanon, where he was acting dean of agriculture at
American University while on leave from Colorado State University.
   The ceremony Thursday night in the CSU Student Center was a
simple one of poetry and music. The centerpiece was a 1966 tape
recording of Sutherland reciting poems of Robert Burns, who like
Sutherland is a native of Scotland.
   Coincidentally, friends of the Rev. Lawrence Martin Jenco had
sent Jenco the tape 20 years before Jenco and Sutherland met as
fellow hostages. Jenco rediscovered the tape after his release in
July 1986.
   ``For us, it was a tremendous joy to listen to him,'' Jenco
said. ``And frequently, when things got sad or depressing, we would
say, `Tom, is there any possibility of you reciting a poem for us?'
   ``And frequently he would do this and would uplift our spirits.''
   Only one American has been held hostage in Lebanon longer than
Sutherland: Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, who was abducted March 16, 1985.
   Since Sutherland's abduction, his wife, Jean, has returned to
Beirut to continue teaching at American University.
   ``I know a lot of people who have lost their dads,'' Kit
Sutherland said. ``They will never again be able to tell them that
they love them. We're lucky. He's still alive and we'll see him
soon.''
</TEXT>
