<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MassGrave 1stLd-Writethru a0486 06-10 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mass Grave, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Begin Digging Up Mass Grave with Possible Death Squad
Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with 12 bodies found. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers used shovels and their bare
hands today to dig up 12 bodies from a mass grave where human
rights advocates say victims of right-wing death squads may have
been buried.
   The church-backed Ecumenical Movement for Justice and Peace said
the three-square-yard shallow pit held at least 22 bodies, which
were mysteriously buried in April at the suburban South Cemetery.
   Movement officials obtained a court order authorizing exhumation
of the bodies to determine whether they were members of the
left-wing Youth for Democracy and Nationalism, reported missing
since April.
   Lawyer Romeo Capulong, the movement's chairman, called the court
order a breakthrough in efforts to locate victims of death squads.
   ``The relatives of victims of disappearances were never able to
find a mass grave like this,'' Capulong said.
   Health department workers began the dig after spraying the area
with disinfectant. The workers found the first body about three
feet below the surface of the muddy pit. By late afternoon, the
diggers had found at least 12 decomposing bodies, including that of
a woman.
   ``We believe the presence of mass graves is an indication of
death squads all around us,'' said Sister Pat Lardizabal, a Roman
Catholic nun.
   However, Dr. Ethelyn Nieto, Manila city health officer, claimed
at least some of the bodies had been properly buried after
autopsies. Nieto said the bodies had remained unclaimed for months
before they were buried.
   Volunteer Dr. Aurora Parong said at least one of the bodies
showed that it had not undergone an autopsy.
   ``The fact that he was not autopsied shows us that he could have
been illegally buried,'' she claimed.
   She said the digging would continue until all 22 bodies believed
buried there were recovered.
   Amor Cabusao, 55, was looking for her missing son, Ernesto. A
laborer, he disappeared July 17 during a police sweep of Manila's
slum district of Tondo, which military authorities claim to have
been a refuge for communist hit squads in the capital.
   At least 100 soldiers, policemen and village officials were
killed by communist guerrillas in the capital last year.
   Civil rights groups have frequently charged their members have
been victims of right-wing death squads seeking to eliminate
leftists and sympathizers to the 19-year Communist insurgency.
</TEXT>
