<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Reaction     06-10 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Reaction,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many South Koreans Angered at Radical Students Marching to North
Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM_Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many South Koreans reacted with
disappointment and anger today to moves by radical students to
march to communist North Korea for unification talks.
   ``What a stupid idea it is. They are simply crazy,'' said the
owner of a small bakery near Yonsei University in Seoul, where
thousands of students battled riot police.
   ``I supported them when they fought for democracy last year. But
this time, I simply don't understand them,'' said the shopkeeper,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Coughing and sneezing in a small bakery filled with drifting
tear gas, the shopkeeper said he could not understand the students
shouting the same slogans that North Korea puts out daily through
its propaganda outlets.
   Few people interviewed supported or showed sympathy with the
students who called for talks with their North Korean counterparts
on reuniting their land left divided since the end of World War II
in 1945.
   Chung Soon-im, a 38-year-old housewife, said sarcastically,
``Let them go to the north and live there for a few months. They
need to learn by experience what is good and bad.''
   A uniformed army captain interviewed in a subway said: ``I would
like to shoot them. They are too naive or idiots.''
   President Roh Tae-woo, who took office Feb. 25 after victory in
last December's elections, has liberalized debate on unification
but said the government should serve as a unified channel of
dialogue with North Korea.
   ``I do agree that the students have the right to meet their
North Korean friends. It would help ease the bitter rivalry between
the two sides,'' dissident Buddhist monk Song Kwan said after a
rally at Yonsei University.
   Another dissident leader, Moon Ik-hwan, told students at the
rally, ``The Roh Tae-woo regime has neither capability nor will to
push national unification. I support the student talks.''
   About 4,000 students, shooting clenched fists into the air, rose
in wild cheers and sang a song titled ``Our Lifelong Wish is
Unification.''
   But many intellectuals say the student activism could backfire.
They point out that the military staged a coup in 1961 after
radical students called for similar unification talks with North
Korea.

</TEXT>
