<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardCommencement     06-10 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Commencement,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arias Urges Harvard Graduates To Help Ease Suffering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President and Nobel
Prize-winner Oscar Arias pledged to continue pressing for peace in
Central America, and asked Harvard University graduates to join him
in taking risks ``to build a different world.''
   At an overcast, rainy 337th commencement ceremony Thursday,
Arias told 25,000 Harvard graduates, alumni and spectators that he
maintained a dream of peace and democracy in strife-torn Central
America.
   Arias, 48, received the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for a plan to end
conflict in the region.
   ``When we proposed the peace plan for Central America, many
people thought we were wrong and that that was an impossible
dream,'' Arias said. ``Out of that risk, we now have a chance for
peace, and guns have been silenced in Nicaragua for the first time
in 20 years.
   ``Don't ever fear the risks you will have to take to build a
different world. Don't ever fear the risks when you are acting on
your own principles. You will soon learn that the accommodation
with the old world, a world where you see violence and injustice,
poverty and submission, offers no reward.''
   Before Arias spoke, Harvard President Derek Bok assailed the
``hypocrisy of encouraging students to address the gravest problems
of society while perpetuating conditions that make it very
difficult for them to do so.''
   Bok cited statistics showing fewer Harvard graduates entering
government, teaching, manufacturing or social work, and he pinned
blame on the failure of salaries in those fields to approach ones
in private, professional jobs.
   Bok conferred degrees to the 5,526 graduates en masse, school by
school.
   Business school graduates were booed roundly when they stood to
receive their degrees waving $100 bills.
   In presenting an honorary doctor of laws degree, Bok praised
Arias for his ``clear voice of peace and reason for our new world.''
   Other honorary degree recipients were: economist John Kenneth
Galbraith, Christian Science Monitor Editor Kay Fanning, operatic
soprano Jessye Norman, mathematician David Harold Blackwell, Roman
historian Sir Ronald Syme, astronomer Vera Cooper Rubin and
epidemiologist Sir Richard Doll.
</TEXT>
