<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-ForeignAid 1stLd-Writethru a0530 06-10 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Foreign Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Says It Will Expand Aid If It Is Not Enough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD comments on Middle East, CORRECT overall
aid figure to $7 billion, no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan, already the world's largest donor of
overseas economic aid, will expand its aid program to developing
countries if the current level is not enough, Foreign Minister
Sosuke Uno said today.
   Uno also said Japan would continue to concentrate on boosting
demand in the domestic economy to relieve its trade surplus with
other countries.
   ``Our $7 billion in ODA (official development assistance) is the
greatest in the world, although in terms of percentage of the gross
national product, it may not be,'' Uno said in a luncheon speech at
the Japan National Press Club. ``If our efforts toward ODA are not
enough, we will work harder.''
   He did not say how the government would determine if Japan's
efforts were sufficient.
   Boosted by the surging value of the yen, Japan's assistance has
risen from $3.8 billion in 1985 to about $7.4 billion in fiscal
1987, which ended March 31. The budget for the current fiscal year
is $10 billion.
   Japanese development aid this year is about 0.3 percent of
Japan's gross national product, below the average 0.36 percent for
major Western donor countries.
   Uno said such aid to developing countries was for humanitarian
and global security purposes.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci urged the Japanese
government during a visit to Tokyo this week to increase its aid to
strategically important Third World countries such as Pakistan,
Portugal, Turkey and Afghanistan.
   Carlucci also called on Japan to bolster its own military and
increase financial support of U.S. troops stationed in this country.
   ``Just don't ask us to send our Self-Defense Forces abroad,''
Uno said today. ``Don't ask us to take any guns overseas.''
   Western allies have urged Japan to take a more active role in
global security. The government says the constitution, which
renounces war, limits Japanese contributions to non-military
actions.
   Uno said his forthcoming trip to Israel as the first Japanese
cabinet official to visit that country represents absolutely no
change in Japanese policy toward the Middle East.
   ``It is not at all a case of emphasizing Israel and neglecting
the Arab countries, or emphasizing Arab countries and neglecting
Israel,'' he said. ``There is absolutely no change in our Mideast
policy.''
   Japan imports 99 percent of its oil and is heavily dependent on
Middle East petroleum. Tokyo tries to maintain cordial relations
with most Arab countries as well as with Israel.
</TEXT>
