<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Europeans 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Europeans, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0490,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Europeans Accused of Training Communist Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf, `Col. Hernani...' to CORRECT Hermansson's age.
INSERTS 1 graf after 7th pvs, `Spokesmen for...' to UPDATE with
Young Communist League saying he is member. Pick up 8th pvs, `The
arrests...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Europeans and a Filipino of
German descent were arrested in a rebel-infested area and accused
of training communist insurgents, a senior military officer said
today.
   Col. Hernani Figueroa, spokesman for the army's southern Luzon
island command, identified the three as Antonio Bosch, 46, a
Filipino of German descent; Klaus Schmidt, 52, a West German
Protestant minister; and Stellan Hermansson, 30, a Swede.
   Figueroa said the three were arrested Wednesday during a
military operation in Quezon province. He said they had been
training communist rebels in the Bondoc peninsula of Quezon
province, a rebel stronghold.
   He said two soldiers identified them as being with a band of New
People's Army guerrillas who raided the town of San Francisco last
February. The soldiers were captured in the raid but escaped by
killing their guards a few days later.
   Figueroa said the three were undergoing interrogation and were
being held in a room at the command headquarters in Lucena City, 60
miles southeast of Manila.
   He said the military planned to charge them with either
espionage or murder and robbery in the San Francisco raid. He said
the trio was found with a camera containing film of rebels training
and Hermansson was depicted holding a .30-caliber machine gun.
   Spokesmen for the West German and Swedish embassies said they
were unaware of the reports. A spokesman for St. Andrew's
Theological Seminary in Manila said Schmidt had been teaching
biblical studies there for the past year and was expected to return
for classes next week.
   In Sweden, officials of the Young Communist League said
Hermansson was a member of the organization. Spokesman Erik
Cardfelt said Hermansson arrived here May 18 to travel and gather
information for lectures. He said Hermansson was a freelance
journalist and was to have returned to Sweden Saturday.
   The arrests followed charges by the military that Western groups
are supporting the New People's Army, which has been waging a
19-year insurgency to establish a Communist state.
   Last month, a captured rebel claimed journalists from New
Zealand paid her guerrilla unit to stage an ambush in February in
southeastern Luzon in which 11 soldiers were killed.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos told foreign reporters Thursday
that there was no corroborating evidence to support that charge.
</TEXT>
