<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-10 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Ices North, Midwest; Thunderstorms Plague South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-pressure system caused the mercury to plunge in parts of
the Northeast and upper Midwest today, while fierce winds ripped
off roofs, downed power lines and toppled a 75-foot-tall pine tree
in the South.
   Frost and freeze warnings were posted this morning from southern
New York into Pennsylvania's northern mountains. Frost and freeze
advisories covered parts of central and northeast Wisconsin and
northern Michigan.
   Meanwhile, thunderstorms drenched parts of the Southeast. The
storms extended from eastern North Carolina through much of South
Carolina into the central Gulf Coast region.
   In Georgia, strong winds ripped a roof off a house and a barn
Thursday night in Bullard, while trees and power lines were downed
in parts of Macon, Irwinton and Toomesboro. The winds toppled a
75-foot pine tree as the storms moved through an area near
Charlotte, N.C.
   The storm system brought rain to some drought-stricken areas,
along with crop-damaging hail. ``It was not a lot of rain, but
every little bit helps,'' said Joe M. Peliffier, a meteorologist
with the National Weather Service at North Carolina's
Raleigh-Durham International Airport.
   New Orleans was inundated by 3\ inches of rain within an hour
early this morning.
   Thunderstorms also moved across parts of eastern Colorado and
extreme northwest Kansas into north-central New Mexico late
Thursday and early today.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms along the
coast of the Carolinas, Georgia and across Florida; showers in the
Pacific Northwest into northwest Montana; and sunny skies over much
of the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 60s and 70s from
New England across the Carolinas, from the inland portion of the
central Gulf of Mexico states across the Great Lakes, from Arkansas
across Missouri, and along the Pacific Coast; 100 to 110 from
southwest Texas across the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s
in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 32 at
Bradford, Pa., to 88 at Del Rio, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 61 cloudy; Boston 50 fair; Buffalo 43 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 68 cloudy; Cincinnati 46 fair; Cleveland 51 fair;
Detroit 47 fair; Miami 78 fair; New York 56 fair; Philadelphia 51
fair; Pittsburgh 47 fair; Portland, Maine, 50 cloudy; Washington 54
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 67 fair; Chicago 53 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
74 fair; Denver 61 cloudy; Des Moines 55 fair; Indianapolis 50
fair; Kansas City 56 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 58 fair; Nashville
54 fair; New Orleans 70 thunderstorms; St. Louis 58 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 74 windy; Anchorage 59 cloudy; Las Vegas 76
fair; Los Angeles 60 fair; Phoenix 85 fair; Salt Lake City 63 fair;
San Diego 60 fair; San Francisco 57 cloudy; Seattle 52 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 48 showery; Toronto 45 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
