<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShootingsRally     06-10 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shootings Rally,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Night of Unrest In Wake Of Shootings By Off-Duty Cop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH AMBOY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters angry at the slaying of a
man shot by an off-duty police detective roamed downtown following
the man's funeral, throwing rocks and bottles at officers and
looting stores, authorities said.
   Sixteen people were arrested and several police received minor
injuries in the confrontation late Thursday, the second straight
night the town's Hispanic community had turned out to denounce
Monday's shootings of Carmen Castro Coria, 25, and his 27-year-old
brother, Matteo.
   Carmen Coria died instantly from a bullet wound to the head, and
his brother, shot four times, was in critical condition at Robert
Wood Johnson University Hospital in New Brunswick.
   Sgt. Allen Fuller, an off-duty detective, and the victims had
been drinking at the same bar when Fuller tried to break up a fight
outside, said Middlesex County Prosecutor Alan Rockoff. Carmen
Coria apparently threatened the officer with a beer bottle, he said.
   Fuller has been suspended with pay while Rockoff's office
investigates the incident. Protesters claim the shooting is only
the latest example of police brutality and harassment, and they
want a special prosecutor to handle the investigation.
   About 1,000 people attended a funeral Mass for Coria on Thursday
evening. As the crowd began to disperse afterward, smaller groups
on foot or in cars roamed through downtown, overturning a car,
breaking store windows and looting, said police Capt. James Volosin.
   Many followed the hearse back to the funeral home, near police
headquarters. Some threw rocks and bottles at the 25 officers in
riot gear standing by, Volosin said. One unidentified officer was
admitted for observation at Raritan Bay Medical Center after being
hit with a bottle, and several others suffered minor injuries, he
said.
   Most of those arrested were charged with criminal mischief, with
the remainder facing charges of assault on a police officer, said
Volosin. All were held overnight in the city jail.
   Police reported the streets were quiet by 1 a.m. today.
   Earlier Thursday, civil leaders met with Mayor George J.
Otlowski to demand that a forum be held so members of the Hispanic
community can air grievances.
   Otlowski said a community relations team was being formed.
   On Wednesday, about 500 people held a rally in a park across
from City Hall after a city council meeting. Windows were broken at
City Hall and some downtown businesses, police said.
</TEXT>
