<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-Hepatitis-Pregnancy     06-10 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-Hepatitis-Pregnancy,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Recommends Hepatitis B Tests For All Pregnant Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials, saying testing only
high-risk women has not worked, are now recommending hepatitis
testing for all pregnant women and immediate vaccinations, if
necessary, for their babies.
   The new recommendation, announced Thursday by the national
Centers for Disease Control, is aimed at preventing some 3,500
American babies each year from becoming carriers of type-B
hepatitis.
   Each year in the United States, about 16,500 babies are born to
mothers with hepatitis B infections, the CDC said. About 3,500 of
those infants become chronic hepatitis B carriers, and it is
estimated that more than 25 percent of them will die of liver
cancer or cirrhosis.
   In 1984 the CDC recommended hepatitis B tests for women in
high-risk groups, such as intravenous drug users and some venereal
disease patients. But the agency said Thursday that many
obstetricians don't know what the high-risk groups are, and the
plan has not worked.
   ``It is now evident that routine screening of all pregnant women
is the only strategy that will provide acceptable control'' of
mother-to-child hepatitis B transmission, the Atlanta-based CDC
said.
   The CDC's Immunization Practices Advisory Committee said
pregnant women should be tested for hepatitis B during an early
prenatal visit. If a woman is infected, her baby should receive
hepatitis B immune globulin, preferably within 12 hours of birth,
to provide immediate protection, and hepatitis B vaccine within
seven days and again at 1 month and 6 months.
   Such a routine is between 85 percent and 95 percent effective in
preventing a child from becoming a chronic hepatitis B carrier, CDC
researchers said.
   ``Hepatitis B vaccine is the first human vaccine that can
prevent both serious chronic disease and a uniformly fatal type of
cancer,'' the CDC noted.
   Still, vaccinating every newborn child in the United States for
hepatitis B is not currently practical from a cost standpoint, said
Dr. Mark Kane, a CDC hepatitis specialist. A child's vaccine
regimen costs $60 or more, he said.
   In addition to intravenous drug users and people who have had
multiple venereal disease infections, other high-risk categories
are homosexually active men and medical personnel exposed to blood
on the job, the CDC said.
   Kane said studies have shown that the CDC's previous
recommendations were inadequate.
   In one study, for example, 40 percent of obstetricians couldn't
name more than two high-risk groups for hepatitis B and 72 percent
didn't know the recommended treatment for infants born to infected
mothers, the CDC said.
   In addition, studies in several inner-city hospitals that test
all pregnant women found that only 35 percent to 65 percent of
those infected would fall under the old guidelines.
   Hepatitis B is one of the two most common forms of hepatitis, a
serious inflammation of the liver. Hepatitis B is transmitted
chiefly in the blood. There is not yet a vaccine for hepatitis A,
which is most commonly associated with poor hygiene.
   About 25,000 cases of each type occur in the United States each
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
