<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-BBC,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministry To Study Possible Expulsion Of BBC</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The home affairs minister has
asked his staff to prepare a report on whether the British
Broadcasting Co. should be expelled from South Africa, the ministry
said today.
   On Thursday, Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok suggested that
the BBC might be ordered out because of a film it broadcast in
Britain this week about detained black children in South Africa.
   ``Naturally, the BBC regrets any action which would further
impede its coverage from South Africa,'' BBC spokesman John
Moulding said in London today. Asked whether the BBC was justified
is televising the film, he said: ``We're satisfied with the
journalistic integrity of the film.''
   In Johannesburg, Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha, who is in
charge of foreign press credentials, instructed his staff to ``look
into the presence of the BBC in South Africa and report to him,''
the ministry said.
   It said Botha might issue a statement on the matter next week.
   The South African government had appealed to the BBC for a
chance to view the film, ``Suffer the Children,'' before it was
broadcast Wednesday night. The BBC refused.
   The BBC said it had commissioned the report from an independent
London-based company, Penumbra, which filmed inside South Africa
without government permission and without seeking police comment
because of emergency restrictions on the news media.
   Vlok said Thursday that a BBC spokesman had phoned his office
Wednesday, asking for comment on allegations in the film about
torture of children during police interrogation. Vlok said that
when his press spokesman, Leon Mellet, asked the BBC why the
comment had not been sought earlier, the interviewer had said,
``Quite frankly, the BBC does not believe the South African
government.''
   Vlok said, ``If this is the BBC's attitude, then why should the
South African government continue to host their representatives in
our country?''
</TEXT>
