<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Piedmont-Baby     06-10 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Piedmont-Baby,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Traffic Controllers Reroute Planes to Help Woman in Labor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who went into labor on a flight
to Charlotte got to an ambulance with 10 minutes to spare, thanks
to air traffic controllers who rerouted rush-hour air traffic and
cleared taxiways for the woman's plane.
   A baby girl was born to the 22-year-old woman in the ambulance,
which had to pull off the road before reaching Presbyterian
Hospital.
   The race with the stork began shortly after 8 a.m. Thursday when
the pilot of Piedmont Airlines Flight 300 from Birmingham, Ala., to
Charlotte and Raleigh-Durham asked controllers to get him down and
to a ramp in a hurry.
   Air traffic controllers summoned an ambulance while rerouting
eight to 10 planes. When the flight touched down at
Charlotte-Douglas International Airport, controllers held other
planes while it pulled up to a gate.
   A medical emergency team rushed the woman into the waiting
ambulance and sped off to the hospital.
   On Thursday afternoon, as she was recovering, the woman, who
requested that her name not be released, received an unexpected
memento of the early arrival _ a vase of roses and a card from the
airport controllers.
