<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JetLag     06-10 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Lag,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet Lag Afflicts Nine of 10 Long-Distance Travelers, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jet lag hamstrings tens of millions of travelers
annually, and most don't know how to combat it, although proven
stategies exist to reduce or eliminate it, a new survey indicates.
   The survey found that 94 percent of people jetting across three
or more time zones suffered symptoms of jet lag, and 45 percent
were bothered severely, yet less than half tried to do anything
about it.
   ``If you ask the average person what could he or she do, most
might only say, `Take a semi-rest the first day or two when you
arrive,''' said Dr. Michael Irwin, medical director of the United
Nations.
   Yet, he said, several ways of coping are known to be helpful.
   Irwin was in Chicago on Thursday to discuss findings of the poll
of 784 long-distance travelers. The study, commissioned by the
Upjohn Co. of Kalamazoo, Mich., was conducted by pollsters R.L.
Associates of Princeton, N.J., with the help of United Airlines and
British Airways.
   Symptoms that bothered more than nine of 10 included fatigue,
sleeplessness, impaired concentration, slowed reflexes,
irritablity, upset digestion, hunger at odd hours and-or
depression, the survey found.
   Yet only about 45 percent of the total said they did anything to
avoid the ill effects, it said.
   Those who did make an effort most commonly avoided alcohol on
the flight, rested a few days on arrival, exercised daily on
arrival, adjusted sleeping patterns before leaving or used a
short-term sleeping medication the first night or two in the new
place.
   ``Most people still don't realize to avoid alcohol on the
plane,'' said Irwin, whose interest in the problem of jet lag
developed from his duties overseeing the health of U.N. staff.
   ``The reason is that the combination of dry air inside the plane
_ less than 5 percent humidity _ with the alcohol makes you very
dehydrated, and it's harder to adjust to a different time zone.''
   He said at least 100 biochemical and hormonal rhythms exist in
the body, which govern daily cycles such as sleep, and all suffer
with dehydration.
   Jet lag is worse flying from west to east, as evidenced by the
finding that 23 percent of East Coast travelers to Europe reported
severe jet lag, while only 14 percent had severe problems on the
reverse trip, the survey said.
   On long trips _ crossing three or four time zones _ exercising
outdoors can do much toward resetting the biological clock, Irwin
said.
   He said it would be ideal to exercise in morning daylight after
an eastward flight, to help the body to adjust to an earlier day,
and in evening daylight after a westward flight, to help the body
to adjust to a later day.
   Short-acting sleeping medications, known as benzodiazepines, are
also very useful to help readjust sleeping patterns the first day
or two after arrival, without causing grogginess during normal
waking hours, he said.
   ``Only take medication prescribed by a doctor, not something
given by a friend or (bought) over the counter,'' Irwin said.
   The travelers surveyed had made at least two round-trips of
5,000 miles, once eastward and once westward, in the 24 months
before the survey in June 1987, said Upjohn spokesman Leonard H.
Gross.
   U.S. airlines carried more than 29 million passengers on
international flights from June 1985 through May 1986, the company
said. Even if only half flew east or west, the survey suggests the
number of people suffering jet lag is huge, the company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
