<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Fried-Meese     06-10 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fried-Meese,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservatives Want Solicitor General Dismissed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives angry at Solicitor General
Charles Fried for hiring a deputy they view as too liberal want
Fried dismissed unless the solicitor general urges the Supreme
Court to overrule a major civil rights precedent.
   Fried is the department's No. 4 official who, after considering
resigning in March, has stayed on despite a wave of protest
resignations and departures by top aides to Attorney General Edwin
Meese III over the past 2{ months.
   ``We urge you to relieve Mr. Fried of his responsibilities'' if
the solicitor general refuses to file a brief supporting reversal
of the precedent, Paul Kamenar, executive legal director of the
Washington Legal Foundation, said in a letter to Meese.
   Fried is considering what position the government should take in
response to the court's 5-4 vote to invite arguments in Runyon v.
McCrary. In that 1976 case, the court ruled that a civil rights law
from the Reconstruction era could be used to desegregate private
schools and to seek damages for racial discrimination in a wide
range of areas.
   Kamenar's letter Wednesday also criticized Fried's decision to
hire, with Meese's approval, Harvard Law School professor David
Shapiro as deputy solicitor general.
   Shapiro wrote a 1976 law review article criticizing Supreme
Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist as a judge who is inflexibile
and whose performance on the bench is below his capabilities
because of his unyielding ideology. Department officials
successfully pushed for Rehnquist's elevation to chief justice.
   Justice Department conservatives were angry over the naming of
Shapiro, say department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The conservative weekly ``Human Events'' calls Shapiro a
``liberal'' and says he should not have been hired by Fried and
approved by Meese.
   Fried's selection of Shapiro comes at a period when Meese, beset
by legal problems and trying to hang onto his job, wants as many
top officials as possible to remain in place to avoid the
perception that the department is in trouble.
   Meese was informed ahead of time about Fried's plans to hire
Shapiro and was told of his background, Justice Department
spokesman Patrick Korten said today.
   ``The attorney general has always permitted department heads to
choose their own deputies,'' said Korten. The department spokesman
denied that Meese was giving Fried a free hand to keep the
solicitor general from leaving the Justice Department.
   Fried also has recently hired as lawyers in his office a clerk
to a liberal District of Columbia circuit court judge and another
clerk to a federal judge who was an appointee of President Carter
and a former aide to Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
</TEXT>
