<2ND_LINE>PM-YWCA Director,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>YWCA in Tacoma Faces Loss of Affiliation for Hiring Male Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Young Women's Christian
Association say they will recommend dropping the 82-year-old local
Y from the national organization for hiring a male executive
director.
   Gwendolyn Calvert Baker, national YWCA executive director, and
national board member Marilynne Keyser failed Thursday to persuade
the local Y's 19-member board of directors to change their position
supporting the director.
   ``This association will continue as an association but will not
continue as a YWCA,'' Ms. Baker said.
   Alan Tiger, 34, hired as executive director on April 19, said he
expected the national organization to drop the local Y. The local
board gave him a unanimous vote of support Thursday night.
   The YWCA constitution limits membership to women and requires
that an executive director be female. Tiger is the first man chosen
for such a job at any Y in the country.
   ``We hired the best person for the job,'' said board member
Susan Ralph, one of three people who interviewed Tiger. ``I think
we can fight just as strong for women's issues _ if not stronger _
from this platform.
   ``If you're a Christian organization, you practice fal board at a meeting
June 21 in Chicago, Ms. Keyser said.
   Once disaffiliated, the Tacoma Y will be barred from using the
YWCA name or symbol; however, local board members said all
operations would continue under funding commitments from the city
and United Way.
   Officials of the city and the United Way, which together provide
more than $300,000 of the Y's annual $577,000 budget, said this
week that funding might be jeopardized if Tiger were fired because
he was a man.
   Tiger said he planned to continue building the local
organization as a provider of services for women, girls and
families in Pierce County, which includes Tacoma and has a
population of 485,000.
   ``We don't consider what we're doing here as a statement,'' he
said. ``We simply want to provide services.''
</TEXT>
