<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     06-10 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers, Producers Talk for Eighth Straight Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters ended a 19-hour
bargaining session with producers this morning but declined to say
whether they were nearing settlement of the 14-week-old strike.
   However, another round of bargaining was scheduled for this
afternoon.
   The latest negotiations, which began at 11 a.m. Thursday, ended
at 6:30 a.m. today, said Cheryl Rhoden, a spokeswoman for the
Writers Guild of America. The talks were scheduled to resume at 4
p.m., she said.
   Today marked the eighth straight day writers have met with
representatives of the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers. Both sides have refused to disclose what is being
discussed, calling the bargaining sensitive.
   However, the entertainment trade paper Daily Variety reported
Thursday its sources said there was some basis for optimism in the
negotiations between the producers and representatives of the guild.
   ``We are still meeting, and still hopeful this thing will come
to a conclusion and we can get back to work,'' said alliance
spokesman Herb Steinberg.
   Facing both sides is the start of the fall television production
season, which usually begins the last week in June and first week
of July. The CBS network has already announced a two-month delay
for the debut of its new shows, blaming the strike.
   ABC Entertainment President Brandon Stoddard told affiliates in
Los Angeles on Wednesday that the No. 2 network plans to begin its
season in October.
   ABC-TV Network Group President John Sias denied the writers
strike had any effect on his network's decision to open the season
later than usual. He cited the Summer Olympic Games and the World
Series, both on No.1-rated NBC, as the chief reason for the move.
   Scriptwriters called the industrywide work halt March 7, when
contract talks broke down over the issues of creative control on
the set and payments made for TV residuals, or reruns.
   The strike has stalled TV and movie productions, with the
exception of a few independent producers that have signed
independent contracts with the WGA.
   The 9,000-member guild has signed full-term contracts with about
80 independent producers, but the alliance contends none of its
large members have signed and the producers who did defect employ
only a fraction of the 3,000 active writers.
</TEXT>
