<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presbyterians     06-10 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presbyterians,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Christians Urge Presbyterians To Work For Palestinian
Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The six-month-old uprising on the West Bank has
erased Palestinian fear of Israel and changed the rules in the
fight over the occupied territories, said two Palestinian Christian
leaders in urging Presbyterians to oppose Israeli and U.S. policy
in the region.
   ``The uprising has really changed things,'' the Rev. Naim Ateek
told reporters Thursday at the 200th General Assembly of the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.).
   Ateek, an ecumenical delegate to the meeting from the Episcopal
Church of Jerusalem and the Middle East, said peace efforts by
Secretary of State George Shultz have been doomed because he has a
``pre-uprising agenda.''
   The Presbyterians are considering resolutions calling on Israel
to end its 20-year occupation of the West Bank and Gaza and join in
a United Nations-sponsored international peace conference. Israel
captured the territories from Jordan and Egypt, respectively, in
the 1967 Six-Day War.
   The Palestinian discussion is one of a number of issues before
various committees of the assembly, which meet today and Saturday
before beginning their reports to the 630-member assembly. The
nine-day meeting ends Wednesday.
   Other topics include consideration of a report on ``Christian
Obedience in a Nuclear Age,'' a controversial paper that has drawn
criticism within the 3 million-member denomination because of its
discussions of church support for those who choose to resist
government actions.
   Ateek said the Palestinians want a homeland alongside Israel.
His contacts with fellow Palestinians in east Jerusalem have led
him to believe that most have accepted the existence of Israel, he
said.
   However, the Palestine Liberation Organization, seen by most
Palestinians as their representative, does not officially recognize
Israel. Its constitution remains committed to the destruction of
the Jewish state.
   Ateek's conclusions were echoed by the Rev. Elias Chacour, a
priest in the Melkite church in Jerusalem who was awarded the
Peaceseeker Award today by the Presbyterian Peace Fellowship, a
sanctioned group with the denomination.
   Chacour told reporters Israel must deal with the Palestinians
soon because they have ``no more patience, no more possibility to
wait under intolerable conditions.''
   The paper before the Presbyterians accuses Israel of
``systematic violation of the human rights of Palestinians in the
occupied territories,'' especially through administrative
detention, collective punishment and torture of prisoners and
suspects and the deportation of dissidents.
   Recommendations addressing U.S. conduct include calling for
pressure on Israel to cease use of excessive force and supporting a
U.N. peace conference. The paper also opposes efforts to expel the
PLO's U.N. mission in New York.
   The ``Christian Obedience'' paper is undergoing a line-by-line
review by a subcommittee of the assembly's Committee on Peacemaking
and International Relations, the same assembly committee that will
address the Middle East paper.
   Objections center on what opponents say is encouragement of
denominational support for resisting the government on a variety of
issues.
   The full assembly will begin hearing committee reports Saturday
afternoon, but many of the more controversial issues won't be taken
up until next week.
</TEXT>
