<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0409 06-10 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0409,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Rise in May</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with report on producer price
index; pickup 3rd graf pvs, `The stock ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices, led by the steepest increase in food costs
since January, rose a moderate 0.5 percent in May, the government
said today.
   If the May increase held steady for 12 straight months,
inflation at the wholesale level would be 5.8 percent, nearly
triple the modest 2 percent increase of the past 12 months, the
Labor Department said.
   The index for wholesale prices at the finished goods level minus
energy and food was up 0.3 percent. Analysts consider this a more
reliable indicator of underlying inflation because of the
month-to-month volatility of food and energy costs.
   Over the past year, wholesale prices excluding food and energy
have risen 2.8 percent.
   On Thursday, the government reported that U.S. businesses plan
the biggest increases in spending on new plant and equipment in
four years.
   The Commerce Department said the ambitious investment plans were
partly due to an improvement in the trade picture. But the
department also said announced that the trade deficit is shrinking
more slowly than previously reported.
   The stock market was mostly lower Thursday as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials, up 48.36 on Wednesday, slipped back 9.60
to 2,093.35.
   Bond prices slipped and interest rates rose as higher commodity
prices stirred concerns about inflation. The dollar also lost
ground.
   The Commerce Department said U.S. companies plan to increase
their spending on plant and equipment this year by 11.9 percent
over 1987.
   The increased investment, found in a May survey, was partly the
result of companies' gearing up to produce more goods for export
and replace imports with products made at home.
   If the projected 1988 increase in capital spending actually
occurs it will be the biggest gain in plant and equipment spending
since 1984, when spending shot up 16.6 percent as businesses
recovered from the 1981-82 recession.
   ``Manufacturing, especially in 1988, looks like it has very
aggressive plans. ... That's got to be good news,'' said David
Wyss, chief financial economist at Data Resources Inc. of
Lexington, Mass.
   However, Wyss warned that rising interest rates or renewed
trouble in the stock market could cause businesses to quickly scale
back expansion plans.
   In a separate report, the department recalculated its trade
statistics to account for seasonal patterns in shipments and found
the deficits came out bigger. The March deficit was put at $11.9
billion, 22 percent higher than the previously reported $9.7
billion.
   The non-adjusted figure of $9.7 billion for the March trade gap,
the best showing in three years, had been hailed by the Reagan
administration as solid evidence that the country's trade problems
had finally turned around.
   The administration said the new figures still showed an
improving trend, and private economists agreed.
   ``There is no reason to be discouraged by the new figures,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist at Boston Co.
   In another report, the Conference Board, a business-supported
research group, said pay increases should average about 5 percent
this year and next for the nation's salaried workers, narrowly
outpacing expected inflation.
</TEXT>
