<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Army Arrests Palestinian In Assault On West Bank Mayor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with suspect arrested in attack on West
Bank mayor, suspect's home destroyed. TRIMS. CHANGES byline. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JELAZOUN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces arrested a
Palestinian suspected of stabbing the Israeli-appointed mayor of a
West Bank town and demolished his cinderblock house today in the
Jelazoun refugee camp.
   Villagers said soldiers arrested Khamis Jawdat Faraj, 26, late
Thursday night. The army confirmed the arrest and said Faraj had
stalked the mayor and stabbed him as an act of Palestinian
nationalism.
   Arab news reports, meanwhile, said the army arrested two
Palestinian reporters and a writer in a continuing crackdown on
Arab journalists. An Israeli newspaper said the military may shut
down West Bank schools again.
   It took 30 minutes for a large, yellow bulldozer to destroy the
three-room house where Faraj lived with his 60-year-old mother.
Only an almond tree, plum tree and rose bush were left standing in
the yard after the demolition.
   ``They are destroying our house _ I don't know what for,'' said
the suspect's mother, Nozha Faraj, who watched the army operation
from next door.
   Faraj was arrested in connection with the stabbing Tuesday of
Hassan Tawil, the 74-year-old mayor of El Bireh. The army follows a
long-standing practice of demolishing the homes of suspects in what
it considers terrorist acts.
   Tawil was stabbed in the heart and was reported recovering.
   Faraj has been detained several times previously because of
alleged involvement in public disturbances, an army statement said.
``He followed the mayor's movements, intending to assassinate him,
and attempted to do so previously, without success,'' the statement
said.
   Underground leaflets issued by leaders of the six-month Arab
uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip have repeatedly
called for Israeli-appointed officials like Tawil to quit their
posts.
   More than 200 Palestinians and two Israelis have been killed in
the violence.
   The Hebrew daily newspaper Haaretz today quoted army sources as
saying schools could close again if students follow orders given in
underground leaflets to leave classes at noon.
   Schools used to recess at noon, but authorities have extended
classroom time to 12:30 p.m. or 1 p.m. to make up for the four
months schools were closed during the height of the uprising.
   A spokesman for the West Bank's military government could not be
reached for comment on the Haaretz report. On Thursday, a spokesman
said the army had no immediate plans to close schools again because
of increased violence.
   On Thursday, protests and a general strike in the occupied lands
marked six months of the ``intefadeh,'' or uprising.
   Ahmed Hassan Hawari, 17, was killed when he was shot in the head
by an Israeli officer in the village of Sebastiya near Nablus. The
army said he was about to throw a cement block at troops from a
terrace when he was shot.
   An 18-year-old youth and a 12-year-old girl were wounded in the
legs during a protest in the West Bank town of Tulkarem, hospital
officials said.
   The army said only one person was shot in the protest but said
two other protesters were wounded when dozens of Palestinians
attacked troops with bottles and stones in Nablus' Arab bazaar.
   A 40-year-old Arab motorist, Rouhi Mohammed Khaliya, died of
heart failure after his car was stoned a he passed the Dheishe
refugee camp near Bethlehem, the army command said.
   Israel radio said several cars carrying blue West Bank license
plates were stoned by Dheishe residents, apparently to enforce
compliance with the strike.
   The deaths brought the Palestinian death toll in the uprising to
204. More than 5,000 Palestinians have been injured and 5,000
jailed since the protests began Dec. 8. Two Israelis also have died.
   The latest arrests of journalists came on the eve of the
protests. The east Jerusalem newspaper Al Shaab said the army
arrested Bader Taleb Yassin Meky, a sports reporter, at his home in
Jericho.
   Al Ittihad, another Arabic-language paper, said Samir Subayhat,
a free- lance reporter from El Bireh, and Muhammad Ayub Abu-Hadrus,
a writer and teacher from the Gaza Strip town of Khan Younis, were
seized at their homes.
   A spokesman for the army said he could not confirm the reports
or explain why the writers were arrested. At least 30 journalists
have been arrested and 20 of them have been jailed without charges
or trial for up to six months, according to Al Haq, an Arab human
rights organization.
</TEXT>
