<2ND_LINE>PM-Crush Verdict, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0567,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$25 Million to Parents Whose Children Were Crushed Under Truck</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to note conflicting spellings of elder child's
name. INSERTS 2 grafs before last graf pvs to add details of
mother's grief.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has awarded $25 million to the parents of
two children who were crushed to death under the wheels of a truck
as they were crossing the street with their mother.
   The jury, finding that a ``Walk-Don't Walk'' sign was partly to
blame, awarded the money Thursday to building superintendent Ismet
Delosovic, 39, and his wife, Fatima, 34, in the deaths of their
children, Vaid, 3, and Blerini, 5. Court papers and attorneys gave
conflicting spellings of the elder child's name, which was also
spelled Blerim.
   The truck, driven by Stephen Rapczak, 25, of Garwood, N.J., and
owned by Higgins Trucking Co. of Clifton, N.J., hit the little boys
May 8, 1981, as they, their mother and baby brother were crossing a
street in Greenwich Village.
   The Delosovics' lawyer, Gary Pillersdorf, said the light didn't
give the four pedestrians enough time to cross the street, turning
green while they were in the crosswalk.
   Rapczak testified during the 4{-week trial that he was unable to
see the family, so he proceeded.
   The two boys were killed almost instantly. The mother and her
third child, 9-month-old Rizo, suffered superficial injuries.
   The jury found found Rapczak and Higgins Trucking 44 percent
liable, but the Delosovics had already settled with them for
$500,000.
   The remaining 56 percent of liability was divided equally
between International Harvester because of alleged poor design of
the truck and the city because of alleged poor design of an
intersection and an improperly functioning light.
   This means International Harvester must pay 28 percent of $25
million, or $7 million, and the city must pay the same.
   Both defendants said they will appeal the verdict as excessive,
Pillersdorf said.
   ``She will never know joy again. You could have given her $100
million. It wouldn't matter,'' he said of Mrs. Delosevic, who told
the New York Daily News and New York Post that she still caresses
the clothes of her dead children and talks to them every night.
   Pillsdorf said his client was so anguished after the accident
that she could not bear to feed her youngest child for a year, and
the two children she has had since then have been named after the
boys who were killed.
   Justice Edward Lehner, the trial judge, scheduled a July 15
hearing for motions on the verdict.
</TEXT>
