<2ND_LINE>PM-Cajun Artist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artist Stages Capitol Hill Show After Soviet Snag</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New in top 9 grafs with show opening. Picks up 8th graf pvs
bgng: Rodrigue, 43 ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Rodrigue displayed his oil paintings
today on Capitol Hill, where he encountered more glasnost than he
found in the Soviet Union.
   Thirteen of the Cajun artist's paintings, which caused a stir at
the Moscow summit, were hung in a meeting room for a one-day show
co-sponsored by Louisiana Reps. Bob Livingston, a Republican, and
James Hayes, a Democrat.
   The show came a week after Rodrigue said a network television
crew smuggled his paintings out of the Soviet Union following an
exhibition during the Moscow summit. Two of Rodrigue's paintings
had been temporarily confiscated.
   ``It was a remarkable contrast to see President Reagan extolling
perestroika and glasnost, and at the very same time an American
artist sees his paintings ripped off the walls,'' Livingston said.
   Hayes said he and Livingston disagree politically on many
issues, but they are united in the idea that artists have a right
to express themselves.
   Rodrigue said he resorted to smuggling the paintings out of the
country after Soviet functionaries refused to hand over the
necessary exit permits so he could leave.
   Soviet officials wanted him to donate his portrait of Kremlin
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, dressed in a yellow suit and carrying
a red flag. Rodrigue said he declined the offer unless he could
meet Gorbachev personally.
   The American television crew ``didn't have to go through
customs'' because they were on a plane that carried reporters who
covered the summit back to the United States, Rodrigue said.
   He refused to identify the network by name for fear it would be
subject to reprisals in the Soviet Union. No one answered the
telephone at the Soviet information office and a message was not
returned.
   Rodrigue, 43, of Lafayette, La., described his experience with
the Soviet bureaucracy as ``horrifying ... the worst show I ever
had.'' That contrasted with his view of ordinary Russians who were
``real nice,'' he said.
   Rodrigue was invited to the Moscow summit by a Soviet delegation
that hoped to create a Louisiana theme at Moscow's international
trade center, the heart of activity during the summit.
   The paintings were to hang in a restaurant where a Louisiana
chef served Cajun food.
   Rodrigue said his first disappointment was that ordinary Soviet
citizens were banned from the trade center so his paintings had
only limited exposure, primarily to American reporters and
officials.
   The day after he put up the oil paintings, Soviet officials
confiscated the one that showed Gorbachev and another depicting
President Reagan mounted on a white horse and wearing a cowboy hat.
   Officials gave conflicting reasons for the action, but Rodrigue
called them all ``real stupid.''
   ``They asked `Why wasn't Gorbachev on a horse?''' he said.
``Then they said the paintings were too expensive. ... Then they
asked why Reagan's painting did not have a sun in it.''
   He added: ``The bottom line really is they didn't want the
president hanging in a Russian restaurant. That's what I think.''
   Rodrigue speculated that widespread media attention on the
painting prompted the Soviets to reconsider. Two days before he was
to leave, they re-hung the two paintings.
   A few hours later, Rodrigue removed the paintings for good and
unsuccessfully asked for the exit permits.
</TEXT>
