<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Professor'sTransfer     06-10 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Professor's Transfer,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UMass Chancellor Asks for Investigation into Black Professor's
Transfer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Massachusetts' top
administrator has asked the faculty senate to investigate
allegations that a black professor was ousted from the
Afro-American studies department for his views.
   Circumstances surrounding professor Julius Lester's reassignment
to the Judaic studies department might be referred to the American
Association of University Professors for a formal investigation to
clear up ``serious and, in some cases, perhaps misleading
allegations,'' Chancellor Joseph Duffey said.
   Lester has accused the Afro-American studies department of
racism in objecting to his criticisms of the black community and of
such leaders as the Rev. Jesse Jackson and the late author James
Baldwin.
   ``The department reacted (to the Baldwin criticism) as if I had
attacked every member,'' Lester has said. ``They're acting as if
James Baldwin is a person who is above criticism. ... In effect
they're kicking me out. If a white did this to a black faculty
member, people would say `racism.' It's no different if a black
person does it to a black faculty member. It's worse.''
   Department members met a few months ago to discuss Lester's
unorthodox views and voted to recommend that he be reassigned to
another department.
   Lester had already begun talks with administrators about leaving
the department when its members cast their vote. The reassignment
became official last week and was made with the approval of all
parties involved.
   In a letter, Duffey wrote Afro-American studies professor
Michael Thelwell on Thursday, he criticized the department for the
meeting and for a letter faculty members sent the dean of
humanities suggesting Lester ``would be infinitely more comfortable
in a different location.''
   ``Julius Lester represents the kind of teacher this university
cherishes,'' Duffey said Thursday.
   The department had written a 40-page report rebutting Lester's
claim in his book ``Lovesongs'' that Baldwin made anti-Semitic
remarks during a 1984 faculty discussion. The report included
transcripts of Baldwin's remarks.
   ``Because Baldwin represented a constant struggle with racism of
all forms, we took those charges to be grossly serious,'' Thelwell
said.
   Julius, 49, is a 17-year veteran of the department and the
winner of the university's most prestigious faculty awards.
   He gained notoriety in the 1960s as a spokesman for the black
power movement. Although he once broadcast a poem taunting Jews, he
converted to Judaism six years ago and has since irritated his
black colleagues with his opinions. He wrote an essay in 1984, for
example, accusing Jackson of posing as a messiah to blacks in his
quest for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
