<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0583 06-10 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0583,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Seamen Killed In Iraqi Air Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with latest convoy enters gulf,
convoy approached by two speedboats in Hormuz. ADDS byline. TRIMS
to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes attacked a tanker
off Iran's Persian Gulf coast at dawn today, and shipping sources
said two seamen were killed in an earlier Iraqi air strike on a
salvage tugboat.
   The latest convoy of Kuwaiti tankers and their U.S. Navy escorts
passed through the Strait of Hormuz and sailed into the gulf today.
Two small boats that resembled Iranian speedboats approached the
convoy but did not attack.
   The official Iraqi News Agency quoted a military spokesman as
saying the jets hit a ``large maritime target,'' which usually
means a tanker.
   The spokesman, who was not identified, said the marauding
fighter-bombers scored ``an accurate and effective hit'' on the
unidentified vessel.
   There was no independent confirmation of the Iraqi claim of an
attack today. But shipping sources in the gulf and the London-based
Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit said the 742-ton tug Salverve
was hit by an Iraqi missile Thursday in the northern gulf.
   Thursday's attack was the first confirmed Iraqi air raid on
Iranian shipping lanes in about four weeks.
   Lloyd's, which monitors shipping around the world, said two
crewmen were killed abord the Singapore-flag tug. Shipping
executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the casualties
were probably Filipinos.
   The Salverve has been hit twice before. It suffered no
casualties in the first attack July 7. But its British captain and
two Filipino crewmen were killed in a Jan. 28 raid, when the
Salverve was towing a tanker damaged in an Iraqi air strike the day
before.
   Salverve is owned by the Singapore-based Semco Salvage Ltd., one
of the salvage companies that regularly work with Iranians.
   More than a half-dozen salvage tugs, mainly Semco vessels, that
operate off the Iranian coast have been hit in the so-called
``tanker war,'' a spinoff from the Iran-Iraq conflict, which began
in September 1980.
   Iraqi warplanes regularly attack Iranian tankers, seeking to
choke off Tehran's vital oil exports which pay for its war effort.
The Iranians retaliate by attacking neutral commercial ships in the
waterway. The last confirmed Iraqi raid was on the Iran-flagged
tanker Bisoton May 16.
   The 36th U.S. convoy of the year _ three U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti
oil carriers and two escorting warships _ departed from an assembly
area in the Gulf of Oman, steamed through the Strait of Hormuz and
entered the Persian Gulf early today.
   The convoy, guarded by the 3,880-ton guided missile frigate USS
Fahrion and the 7,810-ton destroyer USS John Hancock, was joined by
about nine other ships from other countries that tagged along for
the journey through the strait.
   The two vessels that approached to within two miles of the
convoy each carried two crew members but there was no sign of
weapons, said Lt. Cmdr. Brad Goforth, a Navy spokesman with a
Pentagon news media pool aboard the Fahrion.
   Iran usually hits vessels sailing to or from Kuwait or Saudi
Arabia in its retaliatory strikes. It accuses both countries of
aiding Iraq.
   This prompted Kuwait last summer to re-register 11 of its
tankers in the United States to entitle them to U.S. Navy
protection.
   The U.S. Navy widened its protective role to non-American
vessels May 3 and said its warships would aid any vessel in their
vicinity if it was attacked by either side outside designated
exclusion zones.
</TEXT>
