<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-DonahueHouse     06-10 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Donahue House,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talk Show Host Draws Ire of Neighbors For Razing House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phil Donahue has razed an experimental,
all-concrete house despite criticism that he was destroying a
landmark, but the talk-show host questioned why the community let
the 26-year-old house fall into disrepair.
   ``Why didn't somebody take care of this building?'' Donahue said
after the building, next door to his classic Tudor-style mansion,
was demolished Wednesday. ``Where were all these caring people when
the building was unoccupied?''
   Donahue, who bought the concrete house and 7.2 acres of land
around it for $6 million two months ago, said he wanted more space,
privacy and security for his wife, actress Marlo Thomas, and their
family. He denied that he wanted to improve the view of Long Island
Sound from his mansion.
   Donahue said he didn't know about the house's architectural
significance and that it had become a hostel for ``vagrants, lovers
and other strangers'' who left behind ``empty beer cans and
McDonald's wrappers.''
   Some local historians described the concrete house as the
affluent town's most architecturally significant building, a piece
of sculpture as well as a structure.
   ``I still get knots in my stomach when I think about it,'' said
Mary McCahon, Westport's architectural historian. ``It was a
wonderful building. The best design in Westport. Tearing it down, I
think, on a scale of 1 to 10, is a 10. It's pretty bad.''
   John M. Johansen, the internationally known architect who
designed the house, said: ``This wasn't a very exemplary act from a
public figure. And they've nicknamed him `Mr. Sensitivity.'''
   The house, designed in what McCahon called a
contemporary-expressionist style, was built as a retirement cottage
for a wealthy physician.
   ``Many people who are expressing deep concern have never seen
the house, nor have they been in it,'' Donahue said, adding that
the house's style left him cold. ``I did not find this an inviting
home.''
</TEXT>
