<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Pluto 1stLd-Writethru a0594 06-10 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pluto, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0594,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Directly Observe Pluto Atmosphere For First Time, NASA
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with scientists saying observations show
Pluto has substantial atmosphere, details of findings. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists flying over the southern
Pacific Ocean directly observed the atmosphere of Pluto for the
first time, NASA has announced.
   While scientists previously had strong indirect evidence for the
existence of an atmosphere on the solar system's ninth planet, the
astronomers who viewed Pluto from a telescope aboard NASA's Kuiper
Airborne Observatory on Thursday got the first direct look at it,
said space agency spokeswoman Diane Stanley.
   The observations show that Pluto is surrounded by what appears
to be a substantial atmosphere, said J. Kelly Beatty, senior editor
for Sky & Telescope magazine, reporting in Friday's edition of The
Boston Globe. Beatty, who rode aboard the NASA aircraft, filed his
report from Pago Pago in American Samoa.
   The discovery of a significant atmosphere could end years of
debate over the extent of the atmosphere of Pluto, which averages
more than 3.7 billion miles from the sun in its orbit, Beatty said.
   The Massachusetts Institute of Technology researchers, flying at
an altitude of 41,000 feet, used a solid-state video camera
attached to a 36-inch telescope to watch the light of a star as the
tiny planet started to move in front of it.
   As the edge of the planet started to move in front of the star,
changes in the light confirmed the existence of the atmosphere,
said Stanley, a spokeswoman at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Ames Research Center in Mountain View.
   James Elliot and MIT colleague Edward W. Dunham said that Pluto
must be surrounded by a gaseous atmosphere because as the planet
passed in front of the star, the faint starlight disappeared and
reappeared gradually rather than abruptly.
   Elliot and Dunham said they are not yet sure what gases make up
Pluto's atmosphere, but possibilities include methane, argon,
nitrogen, oxygen, carbon monoxide and neon.
   The observations were made about 3,500 miles south of Hawaii.
The airborne observatory flew out of Hawaii at 7:30 p.m. local time
Thursday and landed in Pago Pago 7{ hours later.
   In May 1987, scientists at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena published a study in the British journal Nature contending
that Pluto has a substantial atmosphere of methane, or natural gas.
They said observations of the planet in 1983 by the Infrared
Astronomical Satellite showed that Pluto's temperature was uniform
over its entire surface, something that could occur only if a
significant atmosphere existed.
   However, scientists from the University of Arizona and the
Planetary Science Institute, both in Tucson, published a
contradictory study last September in the journal Science. They
said that evidence from the same satellite suggested Pluto's
atmosphere was extremely thin, at least 900 times less dense than
Earth's atmosphere.
   Stanley said that the observations made Thursday will, after
analysis, provide information about the extent of Pluto's
atmosphere and its temperature and pressure.
   Pluto, which is thought to be half ice and half rock, usually is
thought of as the ninth planet from the sun, but because it has an
elongated elliptical orbit, it will be the eighth planet from the
sun until 1990, when it heads outward beyond Neptune's orbit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0118 </DOCNO>
