<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Gulf-PoolReport     06-10 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gulf-Pool Report,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Speedboats Approach U.S. Convoy In Strait Of Hormuz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS FAHRION IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two vessels
resembling Iranian speedboats raced toward a convoy of U.S.
warships and Kuwaiti tankers, but veered off without attacking,
Navy officials said Friday.
   The speedboats came within two miles of the two U.S. warships
and three U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti oil carriers as they steamed
Thursday night through the Strait of Hormuz en route to the Persian
Gulf, the officials said.
   Nine other tankers, at least two of them with ``Philadelphia,
Pa.'' painted on their sterns, tagged along with the convoy as it
ran the gantlet of Iranian missile batteries and gunboats in the
strait.
   The 36th U.S. convoy of the year began its journey at the
so-called ``K-Mart parking lot,'' the convoy assembly area in the
Gulf of Oman.
   By the time the procession turned the corner past Oman's
flashing Didimar Light in the strait, it had swelled to at least 14
ships, according to officers aboard this 3,880-ton guided missile
frigate, which was taking part in its first escort mission since
arriving in the gulf earler in the week.
   The second escort was the 7,810-ton destroyer John Hancock, also
a new arrival, which recently accompanied another Kuwaiti tanker
down the gulf.
   The two vessels that rushed the convoy were Boston Whaler-type
speedboats, often used by Iran to attack neutral shipping in the
southern gulf.
   Each speedboat carried two crew members but there was no sign of
weapons, according to Lt. Cmdr. Brad Goforth, a Navy spokesman
accompanying a Pentagon news media pool aboard the Fahrion.
   ``They just wanted to see who we were,'' said the frigate's
skipper, Cmdr. Thomas E. Plichta, of Charleston, S.C.
   Iran has carried out four gunboat raids on ships in the southern
gulf since May 3, when a tougher U.S. policy permitting American
warships to intervene in attacks on non-U.S. vessels went into
effect. In all four cases, however, no American ships were close
enough to act.
   The U.S. convoy was one of the largest this year and the 57th
since Washington agreed a year ago to reflag 11 Kuwaiti-owned oil
tankers and give them naval escort against Iranian attack. Iran
considers Kuwait an ally of Iraq, Iran's enemy in the Persian Gulf
war.
   The convoy included the 295,085-ton Middletown and the
80,000-ton Ocean City, oil products tankers, and the 48,725-ton
liquefied gas carrier Gas King.
   ``Tag alongs'' have become a regular feature of the American and
European convoys in the gulf, as merchant ships look for ways to
shield themselves from Iranian gunboat raids in the southern gulf
and strait.
   But rarely, if ever, has a convoy attracted as many as the nine
hitchhikers that sailed in front, behind and on both sides of the
convoy Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
