<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceCommissioner     06-10 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Commissioner,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Williams Sworn In As Philadelphia Police Commissioner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie Williams, a 24-year police department
veteran, was sworn in today as the city's new police commissioner
and pledged to put more officers on the street despite budgetary
restraints.
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode called today's ceremony a ``historic
occasion,'' although he did not specifically mention that Williams
is the first black to serve as police commissioner. Goode is the
city's first black mayor.
   Williams, 44, will succeed Kevin Tucker, who resigned to take a
job in private business after about 2{ years on the job. Tucker had
appointed Williams to the post of deputy commissioner.
   The new commissioner faces what police union officials say is a
crisis of manpower. He's under orders to reduce the 6,500-member
force by a reported 350 officers, or 5 percent.
   At the same time, the city is releasing hundreds of people from
its jails to get the prison population down to a court-mandated cap
of 3,750 inmates.
   Williams has said his major goal is to prevent any reduction of
the patrol force, which includes more than 3,000 uniformed police.
   He also said he would continue to battle street-corner drug
sales and try to modernize the police department's communications
system.
   Fraternal Order of Police president Robert Hurst today said
Goode had asked him to sit down with the new commissioner and
discuss how to cut police manpower. However, Hurst said he couldn't
do that, since his job was to fight for police offices, not to have
their numbers reduced.
</TEXT>
