<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Korea,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Asks Soviets, Others Countries To Attempt To Insure Peaceful
Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has asked the Soviet Union
and other countries to use their influence to attempt to insure a
peaceful summer Olympic Games in Seoul, South Korea, the White
House said today.
   ``We obviously are hopeful that the Olympics will go off without
any demonstrations or undue disruption,'' spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said. ``We have raised this matter with the Soviet Union
in asking them to use their influence and we have spoken to all
countries who might have any influence to try to insure a peaceful
and successful Olympics in Seoul.''
   He said the issue was raised by Secretary of State George P.
Shultz in his meetings with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze before the U.S.-Soviet summit in Moscow
   He said as far as he knew it was not raised by President Reagan
in his summit meetings with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
