<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-USArt     06-10 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-US Art,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First U.S. Art Exhibit in 11 Years At Public Cultural Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American art is on display in a
public cultural center here for the first time since Marxist
Ethiopia became a staunch ally of the Soviet Union 11 years ago.
   U.S. Charge D'Affaires James Cheek opened the exhibit, ``U.S.A.
Printworks: Selections From the Brandywine Workshop Collections,''
Thursday night at the Addis Ababa City Hall Cultural Center.
   He said he hoped the art show would bring about a better
understanding of American art and society and encourage more
cultural exhanges between Ethiopia and the United States.
   The eight-day show came to Ethiopia after traveling extensively
throughout other parts of Africa, Latin American and Asia. It was
sponsored by the U.S. Embassy's Public Affairs office under the
U.S. government's cultural exchange program.
   The Brandywine Workshop was opened in Philadelphia, Penn., in
1972 by printer Allan Edmonds to provide access to sophisticated
printing techniques for artists.
   John Burns, the U.S. Embassy's public affairs spokesman, said
Friday his office sponsored an American art exhibition in Ethiopia
two years ago, but it was held in the Italian Cultural Center.
   He said the current exhibit marks the first time an American art
show has been held in a public cultural center in Ethiopia since
1977, when the government closed the U.S. Information Service and
the U.S. Military Assistance and Advisory Group office.
   Until Emperor Haile Selassie was overthrown in 1974, Ethiopia
was one of the West's staunchest allies. The nation turned to the
Soviet Union during its 1977-78 war with Somalia over a region of
eastern Ethiopia inhabited by ethnic Somalis known as the Ogaden.
   Cheek said the collection of prints from the Brandywine Workshop
collection were selected because they reflect the ethnic and
stylistic diversity in American art.
   Among the 34 artists whose works are represented in the exhibit
are Richard Hunt, of Chicago, and Sam Gillian, who was born in
Tupelo, Miss., but works in the Chicago area.
   Also represented in the show is Jules Olitski, a Soviet-born,
U.S.-educated artist based in New York. Olitski's works have been
shown in the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Whitney Museum of
American Art, and the Chicago Art Institute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
