<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Pollution     06-10 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Pollution,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spill from Chemical Fire Causes Serious Pollution of Loire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOURS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government cut off drinking water to
200,000 people after cancer-causing discharge from a chemical fire
flowed into the Loire River, authorities said Friday.
   An explosion and fire Wednesday night at the Protex factory in
Auzouer-en-Touraine, 15 miles northeast of Tours, injured one
person and sent phenol and metallic pollutants into the Brenne, a
tributary of the Loire.
   Protex produces synthetic carpets and other floor coverings.
   The government detected traces of phenol in the water supply
Thursday afternoon and immediately switched off water mains to
Tours and its northern suburbs, said Environment Minister Brice
Lalonde.
   Markets were mobbed with people buying emergency water supplies,
and the Interior Ministry shipped in potable water. The government
was conducting hourly checks on the water supply in the area.
   Lalonde said the government would take legal action against
Protex. The factory owners were ordered to secure the site to guard
against renewed spills, he said.
   Tours is 140 miles southwest of Paris in the Loire Valley, a
scenic and culinary center. The Brenne flows into the Loire a few
miles upstream of Tours.
</TEXT>
