<HEAD>Motorist Jailed for Refusing to Give Govt. Official a Lift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kenyan motorist who refused to give a
stranded government official a ride was jailed for three months for
``very unsocial behavior,'' press reports said Friday.
   Peter Makau, 36, a factory technician from Nairobi, pleaded
guilty Thursday in Eldoret Court to a charge of ``uttering words of
defiance and disobediency to a lawful authority, namely Yusuf
Haji,'' Nairobi newspapers said.
   Makau was driving through Eldoret in the Rift Valley region of
western Kenya last Wednesday when the commissioner, clad in his
official pith helmet and khaki uniform, hailed him for a ride. His
official car had broken down on the way to an official function.
   The commissioner, the top government official in the Rift Valley
province, was late.
   Makau told Haji, ``Go and find a GK (Government of Kenya
vehicle). My car is not a government vehicle.''
   The angry official reported the incident to local police.
   ``Government officials deserve respect,'' magistrate Njuguna
Kimani said when sentencing Makau to jail without the option of a
fine. ``The accused lacked respect.''
