<HEAD>GOP Senate Candidate in Maryland Withraws From Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican candidate to challenge Sen. Paul
Sarbanes, D-Md., in November has told party leaders he can't devote
the time needed to mount a proper campaign and will quit as the
party's candidate.
   Thomas L. Blair, 43, faced an uphill battle in his challenge to
Sarbanes, a two-term incumbent who won with 57 percent of the vote
in 1976 and 63 percent in 1982.
   The party's state central committee will choose a replacement
candidate, party officials said.
   In a letter to the chairman of the state GOP, Blair said he
regretted his ``present inability to conduct a full-time campaign
to retire Mr. Sarbanes from the Senate.'' Blair said in the letter
he faced ``intense pressures and business events.''
   Blair's office said he was unavailable for comment Thursday and
referred calls to the Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee in
Washington. Blair's letter was released through that office.
   One GOP source said the firm that took over Blair's health-care
management consulting firm wouldn't give him time off to campaign.
