<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-US     06-10 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Asked To Let Red Cross Look For U.S. POWs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Frank H. Murkowski said today he had
asked Vietnam to allow the Red Cross to verify that there are no
American prisoners of war still in the country.
   The Alaska Republican made the request in a meeting in New York
with Vietnam's foreign minister, Nguyen Co Thach, who is attending
a special U.N. General Assembly session on disarmament.
   ``I was very pleased with the response,'' said Murkowski. ``It
was a very positive one. He said the suggestion was very
appropriate and would address it upon his return to Hanoi.''
   Murkowski is a member of the Senate Veterans Affairs Committee.
   ``We have also contacted the International Committee of the Red
Cross, and they have indicated receptiveness'' to cooperating,
Murkowski told The Associated Press by telephone from Washington,
where he had returned later in the morning.
   Vietnam's U.N. ambassador, Trinh Xuan Lang, also attended the
meeting.
   Murkowski said the cooperative attitude of the Vietnamese was
encourging in light of next week's scheduled meeting of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee to consider the possibility of America
and Vietnam establishing interest sections in each others'
countries.
   Vietnam and America do not have diplomatic relations.
   ``I proposed to the foreign minister my conviction that until
the suspicion and doubt is removed on the MIA-POW issues, it's
going to be difficult to make headway,'' said Murkowski.
   ``I suggested it is time to invite the ICRC to come into Vietnam
and examine the area intensely, and satisfy themselves and issue a
report.''
   A total of 2,400 Americans are listed as missing in Indochina as
a result of the Vietnam War. Of that number, 1,762 are listed as
missing in Vietnam.
   All told, the remains of 156 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States and subsequently identified by the laboratory
since the end of the war.
   On Wednesday, Thach met retired Gen. John Vessey at the U.S.
Mission to discuss Americans missing in action.
   U.S. officials said they could give no details of the meeting.
   
   Vessey is President Reagan's special envoy to Vietnam on
prisoners of war, MIAs, re-education camp inmates and other
questions. He and Thach have met in Vietnam and agreed to work
toward solution of problems left over from the war.
</TEXT>
