<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Terrorism-Summit     06-10 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorism-Summit,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Sees Weakening of European Pressure on Libya</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some European governments are easing their
pressure on Libya and thereby encouraging its leader, Moammar
Gadhafi, to resume his international terror campaign, the top U.S.
counterterrorism official said Friday.
   Ambassador L. Paul Bremer told a congressional hearing that at
the forthcoming seven-nation economic summit in Toronto, the United
States would stress to its allies the need to continue the
international isolation against Gadhafi.
   ``Evidence has emerged indicating that some European governments
are weakening their resolve to keep the pressure on Libya,'' Bremer
said in remarks prepared for testimony before the Senate
Appropriations Committee.
   He did not elaborate, but U.S. officials have noted that
European oil companies recently have renewed their exploration
projects in Libya, and that British business executives have
returned to live there.
   ``We know the governments can't control private business, but
these kind of actions realy send Gadhafi the wrong signal,'' said
one official who spoke only on condition he not be named.
   The number of terrorist attacks in 1988 ``is up significantly''
from 1987, Bremer said. ``We are deeply concerned by an upsurge in
Iranian terrorism and recent evidence that Libya is becoming more
active as a sponsor of terrorism.''
   Although Libyan sponsorship of terrorism declined sharply after
the U.S. air raid on Libya in April 1986 and the Western economic
sanctions imposed that year, Libyan agents and surrogates are
active throughout the world, Bremer said. The surrogates include
the Japanese Red Army and the Palestinian Abu Nidal group, which is
based in the Libyan capital of Tripoli, he said.
   The leaders of the world's major industrialized countries
pledged last year at their summit in Venice, Italy, to combat
terrorism.
   ``We expect our friends and allies to live up to that commitment
and will advocate this'' in Toronto, Bremer said.
   Other U.S. officials say the summitteers probably will focus
their discussions on efforts to secure international aviation
against terrorism. They say several paragraphs on the subject will
be included in a joint political communique to be issued during the
summit, which takes place June 19-21.
   The question of air safety has become particularly pressing in
view of several recent hijackings and bombings, notably North
Korea's bombing of a Korean Airlines jet last year in which 115
people were killed.
   U.S. officials are concerned that North Korea may try to disrupt
the Olympic Games in Seoul, South Korea, in September, Bremer said.
   The United States has been providing training and sharing
intelligence with South Korea and other governments to reduce the
chance of such attacks, he said.
   ``To help prevent a terrorist incident either at or en route to
the Seoul Olympics, the United States and South Korea are
co-hosting a regional aviation security conference at the end of
this month'' in Seoul, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
