<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Alexander-Veep     06-10 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alexander-Veep,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alexander Ready for University But Wouldn't Reject Veep Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional profiles of vice presidential
prospects</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, ready
to step into new duties as a university president, says he's an
unlikely choice for the No. 2 spot on the national Republican
ticket. But he's willing to change his plans if George Bush asks.
   Like everyone else on the veep lists, Alexander says he isn't
seeking the job. But he's thought about the possibility and is
frank in his assessment:
   ``It's hard to want, impossible to seek, and virtually
impossible to turn down.''
   Alexander has had time to think about such matters.
   The day after leaving the governor's office in 1986, he and his
family _ his wife Honey and four children _ packed up and moved to
Australia for six months. The kids went to school and Alexander
just hung out, thinking.
   ``People couldn't believe it: `The others are running for
president and you're running for the other side of the world,''' he
said. ``I just went to be there with my family and think about what
I wanted to do next.''
   He has written a book about the hiatus. Called ``Six Months
Off,'' it is being published this summer.
   Alexander, a two-term governor who emphasized education during
his administration, is well known to his fellow governors _
including Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, the likely Democratic
presidential nominee.
   He's often mentioned among the potential vice presidential
running mates for Bush, who has consulted with Alexander while
trying to fill out the programs to back his oft-stated goal of
becoming ``the education president.''
   Alexander's terms as governor, and his stint as chairman of the
National Governors' Association, were marked by activism. He
acknowledges the contrast with Republican-led efforts to reduce
government on the national level, but says states must step into
the gap.
   ``I've tried to be a preacher of the rest of the Republican
message,'' he said.
   ``I've always believed many Southern Republicans have gotten so
fascinated with the Washington message, which is usually put the
harness on government, they've forgotten the rest of the Republican
message, which is what needs to be done ought to be done locally,''
Alexander said. ``That's sort of been my philosophy, and it's been
very activist.''
   Alexander recently was named president of the University of
Tennessee, and he begins his new job July 1, two days before he
turns 48. Although he told university trustees he was leaving
partisan politics behind, he also told them the vice presidency was
a possibility that he couldn't turn down.
   ``If I were asked, I would accept it,'' Alexander said in a
recent interview, recounting what he told the university officials.
   ``I genuinely don't expect it. I think it's an extremely remote
possibility,'' he said. ``I think almost anybody who was asked
would accept it.''
   Two years ago, Dukakis was picked the most effective governor in
a survey of governors by Newsweek magazine. Second-place finisher
in that balloting was Alexander _ although two-thirds of the
governors at that time were Democrats.
   A former Democratic governor, Charles Robb of Virginia,
acknowledged Alexander's return from Australia last summer: ``We
all hoped that he would stay there. He makes Democrats nervous.''
   A lawyer, he got his start in politics working for Howard Baker,
then a senator from Tennessee, and he worked as an aide in the
Nixon White House. He ran for governor in 1974 and lost, but won
four years later and became the first Tennessean to serve eight
consecutive years in the office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
