<DOCNO> AP880610-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea-Reax     06-10 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea-Reax,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Koreans Disapprove of Students' Move For Unification Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most South Koreans reacted with anger
Friday to plans by radical students to march to communist North
Korea for unification talks. The critics included some who backed
pro-democracy riots last summer.
   ``I supported them when they fought for democracy last year. But
this time, I simply don't understand them,'' said the owner of a
small bakery near Yonsei University in Seoul, where thousands of
students battled riot police.
   Coughing and sneezing in his bakery filled with drifting tear
gas, he termed reunification ``a stupid idea'' and called the
students ``simply crazy.''
   ``Students are not politicians. Such contact should be made in
an orderly manner through the government,'' said the shopkeeper,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Few South Koreans support or sympathize with the radical
students' call for talks with North Korean students to reunite the
peninsula, which was divided at the end of World War II.
   ``Let them go to the North and live there for a few months. They
need to learn by experience what is good and bad,'' said Chung
Soon-im, a 38-year-old homemaker.
   A uniformed army captain interviewed in a subway said: ``I would
like to shoot them. They are too naive or idiots.''
   President Roh Tae-woo, who took office Feb. 25 after elections
in December, has liberalized debate on unification but said the
government, not students, should lead any dialogue with North Korea.
   South Korean students, traditionally a major political force,
played a key role in nationwide public protests last summer that
led to sweeping democratic reforms, including direct presidential
elections.
   The radical students are a very small but loud minority.
   Government officials say they account for just 2 percent to 3
percent of the country's 1 million students. About 41 million
people live in South Korea.
   ``I do agree that the students have the right to meet their
North Korean friends. It would help ease the bitter rivalry between
the two sides,'' dissident Buddhist monk Song Kwan said after a
rally at Yonsei University on Friday.
   Another dissident leader, Moon Ik-hwan, told students at the
rally, ``The Roh Tae-woo regime has neither capability nor will to
push national unification. I support the student talks.''
   About 4,000 students, clenched fists in the air, rose in wild
cheers and sang a song, titled ``Our Lifelong Wish Is Unification.''
   They demanded permission to march to the border village of
Panmunjom for the unification talks. South Korea banned the march
as a national security threat.
   The students are also demanding that North Korea be a co-host of
September's Olympic Games in Seoul as a step toward reunification
and that the 42,000 U.S. troops stationed in South Korea withdraw.
   Many intellectuals have said the activism could backfire. They
point out that the military staged a coup in 1961 after radical
students called for similar unification talks with North Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
