<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthKorea Bjt   06-10 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea, Bjt,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Police Block Student Unification March To North Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police firing tear gas blocked
thousands of students Friday who tried to march to communist North
Korea for reunification talks. Radicals hurled rocks and firebombs,
trying to fight their way through.
   About 60,000 riot police blanketed the South Korean capital and
roads leading north to disperse students trying to reach the border
30 miles away. Fierce street clashes erupted at Yonsei University
as about 5,000 screaming students tried to fight their way out.
   An estimated 8,000 troopers surrounding the school fired
hundreds of tear gas bombs into the charging students. Both sides
hurled rocks and bricks.
   Police and protesters with skin burns or wounds streaming blood
staggered or were carried to safety. Authorities didn't say how
many people were injured.
   North Korea's Korean Central News Agency said in a report
monitored in Tokyo that delegates and students from the North
waited at the truce village of Panmunjom for the southern students.
   Ko Ung Sam, head of the delegation, was quoted as saying, ``The
responsibility for the failure of the talks rests entirely with the
U.S. imperialists and the South Korean rulers.''
   Police and press reports indicated at least 700 students were
arrested in various parts of South Korea. Most detainees were
expected to be held briefly.
   Radical students _ who government officials say account for just
2 percent to 3 percent of the nation's 1 million students _ called
the march to force reunification of the communist North and the
pro-Western South.
   The radicals claim the United States, which has 42,000 troops in
South Korea, enforces partition to rule the South. The protests
were vehemently anti-American.
   ``Let's go and meet our brothers from the North!'' the students
at Yonsei yelled, beating drums and singing revolutionary songs.
``Yankee go home!'' yelled others. ``Skin the Yankee imperialists!''
   ``We call for struggle of the masses for unification and against
dictatorship!'' a speaker shouted as students cheered.
   Riot troopers hit by firebombs screamed in agony as other
officers frantically beat out the flames. Students wielding clubs
attacked police who tried to ward off blows with riot shields.
   A dozen armored police vans with multiple tear gas launchers
fired barrages of gas bombs to hold back attacking protesters as
police martial arts squads attacked. Students tried to immobilize
the vans with firebombs and clubs.
   Students in nearby sidestreets tried to attack police from
behind and stationed themselves on several high rooftops.
   Clashes broke out in at least six provincial cities as students
supporting the march clashed with police. Dozens of students were
arrested at bus and train stations as they tried to reach Seoul for
the march.
   At Seoul's railway station, thousands of riot police threw tear
gas grenades to break up crowds of students trying to get to trains
to the border. Some students hurled rocks and firebombs, but most
did not fight back.
   The police detained hundreds of students, beating and kicking
detainees as they dragged them away. Students had blood streaming
from their faces.
   Their attempts to assemble in various parts of Seoul failed
repeatedly. About 4,000 students who staged a sit-down strike in
the north of Seoul were dispersed by charging police firing tear
gas.
   Riot squads guarded train and bus stations to stop students from
getting to Panmunjom, in the demilitarized zone. About 40 students
who sneaked through were arrested near the border, which is
off-limits to civilians.
   Large detachments of riot police stood guard at intersections
and along main streets in Seoul. Riot squads surrounded government
buildings and U.S. diplomatic facilities to prevent attacks.
   Many onlookers criticized the protesters, saying they were
leftists or fools who would help the communist North conquer the
South.
   ``Let them go to the North and live there for a few months,''
said Chung Soon-im, a 38-year-old homemaker. ``They need to learn
by experience what is good and bad.''
   A uniformed army captain said: ``I would like to shoot them.
They are too naive or idiots.''
   Most South Koreans want reunification with the North but fear
the North is determined eventually to conquer the South.
   North Korea invaded the South in 1950 to launch the Korean War
and the two nations remain bitter enemies with no ties or contacts.
   The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, deny
they are communists and insist reunfication overrides ideological
considerations.
</TEXT>
