<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-PlaneBombing     06-10 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Plane Bombing,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Say North Korean Linked To Plane Bombing Likely To Be
Pardoned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Korean woman who said she
planted a bomb aboard a South Korean jetliner may be pardoned after
the Olympic Games in Seoul, newspapers reported Friday.
   The woman, Kim Hyon Hui, could be pardoned even if she were
found guilty, because she cooperated in the government's
investigation of the November 1987 bombing, the newspapers said.
   The reports, carried in all the city's daily papers, quoted a
prosecution source but did not give the source's name. They said
local and international laws against terrorism mandate a trial for
Kim, who acknowledged her role in the bombing of the Korean Air
jetliner.
   All 115 people aboard were killed.
   ``Strong public sentiment and concerned local and international
laws make it inevitable to try the woman after the Olympics,'' the
newspapers quoted the source as saying.
   The South Korean government has decided to delay Kim's trial
until after the Olympics to avoid a possible adverse impact on the
Games, the reports said. A record 161 countries are scheduled to
take part in the Games, which run from Sept. 17 to Oct. 2.
   Kim, 25, told a news conference in Seoul in January that she and
a male North Korean agent planted a bomb aboard the jetliner, which
disappeared off Burma on Nov. 29.
   Kim said they bombed the jetliner on orders from North Korean
leaders to disrupt the Olympic Games. North Korea has denied
involvement.
   The North Korean couple, passengers on an earlier part of the
flight from Baghdad, Iraq, to Seoul, got off the plane in Bahrain.
They took poison before being questioned at Bahrain Airport. The
man died, but Kim survived and was sent to Seoul in December.
</TEXT>
