<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SexStrangling     06-10 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Strangling,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Gets Maximum Sentence in Girlfriend's Strangulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a case that echoed the ``rough sex''
defense of the ``preppie killing'' trial, a teen-ager who strangled
his girlfriend was sentenced today to up to four years in prison,
the most he could have received.
   Joseph Porto, 19, had been found guilty of criminally negligent
homicide in the death of Kathleen Holland, 17, whom he said he
strangled in a sex act gone awry.
   In sentencing Porto to one and one-third to four years in
prison, Nassau County Court Judge John Thorp Jr. said, ``The
punishment does not fit the crime.''
   Porto's attorney, Barry Slotnick, who represented subway gunman
Bernhard Goetz, had asked the judge to give his client probation.
   He later called the sentence excessive and said he would seek to
have the verdict and sentence overturned.
   Porto showed no outward sign of emotion when the sentence was
announced.
   In asking for the maximum sentence, prosectutor Kenneth Littman
said, ``The probation report paints a picture of a self-centered,
arrogant and spoiled young man who acts impulsively and
aggressively toward young women.''
   He said officers detected no remorse in Porto and in fact said,
``Porto smirked during the entire interview with probation
officers.''
   Porto, of Bayville, was charged with second-degree murder after
he confessed in writing and on videotape to strangling Miss Holland
on Sept. 27, 1986, when she tried to end their nine-month
relationship.
   In his confession, Porto said he used his hands and a high
school graduation tassel to choke the teen-ager to death. He
recanted the confession during his April trial and, like the
``preppie killing'' defendant Robert Chambers, said Miss Holland
died accidentally while they were having sex.
   Porto told the jury he tied a rope around Miss Holland's neck to
heighten her sexual pleasure and apparently yanked too hard in the
heat of passion.
   The jury acquitted him of murder and manslaughter charges while
finding him guilty of the lesser charge.
   Porto's defense was offered shortly after Chambers, who was
charged with murdering teen-ager Jennifer Levin during a 1986
sexual tryst in Central Park, claimed he accidentally killed her
during rough sex.
   Chambers interrupted his trial and pleaded guilty to a lesser
charge of first-degree manslaughter.
</TEXT>
