<DOCNO> AP880610-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     06-10 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Officials Cautiously Optimistic About Aug. 31 Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major elements are coming together
for the first space shuttle mission in 2{ years but critical
milestones lie ahead on the road to an August launch, shuttle
officials reported Friday.
   ``The August target is optimistic, for sure, but given where we
are today, we've got a shot at it,'' launch director Bob Sieck said.
   ``We're getting close and there's a feeling of excitement
here,'' said astronaut Bob Crippen, deputy director of shuttle
operations, who will make the final decision on whether Discovery
is launched on the first post-Challenger mission, now set for Aug.
31.
   Sieck and Crippen addressed a news conference on the day two
major parts for the Discovery flight were joined in an assembly
building _ the huge external fuel tank and the two solid fuel
booster rockets.
   Engineers next week will complete a major overhaul job on
Discovery and will mate the spacecraft with the tank and boosters.
   Transfer of the spaceship to the launch pad is set for June 25.
   ``That will be the most tangible evidence to us that a launch is
near,'' Sieck said.
   A key test is set for July 18 when Discovery's three main liquid
fuel engines are fired with the shuttle bolted firmly to the pad.
The 20-second ignition will evaluate modifications made to the
power plant and provide countdown experience for the launch team.
   Full scale test firings of the redesigned solid fuel booster
rockets are scheduled for next Tuesday and on July 26 at the Morton
Thiokol plant in Utah.
   All three tests must be completed successfully and evaluated
before Discovery can be committed to flight.
   ``We'll get through these milestones and then we'll look at the
launch date,'' Sieck said.
   A faulty joint in one of the 126-foot booster rockets allowed
flame to escape and destroy Challenger and its seven-person crew in
a fiery explosion on Jan. 28, 1986.
   Crippen said that once the tests are complete and a firm date
has been set, National Aeronautics and Space Administration
officials must clear another major hurdle _ a flight readiness
review scheduled two weeks before liftoff.
   ``That meeting will be the culmination of many earlier meetings
and decisions and will decide if we are ready to fly,'' Crippen
said.
   Two days before launch, Crippen's mission management team will
convene to evaluate weather, hardware, software and other elements
and decide whether the final countdown should start.
   At nine minutes before liftoff, with a planned hold called for
in the count, Crippen will call for a go-no-go decisions from Sieck
and other officials.
   ``I will make the commitment whether to proceed at T-minus-nine
minutes,'' Crippen said. ``I assure you we'll be certain it's as
safe as possible before we go.''
   The commander of the flight is Frederick H. Hauck, and the pilot
is Richard O. Covey. Also on the four-day flight are mission
specialists John M. Lounge, George D. Nelson and David C. Hilmers.
   Their chief objective is to deploy a NASA communications
satellite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
