<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-10 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ACME, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cherry farmer Dave Amon found making a profit
wasn't as easy as pie, so he came up with a few innovative ways to
make the cherry pay despite crop gluts and falling prices.
   Visitors to his farm can buy cherry mustard, cherry barbecue
sauce, cherry hot pepper jelly, cherry dressing and cherry dessert
sauce.
   Amon has managed to transform his 400-acre farm in the northwest
region of Michigan's Lower Peninsula into a tourist attraction,
enticing an estimated 65,000 visitors a year to take home some of
his cherry-based products.
   ``Each year I have to put my visitor's hat on and think about
what would turn me on,'' Amon said.
   In his fields, you can pick your own cherries, take a tour on
his ``fruitmobile,'' buy pumpkins in the fall and Christmas trees
in December. In the winter, you can even ski his groomed trails.
   ``We are in the cherry capital of the world and it wasn't too
long ago when all you could get was a piece of cherry pie or maybe
a cherry decoration on your meal,'' said Keith Charters, owner of
the Music House Museum and chairman of the area's convention bureau
board.
   Michigan is the country's No. 1 producer of tart cherries and
fourth leading grower of sweet cherries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professors and students got a chance to
take a few good whacks at a temporary classroom structure that was
revered by none, but reviled by all at Fresno State University.
   Faculty and students regarded the San Ramon I building as a
noisy claptrap that was too hot in the summer and too cold in the
winter. And, they say, it was just plain ugly.
   So, when the time came to tear down the structure built two
decades ago on the campus 200 miles south of San Francisco, plenty
of volunteer demolitionists showed up.
   About a dozen professors, administrators and students used
sledgehammers to attack the building Thursday before a professional
wrecking crew completed the job.
   Student Robert Petrucci even brought a 3-foot pipe wrench to get
``the last vengeance.'' Petrucci said the noise problem in the
building was so bad that ``you could hear people sneeze three
classrooms down.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angler Craig Merchant's battle with a
quillback carpsucker won't qualify as a great moment in fishing
history.
   He says the fish didn't fight, he wasn't trying to catch it, and
he didn't know what it was when he did.
   But as the world will soon know, Merchant's quillback carpsucker
_ a fish that truly looks like its name and smells worse _ was
something special.
   Apparently, it's the biggest quillback carpsucker ever caught.
   The 22{-inch, 6-pound, 14-ounce fish has been confirmed as a
state record and is expected to meet quick approval for the world
record from the Freshwater Fishing Hall of Fame in Wisconsin,
Michigan Department of Natural Resources spokeswoman Patricia
Merrick said Thursday.
   The fish was caught April 30 in the Kalamzoo River northwest of
Kalamazoo in southwestern Michigan. Merchant, a 43-year-old
toolmaker from nearby Wayland, said he almost threw the fish back
because he didn't know what it was.
   ``I thought it was just an old trash fish from a dirty old
river,'' Merchant said. ``I was fishing for walleye.''
   The previous world record quillback carpsucker, 5 pounds, 12
ounces, came from Lake St. Clair, near Detroit, in 1982. Merrick
said the bony, bottom-feeding fish averages one to two pounds.
</TEXT>
