<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NaziBar     06-10 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi Bar,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial `Nazi Bar' Gets New Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of Bangkok's ``Nazi Bar''
renamed the nightspot following strong objections from several
foreigners, the manager said Friday.
   Owners replaced caricatures of Adolf Hitler, photos of Nazi
storm troopers and cartoons of Italian Fascist leader Benito
Mussolini with racing posters when the pub was renamed ``No Name''
on Wednesday.
   The name was changed, manager Aor Sarayuk said, ``to make
everybody happy.''
   ``We don't want to offend even a few people, so we're
experimenting with a new, neutral name and decor,'' Aor said in a
telephone interview.
   Some foreigners had complained in the pub and in letters to the
English-language Bangkok Post that the name glamorized Hitler's
brutal regime in Germany before and during World War II. But Aor
said Thai patrons remained unconcerned.
   Aor earlier said he and his business partners focused on the
Nazi theme because of ``its powerful, catchy and emotive appeal.''
Waiters in the bar, which opened in early May, wore swastika
armbands.
   The new decor features racing cars, including Ferraris and
Porsches.
   ``Not many people object to cars,'' Aor said.
</TEXT>
