<DOCNO> AP880610-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0527 06-10 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Tries To Show Financial Reporting Procedure Hard to
Understand</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with start of testimony today,
picking up 3rd graf pvs, ``It was ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense in former Gov. Evan Mecham's
criminal trial tried to establish in testimony today that Arizona's
campaign financial reporting procedure can be difficult for
candidates to understand.
   Mecham and his brother Willard, his 1986 campaign treasurer,
face felony charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan on
financial reports required by the state.
   Secretary of State Jim Shumway testified that his office would
advise a campaign to seek legal help if it asked how to report a
loan that was backed by promissory notes, such as the loan from
developer Barry Wolfson.
   Under questioning by Willard Mecham's lawyer, Joe Keilp, Shumway
said his office does not provide instructions on how to fill out
all of the required reports.
   Prosecutor Michael Cudahy objected as Keilp asked Shumway
whether his office had been working recently with other state
officials to revise the law.
   Cudahy also objected when Keilp referred several times to a
meeting Evan Mecham sought with Shumway in October 1987, after the
$350,000 loan was revealed by the news media. Judge Michael Ryan of
Maricopa County Superior Court ruled Thursday that testimony on the
meeting was inadmissible because any advice Mecham sought at the
time was irrelevant to his intent in filing his financial
statements months earlier.
   On Thursday, former top Mecham aide Edith Richardson testified
that the loan was well known among his inner circle.
   Mrs. Richardson said that she learned, probably early in 1987,
that developer Barry Wolfson had provided Mecham with the money.
   ``It was just common knowledge that there was a loan,'' Mrs.
Richardson, former special assistant to Mecham, told the Maricopa
County Superior Court jury.
   Mecham and his brother Willard, his 1986 campaign treasurer,
face felony charges of concealing the loan on financial statements
required by the state.
   Other witnesses in the trial have testified that they may have
had some general knowledge of a loan, but that they did not know
Wolfson was involved.
   Meanwhile, attorneys took a formal deposition Thursday from Gov.
Rose Mofford during a closed session at her home, but defense
lawyers later decided it will not be introduced as evidence. The
deposition was to be used in lieu of Mrs. Mofford's testimony in
court, because she still has been suffering ill effects from a mild
concussion she received in a recent fall.
   According to a tape recording of the deposition session, Mrs.
Mofford said she knew nothing about the Wolfson loan, about
Mecham's campaign and personal financial disclosure statements or
about the criminal case.
   Mecham is on trial on six felony counts of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents, and faces up to 22 years in
prison if convicted on all counts. His co-defendant and brother,
who served as campaign manager, is charged with three similar
counts and faces up to 9{ years in prison if convicted.
   The defense has contended that the $350,000 loan was properly
reported as part of a $465,000 lump sum listed as a contribution
from Mecham. The defense also has said the failure to itemize the
loan was an innocent mistake.
   Mecham, a Republican, took office in January 1987. He was
removed from office April 4 when the state Senate convicted him of
two unrelated impeachment counts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
