<DOCNO> AP880610-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HolocaustSurvivors     06-10 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holocaust Survivors,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Official Discusses East German Plan To Pay Victims Of Holocaust</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POTSDAM, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. official on Friday discussed
with East German leaders a plan that for the first time would
provide payments from this communist nation to Jewish victims of
the Nazi Holocaust.
   U.S. Deputy Secretary of State John Whitehead met with Foreign
Minister Oskar Fischer to discuss details of East German plan, made
public by the official ADN news agency on Wednesday.
   ``We welcome the announcement,'' Whitehead later told The
Associated Press.
   The ADN dispatch said East Germany was prepared to lend
``humanitarian aid'' to Jewish survivors of the Holocaust living
outside its borders.
   East German officials previously had argued that their nation,
which was formed in 1949, bore no legal or moral responsibility for
the actions of Adolf Hitler's Third Reich.
   The news agency did not specify the amount of the payments.
Whitehead said Friday that the amount ``is currently being
discussed.''
   On Monday, Heinz Galanski, chairman of the West German Jewish
Council, said East Germany was prepared to pay up to $100 million
to Holocaust victims.
   Whitehead that he and Fischer would meet again to discuss the
issue within the next few days.
   ``We hope this matter can be resolved in the near future,''
Whitehead said.
   More than 6 million Jews were killed under Nazi rule.
   In 1952, the Luxembourg Agreement covering reparations was
signed by the World Jewish Congress and West Germany, but not by
East Germany.
   Since then, West Germany has paid more than 80 billion marks _
worth $48 billion in today's currency exchange _ to Holocaust
survivors.
   Whitehead indicated that there was an urgency in providing the
additional aid.
   ``It is a tragic situation (the plight of Holocaust survivors)
because the victims, if you think about it, are now quite elderly.
There are only a small number of them left,'' Whitehead said.
   Whitehead said talks on the issue also would continue with East
German officials in Washington.
   Whitehead and Fischer are attending a three-day conference on
East-West security issues in Potsdam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
