<HEAD>Four Dead in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with four dead, men from Panhandle, other
details</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ELGIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane crashed nose-down in a
field near this central Texas town today after losing radio and
radar contact with air controllers. All four men on board were
killed, authorities said.
   The flight was believed to have originated in the Texas
Panhandle and was bound for Austin, about 25 miles west of the
crash site, authorities said.
   The plane flipped over and crashed nose-down, said Con Keirsey,
Bastrop County deputy sheriff. The propeller was buried in the
earth.
   Three of the victims were from Perryton, about 110 miles
northeast of Amarillo, and a fourth victim was from nearby Booker,
said Ochiltree County sheriff's spokeswoman Judy Guinn. The four
were identified as businessmen but their names were not released,
pending notification of their families.
   The downed plane was discovered at 8:51 a.m. by a Department of
Public Safety helicopter on a training mission from Austin, said
agency spokesman Mike Cox said.
   Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Mitch Barker said the
plane was on an instrument landing approach to Austin when radio
and radar contact was lost.
   The helicopter pilot told ground crews the plane appeared to
have hit the gound at a severe angle, authorities said.
   ``All you could see was a crumpled up plane,'' said Bobby Dodds,
who lives about a mile north of the crash site.
</TEXT>
