<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Veep-Graham     06-10 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veep-Graham,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Senator Could Offer Enthusiastic Campaign Style</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional stories on vice presidential
prospects; moved earlier for PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They differ on why, but friends and foes of Florida
Sen. Bob Graham agree on one thing _ he's a political winner.
   ``Graham's a phenomenon,'' said Charles Black, a Republican
consultant who helped run then-Sen. Paula Hawkins' unsuccessful
1986 re-election bid against Graham. ``He is not what you call a
charismatic personality, but he's a public relations genius.''
   ``Bob Graham has managed to survive in Florida because he has
some of the attributes, the personal skills, of Ronald Reagan,''
added J.M. ``Mac'' Stipanovich, chief adviser to Republican Gov.
Bob Martinez. ``He is able to communicate very well with the mass
public, symbolically and physically. He is very skilled at
convincing everybody he's on their side.''
   The first-term senator is on most lists of potential Democratic
running mates for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, although
Graham's brief Washington tenure could work against him.
Conventional wisdom would point the governor in the direction of
someone with long experience in the nation's capital.
   Graham also has some serious policy disagreements with Dukakis.
For example, he is known for vigorous enforcement of the death
penalty, signing more than 150 death warrants while 16 executions
were carried out, and for support of military aid to the Nicaraguan
Contras. Dukakis opposes both.
   Among his advantages, Graham would give Dukakis a strong
opportunity to carry electoral giant Florida, which Graham governed
for eight years.
   Graham has solid ``New South'' progressive credentials and his
years as governor saw major education and environmental programs.
   While Graham isn't an exciting speaker, he's proven to be a
tireless, enthusiastic campaigner given to singing and poking fun
at himself. He was a star attraction at annual Florida press corps
skits in which Graham did take-offs on rock music stars and Latin
dictators.
   He built his uphill gubernatorial campaign in 1978 around ``100
Workdays,'' spending a day each at 100 jobs including Hialeah
stable boy, tomato picker, garbage man, bellboy, and chicken parts
processor. The workdays have continued monthly.
   ``He'll go on stage in boxer shorts or paint his face and put on
a headdress,'' Stipanovich recalled. ``In that way he would be a
good counterweight to Dukakis.''
   On the campaign trail, it's often easy to forget that Graham is
a Harvard-educated lawyer and multimillionaire whose family made a
fortune in land development and dairy cattle. His late father,
Ernest, ran successfully for state senator in 1936, the year Graham
was born, and his half-brother, Philip Graham, ran The Washington
Post and was a major Democratic power broker until his suicide in
1963.
   Graham has been a low-key senator. Quietly, he has been active
in Latin American policy and often meets with Reagan administration
officials and leading Democratic colleagues on those issues. He
recently completed a three-nation tour of South America and
returned with detailed knowledge of the complex Latin debt problem,
displayed at a Washington news conference that some reporters
admitted went over their heads.
   Graham suggested that Florida _ which Dukakis called ``a
bellwether state'' before winning its March 8 primary _ is a key
state for Democrats, who have seen only Lyndon Johnson and Jimmy
Carter carry it in the last four decades.
   Democrats still hold a 3-2 lead in registered voters, but the
state has been a challenge to campaign strategists because of its
mix of traditional southern Democratic conservatives in the north,
Reaganites along its Gulf Coast, northeastern liberals along
southeastern Florida, and large blocs of Hispanics and senior
citizens.
   ``If a campaign can be constructed that will carry Florida, that
almost assures that Dukakis will carry the country,'' Graham said.
``If you carry Florida, that means that a Democrat has broad enough
appeal to win anywhere.''
   Although he has indicated he would be interested in
consideration by Dukakis, Graham plays down the possibility.
   ``It's very flattering to be included on a list of some people I
admire _ Sam Nunn, John Glenn, Lloyd Bentsen and the others _ but
I'm not going to be affected by that,'' Graham said. ``I'm looking
forward to the challenges of the Senate. That's where I anticipate
that I will be the next several years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
