<DOCNO> AP880610-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1537EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pee-WeeArt     06-10 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pee-Wee Art,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Pee-Wee's Playhouse' Artist Puts Stuff on Display</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PA1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``You know one of those picture-drawing
guys who thought up the stuff at my place, `Pee-wee's Playhouse,'
like the talking chair and weird puppets and stuff?
   ``Yeah, well, he draws weird stuff for grown-ups, too, but I
think kids like it, too. You can take your mom and dad to see it at
this place in Pepsi-Cola, Fla. Neat, huh?''
   Wait a minute, Pee Wee, that's Pensacola, and the stuff Gary
Panter draws and sculpts is art. It's on display at his first
one-man show through July 16 at the Pensacola Museum of Art.
   But you're right, it is a bit weird.
   The 37-year-old New York artist is one of three people who
design sets for the popular children's television show starring
Paul Reubens, better known as Pee-wee Herman, with the cherry lips,
bow tie and squeaky voice.
   Panter also designs Pee-wee toys and says he'll probably do more
``Pee-wee stuff.'' But he wants to be known for more.
   ``As fun as Pee-wee is, it's not as fun as just painting a
picture,'' Panter said in an interview with the Pensacola News
Journal published Friday.
   ``Everything kind of comes out of painting for me, but modern
art painting theory is so broad you can do anything and call it
painting,'' said Panter, who also has designed album covers for
Frank Zappa and others.
   The show exhibits 22 pieces diverse both in subject and style:
cartoon animals, primitive buffaloes, dinosaur sculptures,
psychedelic murals and simple line pieces.
   They range in size from ``Cookie Company,'' a mural occupying an
entire wall, to ``Dinosaur,'' a 15-inch tall sculpture that would
fit in Pee-wee's toy box.
   Director Mary Takach said the museum occasionally likes to show
works by up-and-coming contemporary artists and chose Panter partly
because of his association with Reubens.
   Panter says he has been inspired by a range of sources including
Picasso, Andy Warhol and Walt Disney. His goal, he said, is to
bring art to ``where it doesn't belong, trying to bridge the gap
between fine art and commercial art.''
   ``It's like when you're driving out in the jungle or somewhere
and you come across a big Smurf sign,'' he said. ``It's really
neat.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
