<HEAD>Duderstadt Named President of University of Michigan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James J. Dukerstadt was named president
of the University of Michigan by the school's board of regents
Friday.
   Duderstadt, university's provost and vice president for academic
affairs since 1986, becomes the school's 11th president Sept. 1.
   His appointment ends a selection process that began after Harold
Shapiro announced in April 1987 that he was leaving Michigan to
become president of Princeton University. Shapiro assumed that post
Jan. 1.
   Duderstadt, 45, graduated from Yale University in 1964 with a
bachelor's degree in electrical engineering. At the California
Institute of Technology, he earned a master's degree in 1965 and a
doctorate in engineering science and physics in 1967.
   Duderstadt joined Michigan in 1969 as an assistant professor of
nuclear engineering. He also was dean of the College of Engineering.
