<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zambia-Bomb     06-10 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zambia-Bomb,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Injured in Bomb and Machine Gun Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb ripped through a house near the
home of officials of the guerrilla-backed African National
Congress, injuring a 12-year-old girl in an adjacent building,
police said Friday.
   Police said the attack occurred Thursday night in the Libala
suburb. They said the home also was hit with machine gun fire.
   Residents in the neighborhood said the blast and machine gun
attack demolished part of the house and shattered the windows of
nearby buildings.
   The injured girl was cut by flying glass, police said. She was
treated at the main hospital in Lusaka. There were no other
injuries.
   It was not immediately known how many occupants were in the
house at the time of the attack.
   Witnesses said the front walls were peppered with bullet holes.
The house was sealed off by police Friday as forensic experts
sifted through the debris, they said.
   The African National Congress is the main guerrilla group
fighting white domination in South Africa and trying to overthrow
the South African government. It maintains its external
headquarters in Lusaka.
   In the past, Pretoria has been blamed for bombings and commando
attacks on ANC houses and offices in Zambia and neighboring
black-ruled nations.
   The ANC declined to comment on the attack Friday. ANC spokesman
Tom Sebina refused to identify the senior ANC officials that local
residents said used a nearby house in Libala.
</TEXT>
