<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Volunteers     06-10 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Volunteers,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Gets Earful From 91-Year-Old Award Winner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Friday presented the first
annual Ronald Reagan Award for Volunteer Excellence to a feisty
91-year-old woman from Jacksonville, Fla., who chided him about his
jokes.
   The presentation climaxed a luncheon at which the president gave
awards for volunteer action to 18 individuals and organizations.
   After Reagan finished giving the regular awards, Bobby Trimble
of Midland, Texas, who received an award at the first such luncheon
in 1982, announced establishment of the Reagan award.
   Trimble said future presidents will select the winner, but in
this case the winner was chosen by leaders of volunteer
organizations in order to keep the creation of the award a secret.
   The winner was Arnolta Williams, a leader in the Jacksonville
black community who has engaged in a variety of volunteer
activities and been credited with helping smooth the way to
peaceful racial integration there.
   After saying how honored he was to give the award to Mrs.
Williams, the president said he would like to stay all afternoon,
but, ``Nancy tells me I've got to help her with the dishes.''
   ``Don't you make another joke like that,'' Mrs. Williams cracked.
   ``Mama Williams,'' said the president, ``that may not be as much
a joke as you think. One of the best jobs I ever had was when I was
in college washing dishes in the girls' dormitory.''
   ``That was before you were married,'' Mrs. Williams said.
   ``Yes,'' said Reagan.
   The winners in addition to Mrs. Williams were:
   _Kaye Kiker, York, Ala., founder of Alabamians for a Clean
Environment.
   _SHARE, Inc., of Los Angeles, an organization of women in the
entertainment industry who raise funds for nonprofit organizations.
   _Operation Comeback, Orlando, Fla., which assists troubled
adolescents referred to Juvenile Court.
   _Verlyn R. and Martha J. Roskam, Glen Ellyn, Ill., founder of an
organization that solicits contributed goods from companies and
gives them to colleges in return for scholarships.
   _The 1987 International Summer Special Olympics Committee Inc.,
South Bend, Ind., which helps mentally retarded athletes.
   _Red River Revel Arts Festival, Shreveport, La., an annual event
since 1976.
   _Roberta R. Roper of Upper Marlboro, Md., who has worked for the
rights of victims of crime since her college-age daughter was
kidnapped and murdered six years ago.
   _First Bank System Community First Program, St. Paul, Minn., a
program to encourage employees to participate in volunteer work.
   _Thomas W. Evans, a New York attorney who developed a program to
expose high school students to the workings of the law.
   _Zachary Fisher of New York, who has led in development of the
USS Intrepid as a sea-air-space museum in New York harbor.
   _Time Inc., Time to Read, New York, a tutoring program using
corporate and community volunteers.
   _Mission Air Ministries, Charlotte, N.C., which provides air
transportation to patients who cannot afford the air fare to
hospitals and medical centers.
   _Barberton Council of Labor Free Clinic Development Project,
Barberton, Ohio, a free medical clinic for residents of a community
with 33 percent unemployment.
   _Margaret A. Gallimore, Dallas, a nurse who has provided a home
for 20 people with AIDS since 1987.
   _Dr. Luis A.N. Gomez, El Paso, Texas, who assists people
suffering from leprosy in Juarez, Mexico.
   _Robert Mosbacher Jr., Houston, Texas, co-charman of the Houston
Committee for Private Sector Initiatives.
   _Harriet H. Hodges, Seoul, South Korea, who helps indigent
Korean children with heart problems.
</TEXT>
