<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryRecruiting     06-10 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Recruiting,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget Cuts Help Services Meet Enlistment Goals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military services easily met or exceeded
their recruiting goals during the first half of the fiscal year,
thanks in part to budget cuts that lowered their manpower goals,
the Pentagon said Friday.
   The Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps also reported
``excellent recruit quality,'' with the percentage of recruits
possessing a high school diploma increasing to 92 percent from 91
percent a year earlier, the Pentagon said.
   Nonetheless, ``concern remains for future recruiting
prospects,'' said Grant S. Green Jr., the assistant defense
secretary for personnel.
   ``This year's recruiting objectives are significantly below
those of last year. Had the services been recruiting to last year's
levels, this quality might not have been achieved.''
   Releasing its latest quarterly report, the Defense Department
said the four services signed up a combined 133,000 recruits during
the first six months of fiscal 1988, a period that ended March 31.
   That compares with a combined goal of 131,100, and all four
services met or exceeded their individual objectives.
   By comparison, during the same period in fiscal 1987, the
services had to sign up 150,900 recruits. The recruiting objectives
have been falling because the Pentagon plans to cut active-duty
strength by almost 36,000 this year to cope with budget cuts.
   On the re-enlistment side, ``several key statistics trailed
those achieved during the comparable period fiscal 1987,'' Green
said.
   ``The Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force reported first-term
re-enlistment rates several percentage points below last year's
second-quarter numbers. The department will continue monitoring
retention trends closely ....''
   The Pentagon pays particular attention to the percentage of men
and women willing to re-enlist after completing their initial
obligation, viewing it as a measure not only of military readiness
and experience in the force but also job satisfaction.
   During the first half of fiscal 1988, 54 percent of Navy
personnel eligible to re-enlist for the first time did so _ down
from 58 percent during the same period a year ago.
   Similarly, the first term re-enlistment numbers dropped for the
Marine Corps from 35 percent to 32 percent, and for the Air Force
from 67 percent to 56 percent.
   The Army managed to buck that trend, reporting that first-term
re-enlistments rose from 40 percent to 46 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
