<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL-Bakkers     06-10 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-Bakkers,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakkers Say They Don't Have Money But Have Plan to Buy PTL</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: `The finances is...' in 4th graf cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER BRYANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelists Jim and Tammy Bakker said
Friday they don't have the money to buy back PTL, but they're
preparing to submit a plan to the bankruptcy trustee that would
allow them to go on television and ``quite a bit else.''
   ``We don't have money in the bank. We haven't asked for people
to put money in the bank. We will launch a campaign, perhaps in the
next few days, to do some of that,'' Bakker said at a news
conference.
   He said he had promises of support from some businesses in Rock
Hill and Fort Mill, near PTL's Heritage USA headquarters, but he
wouldn't provide names.
   ``We have commitments from various people. The finances is not
the problem. This is a very spiritual problem,'' he said, without
elaborating.
   Bakker, who met privately on Thursday with bankruptcy trustee
M.C. ``Red'' Benton, said he's drawing up a proposal that would put
the PTL founders back on television.
   The Bakkers were forced off the air out of the $160 million
evangelical empire they founded in a sex and money scandal. They
stepped down in March 1987 after revelations that ministry money
was used to pay a church secretary, Jessica Hahn, to keep quiet
about a sexual encounter she had with Bakker. That was followed by
further revelations of a lavish lifestyle led by the Bakkers.
   ``We are preparing in the next 48 hours a plan to present to Mr.
Benton and that would include air time and quite a bit else,''
Bakker said.
   Asked if he would use the air time to raise money, Bakker said
he and his wife want to use most of the time helping people.
   ``My goal is to spend most of my time ministering. We have
something that we want to say. We've learned a lot over the last
year and five months. We want to spend time helping hurting people,
to help people that are going through similar situations,'' Bakker
said.
   ``Needless to say, we're going to have to have help to pay the
bills,'' he added.
   Thursday's meeting was Bakker's first detailed discussion with
Benton. The trustee told Bakker that if his presence proved
disruptive at Heritage USA, he would ``really lay down the law with
him.''
   Bakker has said he is raising money to buy back PTL, but has
declined to discuss details, saying God was giving him direction.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds is to rule Thursday on a
liquidation plan for the ministry that calls for most of its assets
to be sold, with the church and television studios to be leased
back by PTL.
   Mrs. Bakker, who underwent treatment for an addiction to
prescription drugs before the couple's departure from the ministry,
said she has not used drugs to cope with stress since their fall
from PTL.
   ``I haven't had a pill in a year and five months!'' she said.
``I made it totally, God and me. That was nice. It was good to be
able to do that.''
</TEXT>
