<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     06-10 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Fighting Kills Eight; U.N. Member Shot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Palestinian guerrilla factions
battled with mortars and machine guns in Beirut's two refugee camps
for a third day Friday. Police said eight people were killed and 50
wounded.
   One stray shell slammed into a crowded vegetable market near the
Chatilla camp at mid-afternoon, killing two people and wounding 31.
   The rest of the casualties occurred in overnight clashes between
PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction and the
dissident Fatah-Uprising group in Chatilla and the Bourj
el-Barajneh camp, police said.
   The Syrian-backed dissidents are led by Col. Saeed Mousa,
code-named Abu Mousa, who broke away from Fatah in 1983 and set up
headquarters in Damascus, Syria.
   Friday's casualties increased the known casualties to 10 killed
and 60 wounded since the latest round of fighting between the
feuding wings erupted Wednesday.
   Also Friday, Israeli-backed militiamen opened fire on U.N.
peacekeepers in southern Lebanon and slightly wounded a Norwegian
soldier, a spokesman for the peacekeeping force said in Jerusalem.
   Members of the South Lebanon Army militia also held U.N. troops
at gunpoint for nearly an hour and prevented them from
administering first aid to the wounded man, said Timor Goksel,
spokesman for the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon, or
UNIFIL.
   The thuds of exploding shells echoed across Beirut as a third
cease-fire mediated by a security committee made up of
representatives of neutral guerrilla factions collapsed after a
brief mid-morning lull.
   Arafat's loyalists had flushed out Abu Mousa's guerrillas from
both embattled shantytowns in previous rounds of fighting in the
last two months, despite a reconciliation between Arafat and Syrian
President Hafez Assad.
   But the dissidents regrouped at the Syrian-controlled edges of
the two camps in recent days, trying to counterattack, police
reported.
   Israeli army officials refused comment on the reported incident
involving pro-Israeli militiamen in south Lebanon.
   Goksel said the militiamen withdrew when an Israeli officer
arrived at the scene and ordered them to release the U.N. troops.
``We filed a complaint with the Israeli army,'' Goksel said. ``We
told them to get a rein on these people.''
   The South Lebanon Army, a force of mainly Christian Lebanese
militiamen, helps Israel patrol its self-declared ``security zone''
in southern Lebanon. Israel set up the zone, a 6-to-10-mile wide
strip of land north of the Israeli-Lebanese border, when it
withdrew the bulk of its troops from Lebanon in June 1985, ending a
three-year occupation.
   Goksel said Friday's incident began when nine militiamen and
four members of the militia's security service broke through a U.N.
checkpoint near the village of Kaoukaba, about 10 miles north of
the Israeli-Lebanese border.
   In response, peacekeepers closed off the next UNIFIL checkpoint
guarded by six Norwegian soldiers.
   ``When the SLA people arrived at that checkpoint, they jumped
out, aimed their guns at the heads of the Norwegian soldiers, took
their weapons and forced them to lie on the ground,'' Goksel said.
   When a Norwegian officer, 2nd Lt. Rune Gleditch, arrived at the
scene and tried to defuse the situation, militiamen opened fire on
him, wounding him in the right knee, Goksel said.
   Gleditch was finally evacuated by helicopter and taken to a
hospital in southern Lebanon where he was reported in satisfactory
condition. Goksel said he did not know Gleditch's age or hometown.
   Since the 5,800-strong UNIFIL force was deployed in Lebanon in
1978, about 250 U.N. peacekeepers have been wounded, Goksel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
