<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RestaurantAngels     06-10 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Restaurant Angels,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Patrollers Enlisted To Repel Riffraff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restaurant Row, a theater district block with
more than a score of fine-to-middling eating establishments, has
called in a volunteer anti-crime patrol to turn a tide of human
riffraff that has driven diners away.
   A team of 30 Guardian Angels, young men and women in red berets,
began patrolling the block this week, and there was ``marked
improvement'' after two days, Joe Allen, owner of a restaurant of
the same name, said Friday.
   ``I've had people calling up for reservations telling me how
glad they were that we are doing this and how much better it makes
them feel about coming here,'' he said.
   The patrollers on West 46th Street, have fingered drug dealers
for police arrests and kept crack-users, loiterers and prostitutes
on the move, Allen added.
   When an explosion of crack cocaine trafficking and loitering
reduced business by as much as 20 percent, Allen and 14 other
restaurant owners asked the Angels for help.
   The restaurateurs gave $300 each to finance the effort; the
Angels receive nothing personally. The restaurateurs supplied the
patrollers with walkie-talkies and allowed them to use a French
restaurant closed because of a slump in patronage as a headquarters
and barracks.
   The patrollers also are being fed, in rotation, by the
restaurants they are protecting. The first week the food has been
coming from Audrone, whose French-Continental fare is rated ``very
good to excellent'' in a popular restaurant guide.
   Restaurant Row has for years enjoyed a thriving business-lunch
trade and solid evening patronage from tourists and theatergoers.
Broadway's playhouses are a short walk away.
   ``My guys have gone from fast-food chicken to dishes they can't
pronounce. It'll be a while before they get a gourmet palate,''
said Curtis Sliwa, who founded the Angels in 1979 and now claims
about 5,000 members nationwide.
   The Angels were organized as an unarmed youth patrol to deter
subway crime. Though frowned on as unqualified vigilantes by
police, their presence reassured subway riders and they branched
out to escorting the elderly.
   Although police made 600 arrests last year in Restaurant Row's
immediate neighborhood and an additional 650 through May of this
year, the problems haven't gone away, said Deputy Inspector Edward
Fitzgerald, commander of the local police precinct.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
