<DOCNO> AP880610-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1830EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArtsFestival     06-10 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arts Festival,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arts Festival Takes Over City for 31 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even for New York, no stranger to the
superlative, it's awesome: The New York International Festival of
the Arts aims to present 350 events, including 100 premieres,
during 31 days.
   In Friday's prologue, three Italian gondolas _ which crossed the
Atlantic by jet _ traveled down the Hudson River.
   The festival proper begins Saturday with the world premiere of
S.P.E.B.S.Q.S.A., an American Ballet Theatre production set to
barber shop quartet music.
   There also is a new ballet and other fare Saturday evening, part
of the 100 premieres scattered among the festival's 31 continuous
days and nights of film, music, dance and theater offered mostly in
Manhattan.
   The theme? Highlighting the 20th century.
   ``There's been a lot done on other centuries,'' Martin E. Segal,
chairman of the festival and chairman emeritus of Lincoln Center,
said Friday.
   ``There hasn't been enough done on the 20th century. I would
rather people enjoy the works of the 20th century while they are
alive rather than have people comment on it while we are all dead.''
   So, from Indonesia to Ireland, from Canada to China, from Mali
to Mexico, from Belgium, France, Australia and other points
worldwide will tumble performing arts events that bear witness to
this century.
   Mary Martin will reprise her hit Sunday of ``My Heart Belongs to
Daddy,'' which she first sang 50 years ago during her Broadway
debut in Cole Porter's 1938 performance of ``Leave it to Me.''
   That's but one of the 75 events designed to capture the
evolution of music in this century. Playing the music of Debussy,
Stravinsky, Stephen Sondheim and Leonard Bernstein will be, among
others, the symphony orchestras of Chicago, Montreal, New York,
Philadelphia and St. Louis.
   There will be an international Pop series, an All-Duke Ellington
Evening, the JVC Jazz Festival and Placido Domingo's closing night,
free concert in Central Park.
   Dance works by George Balanchine, Merce Cunningham and newer
choreographers will be offered among the 11 dance premieres. The
American Ballet Theatre, the Dance Theatre of Harlem and the
Frankfurt Ballet are scheduled.
   Poland, Ireland and Argentina are represented among the theater
offerings. Six plays will premiere off Broadway. Works by Becket,
O'Casey and O'Neill are featured.
   Also on the menu are experimental works, film and television
tributes and showings, multi-arts happenings and symposia on
various arts topics.
   Every festival, however, has its setbacks.
   On Thursday, just before arriving in the United States, 23
performers from the Maly Dramatic Theater of Leningrad learned that
an American producer had canceled a two-day play about life in a
Soviet village.
   Producer Ken Marsolais, who said he was unable to raise the
necessary $450,000, said he hoped to have the Soviets perform at an
off-Broadway location.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Kurds     06-10 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Kurds,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurdish Leader Urges U.S. Officials, Lawmakers To Prevent Genocide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of Iraq's Kurdish minority said
Friday he met with U.S. officials and lawmakers to seek their
support for preventing a massacre of his people by Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein.
   ``The government of Iraq has resolved to rid itself of what it
has termed the Kurdish problem by eliminating the Kurdish people,''
said Jalal Talabani, head of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan.
   The program to eliminate the estimated 4 million Iraqi Kurds
began in 1963 and is in its final phase, he told reporters.
   Talabani, whose group is one of the two main political
organizations in the northern autonomous region of Kurdistan, said
that over the past three years Hussein's government had destroyed
some 1,300 Kurdish towns and villages, poisoned water sources and
deported some 1.5 million inhabitants to remote desert areas.
   In one attack against the Kurds, Iraq dropped cyanide and
mustard gas last March on the town of Halabja, killing some 5,000
people, he said. The United States has condemned the Iraqi attack.
   Talabani said State Department officials have promised to press
Iraq to desist from human rights abuses against the Kurds.
   Talabani said his group is mostly self-supporting, although it
receives weapons and humanitarian help from Iran. ``We're not a
tool of Iran, but we have a common enemy,'' he said.
   There are an estimated 15 million to 20 million Kurds in the
world, the largest group in Turkey and the rest in Iraq, Iran,
Syria, Lebanon and the Soviet Union.
   Talabani said the Iraqi Kurds, who have pooled resources against
Hussein, were trying to improve relations with the Soviet Union,
which is Iraq's main military supplier. ``Maybe the spirit of
glasnost will help us too,'' he said.
</TEXT>
