<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0636,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Signs Land Reform Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 10th pvs, ``Leftist farm ...'' to
UPDATE with background on land reform; pickup 11th pvs, ``Officials
say ...'' Minor editing to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino signed a
land reform bill into law Friday and said she hoped the measure
will enable the country to feed itself and lift Filipino peasants
from poverty.
   Mrs. Aquino, in a nationally televised speech, congratulated
Congress for passing the bill after nearly a year of debate. The
bill, approved Wednesday, is considered essential in defeating the
19-year communist insurgency.
   The military announced the arrests of a West German, a Swede and
a Filipino of German descent accused of helping communist rebels.
   Seven soldiers and 10 insurgents were reported killed in
fighting west of the capital.
   Also on Friday, workers exhumed 12 bodies from a mass grave at a
suburban cemetery. Human rights organizations said the grave may
contain victims of right-wing death squads.
   The land reform act, which officials say will benefit 3 million
landless farmers, gives landowners the choice of dividing their
property among tenants or sharing profits with them.
   Mrs. Aquino said she hoped the 10-year program will increase
agricultural production and lead to the ``upliftment of the
Filipino masses from their ancient poverty.''
   She said she expects all Cabinet members to support land reform
and threatened to fire officials who impede its implementation.
   Under the plan, each landowner may retain 12 acres and an
additional seven acres for each direct heir over the age 15 who
will till the land. A landowner has the option of sharing profits
or giving workers shares of stock instead of physically dividing
the property.
   Leftist farm groups have branded the plan a ``grand deception''
because they claim it does not go far enough in breaking up huge
estates and redistributing property to the landless.
   Mrs. Aquino had been criticized for the pace of land reform. The
Philippines attempted about a dozen land reform programs in the
past, but they failed for lack of funds or resistance from
landowners.
   Land reform was among the demands of pro-Soviet rebels in the
1950s and early 1960s and is a major demand of communist rebels in
the insurgency that began in 1968.
   Officials say the program, estimated to cost $70 billion, will
be financed by foreign aid and assets of former President Ferdinand
Marcos and his associates. Those assets were seized on grounds they
were acquired illegally.
   The military announced that troops arrested the Rev. Klaus
Schmidt, 52, a West German Protestant minister; Stellan Hermansson,
30, a Swede; and Antonio Bosch, 46, a Filipino of German descent
for possible links with communist rebels.
   The West German and Swedish embassies said they were unaware of
the reports.
   In Stockholm, officials of the Young Communist League said
Hermansson was the organization's president. Spokesman Erik
Cardfelt said Hermansson was a free-land journalist and arrived May
18 to gather information for lectures.
   Col. Hernani Figueroa, spokesman of the military's Southern
Luzon Command, said the three were arrested Wednesday in Quezon
province. He said they had been reported training rebels.
   Figueroa said soldiers identified the three as among guerrillas
who raided the town of San Francisco in February.
   Figueroa said they were being held in Lucena City, 60 miles
southeast of Manila.
   In suburban Makati, workers exhumed 12 bodies from a mass grave.
The church-backed Ecumenical Movement for Justice and Peace said
the grave contained at least 22 bodies buried in April at the South
Cemetery.
   Movement officials obtained a court order authorizing the
exhumation to determine if some of those buried were missing
members of the left-wing Youth for Democracy and Nationalism.
   In Bataan province, communist rebels stormed an army post
Wednesday, killing seven troops and wounding two others, military
officials said. They said two rebels were killed.
   The government's news agency said Friday that eight more rebels
were killed in Orani town in the Bataan peninsula, 30 miles west of
the capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
