<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CoalWildcatters     06-10 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coal Wildcatters,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Proposes Tougher Stance Against Coal
Wildcatters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration asked Congress on
Friday to get tough on coal wildcatters by making it a felony to
strip mine coal without a permit.
   Legislation sent to Capitol Hill by the Office of Surface Mining
Reclamation and Enforcement calls for a maximum prison term of five
years for people convicted of mining without a permit.
   The proposal also would allow a judge to impose a fine of up to
$250,000 against a convicted individual and a fine of up to
$500,000 against a convicted organization.
   Strip mining without a permit is now a civil offense with a top
penalty of $22,500, but office spokesman Alan Cole said that ``the
civil procedures are so ponderous, it's difficult to keep up with
the wildcatters.''
   In a prepared statement, Robert Gentile, acting director of the
office, said that ``what the wildcatters are doing is not only
illegal, it is an insult to law-abiding citizens and the legitimate
coal industry.
   ``The wildcatter's blatant disregard for our system means the
time has come to go after them with a vengeance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
