<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrawleyMove     06-10 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley Move,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brawley Mother Reported Moved to Brooklyn Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a black teen-ager allegedly
abducted and raped by whites was driven on Friday from the Queens
church where she had holed up for two days to a church in Brooklyn,
the pastor of the church said.
   Glenda Brawley sought ``religious asylum'' in Ebenezer Baptist
Church in Queens on Wednesday, defying a court order to testify
before a grand jury investigating her daughter's case. She faces 30
days in jail and a $250 fine.
   On Friday afternoon, Mrs. Brawley, accompanied by some
supporters, drove off with her adviser, the Rev. Al Sharpton, and
lawyer C. Vernon Mason. They did not comment to reporters.
   Sharpton challenged police to arrest Mrs. Brawley along the 10
miles separating the two churches.
   Timothy Gilles, a spokesman for state Attorney General Robert
Abrams, said police would arrest Mrs. Brawley only at the request
of Abrams, who is responsible for the Brawley investigation.
   ``We have no intentions of swooping in to participate in the
media circus that the Rev. Sharpton and attorneys (Alton) Maddox
and Mason are intending to orchestrate,'' said Gilles. ``For the
time being, we have no intention of moving in.''
   William Augustus Jones, minister of Bethany Baptist Church in
Brooklyn, said Mrs. Brawley was taken to his church, where rallies
for the Brawley family have been held for the last two months.
   Sharpton would not say why Mrs. Brawley was being moved.
   The Brawley family's lawyers have contended that law enforcement
authorities have engaged in a racist cover-up and have advised Mrs.
Brawley not to cooperate with the grand jury investigation.
   Tawana Brawley disappeared for four days in November and was
found wrapped in a plastic bag about 10 miles from her home, with
racial epithets scrawled on her. In sketchy interviews with
officials, she said she had been sexually abused by six white men,
one of whom had a police-style badge. A hospital examination found
no evidence of rape.
</TEXT>
