<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Welfare     06-10 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Welfare,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aides Say Reagan Will Veto Welfare Reform Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will veto plans to overhaul
the nation's welfare system now working their way through Congress,
White House aides said Friday.
   The aides said Reagan, atfer meeting with a group of welfare
leaders, declared his intention to veto both a bill passed by the
House and another set for debate in the Senate next week.
   ``I think the president's likely to veto either bill, or both of
them in their present form,'' said Charles Hobbs, director of the
White House Office of Policy Development.
   Earlier, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan told
the meeting he will veto any ``welfare expansion of the type now
under consideration in Congress.''
   Fitzwater said the legislation under consideration ``would spend
billions of dollars to expand the welfare system but without the
reforms that we think are necessary.''
   ``We are especially concerned that the current bill does not
require recipients of welfare to actually work if they are able to
do so,'' he said.
   Reagan also wants a bill that promises waivers of federal red
tape for states and municipalities wishing to try thier own welfare
reforms, Fitzwater said.
   Hobbs characterized the bill before the Senate as an ``expansion
of the welfare balloon that simply doesn't do anybody any good.''
The bill, sponsored by Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y., has 62
co-sponsors.
   Despite the veto threat, New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean said he
believes a welfare-reform bill can be passed and signed by the
president this year. Kean attended the meeting with the president.
   ``We're close ... very, very close,'' Kean said.
   The governor said he believes differences between Reagan and
Congress can be addressed when House and Senate conferees meet to
reconcile versions of the bill.
   Kean said Reagan will insist that a final version contain the
work requirement and the federal waivers. Otherwise, the White
House appears openminded, he said.
   Reagan met with Kean and other delegates to a two-day conference
on the future of welfare reform. Also at the session was Mayor
William Morris of Memphis, Tenn., and several administrators of
promising self-help programs.
   Fitzwater said the group discussed Reagan's welfare-reform
strategy, unveiled in February 1987, calling for pilot projects
designed to get people off welfare rolls by making them
self-supporting.
   Congress has not acted on Reagan's proposal, but the president
has asked his welfare advisory board to work with federal agencies
and state and local governments to launch demonstration projects in
at least half of the states by the end of the year.
   The board has endorsed projects in New Jersey, Wisconsin, Ohio,
Washington and New York and projects in five other states are under
active consideration, Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0206 </DOCNO>
