<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TokenBooths     06-10 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Token Booths,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City and Transit Cops to Increase Token Booth Patrols</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City and transit police announced Friday they
will increase patrols of the city's 3,200 subway token booths
following three more threats to set fire to booths with clerks
inside.
   The three threats occurred late Thursday night and early Friday
morning, officials said, only a week after an attack on a booth in
Brooklyn fatally burned a clerk.
   ``Obviously we are extremely upset at what's been going on,''
Transit Authority President David Gunn told a news conference.
   Although fewer than 10 of the 70 attempted booth robberies this
year involved the threat or actual use of a flammable liquid, Gunn
said the TA's aim is to eliminate the possibility of another fatal
attack.
   Beginning Friday night, the TA police department will assign 50
plainclothes and uniformed officers to token booth protection,
according to Vincent Del Castillo, acting chief of the TA Police
Department.
   City police also will increase their patrols of subway booths,
according to David Scott, chief of patrol for the New York Police
Department.
