<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Anderson     06-10 0128</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Anderson,0131</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former AP Newsman Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James H. ``Andy'' Anderson, a former chief
of bureau for The Associated Press, died Thursday. He was 84.
   Anderson, a native of Independence, Kan., joined the AP in
Kansas City in 1927. He transferred to St. Louis in 1935, and later
became chief of bureau in Oklahoma City from 1944-46.
   Anderson continued to work in Oklahoma City until his retirement
in 1968.
   Stanley M. Swinton, assistant general manager of the AP at the
time of Anderson's retirement, said in 1968 of Anderson's work in
Oklahoma City that ``much of the bureau's success in that period
had been the result'' of his efforts.
   Memorial services for Anderson are scheduled for Saturday at
First Presbyterian Church in Oklahoma City.
</TEXT>
