<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Budget     06-10 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Budget,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Budget Problems Can Be Managed but Sidesteps Details</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One day after suffering another budgetary blow,
Gov. Michael Dukakis said Friday the state's worsening money
problems can be managed. But he declined to give new details on how
that might be accomplished.
   ``Obviously, we have an immediate problem,'' Dukakis said,
referring to a shortfall of at least $400 million in the $11
billion budget for the fiscal year that ends in three weeks.
   Nearly $100 million of that total became due suddenly on
Thursday when the state's highest court ruled in favor of a
corporate tax abatement.
   In his first full-fledged news conference on Massachusetts
issues since clinching the Democratic presidential nomination,
Dukakis acknowledged that the current tax shortfall is serious, but
he said the state is not broke and stuck to his view that the
state's economy remains healthy.
   The governor again declined to specify which tax-raising
measures he supports _ if any _ beyond the $70 million he has
proposed to gain by bringing the state income tax code in line with
federal changes.
   Dukakis was asked if he supports a proposed $40 million tax on
cigarettes, or other new taxes.
   ``That's an open question at this point,'' he said. The need for
taxes depends on how much savings government can realize by scaling
back planned expansions for next year and by trimming the cost of
long-term nursing home care, he indicated.
   Dukakis also repeated his desire to capture a projected $38
million in unclaimed bottle deposits held by bottlers, although
legislative leaders have said firmly they hold little hope for
claiming those funds.
   ``All of these issues are on the table; all of them involve
savings and revenue,'' Dukakis said, promising that a solution to
balance the budget would ``evolve.''
   For next fiscal year, Dukakis initially proposed spending nearly
$12 billion, but he has trimmed that request. In May, the House cut
spending plans further, sending an $11.8 billion package to the
Senate, which is drafting its own budget plans now.
   Dukakis said that because the House did not adopt all of his
proposals to reduce spending, there is room for more cuts.
</TEXT>
