<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugProbe     06-10 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Probe,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Member of Kerry's Drug Panel Says Hearings Designed to Hurt
Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, the senior Republican on
a Senate subcommittee investigating Latin American drug dealing,
angrily accused panel chairman John Kerry on Friday of using the
issue as a political weapon against Vice President George Bush.
   McConnell accused the Massachusetts Democrat of setting up a
series of hearings into drug-running operations that put Reagan
administration anti-drug efforts in a bad light while refusing to
hear testimony from administration witnesses.
   ``The subcommittee is being conducted as if it were a division
of the Dukakis campaign,'' McConnell said in a reference to likely
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Bush has been a central figure in those efforts, first as head
of the South Florida anti-drug task force, then as chief of the
administration's overall drug interdiction effort.
   The investigation ``has deteriorated into a biased, partisan
agenda designed to selectively criticize and condemn rather than
work toward constructive solutions,'' McConnell, R-Ky., told
reporters.
   ``A year and a half of requests to hear from the administration
witnesses to discuss policy plans and options regarding
international drug trafficking have been ignored,'' he said.
   McConnell accused Kerry and his staff of spinning out a story
told by convicted drug dealers of dubious credibility, of declining
to schedule witnesses who might dispute that story and of leaking
information to the press to suit their political goals. McConnell
has not attended the hearings.
   Specifically, he said, Kerry has declined to allow Felix
Rodriguez, a former CIA agent and friend of Bush, to rebut claims
by one previous witness that Rodriguez was involved in channeling
drug profits to Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   In a statement read at McConnell's news conference Friday,
Rodriguez said he had only met the man who made the charge,
convicted money launderer Ramon Milian Rodriguez, on one occasion.
Milian Rodriguez told him ``in passing'' that he might be able to
provide money from the drug operation for the Contras, Rodriguez
said.
   The meeting, on Jan. 18, 1985, was at the office of Raul Diaz, a
former law-enforcement officer and now a private investigator who
put Rodriguez in touch with the drug trafficker, he said. He said
he passed the information to the FBI and the CIA but did not
otherwise follow up. At that time, Rodriguez said, he had never met
Bush.
   Responding to the charges, Kerry accused McConnell in turn of
trying to politicize the drug issue.
   ``I am saddened by my colleague's decision to separate himself
from a serious investigation that has required an awful lot of hard
work over the course of three years,'' Kerry said in a statement.
   ``We have tried to include him in the process. I regret that for
reasons of his own he has chosen to politicize the ongoing work of
the subcommittee as we seek to expose the connections between law
enforcement, foreign policy and narcotics.''
   Kerry said his committee still plans to invite administration
witnesses, including John C. Lawn, head of the Drug Enforcement
Administration. Rodriguez also is expected to be called to testify,
as well as the former head of the South Florida anti-drug task
force, Adm. Daniel Murphy.
   Kerry's chief aide on the investigation, Jack Blum, said he had
been discussing future witness lists with McConnell as recently as
last week and said he was ``astonished'' at the complaints.
   Kerry's Foreign Relations subcommittee on terrorism, narcotics
and international operations has held a series of hearings on the
Latin American drug trade, including the widespread influence of
the Colombian Medellin cocaine cartel.
   While McConnell has not been present for the hearings,
Republican New York Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who is not a member of
the subcommittee, has been present and participated in questioning
much of the time.
</TEXT>
