<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-O'Connor     06-10 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-O'Connor,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Cardinal Greets Soviet Reforms with Mix of Skepticism,
Hope</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With Soviet-Religion, Bjt
^By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York said Friday his
first 48 hours in the Soviet Union left him uncertain about the
reality of change here, but he voiced hope Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev was sincere in his desire for reform.
   ``Mr. Gorbachev is confronted with tremendous problems,''
O'Connor, the archbishop of New York, said in a telephone
interview. ``I think anyone in his right mind prays Mr. Gorbachev
is sincere and wants to bring about a new era.''
   O'Connor and nine other Roman Catholic cardinals are in Moscow
for celebrations marking the 1,000th anniversary of the Russian
Orthodox Church, an event being accorded extraordinary prominence
by authorities in this officially atheistic state.
   O'Connor is the highest-ranking American Catholic in the largest
Vatican delegation ever to visit the country. Evangelist Billy
Graham is also visiting the Soviet Union for the millennium
celebration.
   Earlier Friday, O'Connor and other visiting dignitaries attended
a gala meeting at Moscow's Bolshoi Theatre marking the millennium
of the mass baptism carried out in 988 by Prince Vladimir of Kiev,
the rite that founded the Russian church.
   Raisa Gorbachev, the Soviet leader's wife, was also present.
   O'Connor said the presence of Mrs. Gorbachev, who once was a
teacher of Marxism-Leninism, and the official exposure being given
the event here had stunned the leaders of the Russian church.
   O'Connor noted he had only arrived Wednesday and had only had
time for ``impressions and guesses'' about how Gorbachev's drive
for ``glasnost,'' or openness, had affected religious believers in
the Soviet Union.
   ``Anyone who wants to be honest is in a bit of a dilemma,''
O'Connor said. ``Writing it off as a charade would be as tragic as
if we bought it lock, stock and barrel.''
   Soviet authorities are currently rewriting laws on religion to
allow believers more latitude in expressing their faith. But
O'Connor said ``deprivations and persecutions'' continued against
the Ukrainian Catholic Church, which is not recognized by Soviet
authorities.
   O'Connor also said dramatic changes were needed in the treatment
of Soviet Jewry.
   He said he believed Russian church leaders knew that once the
foreign delegations left, ``things could go back to subnormal'' in
Soviet church-state relations.
   O'Connor began his day by celebrating Mass at St. Louis Roman
Catholic Church in Moscow, as he did Thursday, said Monsignor James
McCarthy, the cardinal's secretary.
   Four other cardinals and 12 priests were also in attendance,
McCarthy said, as well as two bishops, one from the Soviet republic
of Lithuania and the other from Vietnam.
   On Saturday, O'Connor is scheduled to take part in an evening
vigil at the Trinity Cathedral of Moscow's Danilov Monastery
conducted by Patriach Pimen, the head of the Russian Church.
   The next day is the Russian Orthodox equivalent of All Saints
Day, known as ``Sunday of All Saints Who Shone Forth in the Land of
Russia'' and one of the holiest days on the church's calendar.
   O'Connor is scheduled to return to New York on June 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
