<HEAD>Gore May Break Silence, Endorse Dukakis Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., the only former
Democratic presidential hopeful who hasn't made a formal
endorsement, may give Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis his nod
next week, an aide said Friday.
   Mike Kopp, Gore's press secretary, said the Tennessee senator's
staff was ``still working out the details'' for an endorsement of
Dukakis.
   Kopp said he could not discuss the details, but said Gore would
probably endorse Dukakis ``in a few days. It will not be this
week.''
   Three other former rivals for the Democratic nomination _ Bruce
Babbitt, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Sen. Paul Simon of
Illinois _ endorsed Dukakis on Wednesday. The Democratic
front-runner sewed up the nomination a day earlier by winning the
California primary.
   While Gore has not released his delegates, The Associated Press
delegate poll shows 114 have left him over the past four weeks. On
May 13, Gore had 403 delegates while Friday he had 289.
