<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0728 06-10 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0728,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Arrests Suspect in Stabbing of Mayor, Bulldozes His House</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS last 4 grafs `Shamir said ... territorial concessions'
with 5 to CORRECT that meeting with Shevardnadze was in New York
and add information about returning press credentials</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JELAZOUN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army arrested a
26-year-old Palestinian suspected of stabbing an Israeli-appointed
Arab mayor and bulldozed his cinderblock house Friday in the
Jelazoun refugee camp.
   The army said Khamis Jawdat Faraj had stalked Hassan Tawil, 74,
the mayor of El Bireh, and knifed him as an act of Palestinian
nationalism. Tawil was critically wounded.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, troops ordered about 100 Israelis
out of the village of Beita, where the Israelis were planting olive
trees to protest the army's uprooting of orchards and demolition of
14 Arab houses.
   The uprootings and demolitions were in retaliation for an April
6 clash between villagers and Israeli settlers in which two
Palestinians and a 15-year-old Jewish girl were killed.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir returned from a five-day trip to
the United States and told reporters he urged Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze to support direct peace talks between
Israel and its Arab neighbors.
   The army said in a statement it arrested Faraj on Thursday night.
   A large yellow bulldozer leveled the three-room house where
Faraj lived with his 60-year-old mother. Only an almond tree, plum
tree and rose bush were left standing.
   Before sending about a dozen vehicles and two bulldozers into
Jelazoun, the army imposed a curfew and cut electricity to the camp
where about 5,000 Palestinians live. It is about 20 miles north of
Jerusalem.
   Troops removed belongings from the house and found Marxist and
Palestinian nationalist literature inside. Then one of the
bulldozers rumbled up to the one-story house and knocked it down,
raising a huge cloud of dust.
   ``They are destroying our house _ I don't know what for,'' said
Nozha Faraj as she watched the demolition from a neighbor's home.
   The army said her son had been detained several times previously
for alleged participation in anti-Israeli disturbances.
   According to the daily Haaretz, Tawil, who was stabbed Tuesday,
was able to identify his assailant. Tawil told Israel Television
the man asked him for help in obtaining a passport before stabbing
him.
   In Beita, troops uprooted the trees being planted by an Israeli
group called ``Committee for Beita.'' They threw one of the
saplings onto the highway. The move prompted the Israelis to shout:
``Shoot the trees!''
   The Israeli group seeks reparations to villagers whose homes
were destroyed or damaged by the army in punishment for the clash.
   Jewish settlers and the army initially blamed Arab villagers for
the death of Israeli teen-ager Tirza Porat, but an army report
later determined she was killed by a bullet fired by an Israeli
guarding the group.
   According to U.N. figures, 204 Palestinians and two Israelis
have been killed since the uprising began on Dec. 8. About 5,000
Arabs have been injured and 5,000 arrested.
   After Moslem prayers in Gaza City on Friday, troops fired tear
gas to disperse about 50 protesters who threw rocks at soldiers
from rooftops and chanted ``PLO, Israel No!''
   Also Friday, Arab newspapers reported the army arrested two more
Palestinian reporters and a writer. The army has detained 21 Arab
journalists for six months without trial to try to curb the
Palestinian press, which it blames for inciting unrest.
   Shamir said he told Shevardnadze at their meeting in New York he
opposes an international conference on Middle East peace. ``We know
what we want and we don't think a conference of all kinds of
countries should decide our fate,'' he said.
   The Soviets favor such a conference, which would include
America, the Soviet Union, France, Britain and China as the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, but Shamir says
Israel would be outnumbered and pressured to make territorial
concessions.
   The Government Press Office reinstated the press credentials of
NBC television correspondent Martin Fletcher after a six-week
suspension.
   Israel suspended the credentials of Fletcher and Washington Post
correspondent Glenn Frankel on April 26, accusing them of violating
military censorship by reporting that Israel was responsible for
the assassination of PLO military commander Khalil Wazir in Tunisia
on April 16. The government has refused comment on reports of its
involvement.
   Frankel's credentials were returned in May.
</TEXT>
