<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HometownBook     06-10 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hometown Book,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town's Residents Riled By Author's Boring Portrayal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRUM, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This tiny mining town on the Tug River got a
less than flattering portrayal in a book written by a native son
who said Crum was a boring place where nothing ever changes but the
weather.
   ``Crum,'' a novel by Lee Maynard, has been on the bookshelves
for two weeks, but it's hard to find in these parts. The only local
store that stocked it, the Sav-Rite nearby in Kermit, sold its two
copies right away.
   ``I didn't think highly of the book,'' said Crum resident Lorrie
Perry. ``It was not one I'd put on the library shelf.''
   Maynard picked his hometown of 300 on the West Virginia-Kentucky
border as the subject of his first book, published by Washington
Square Press, a division of Simon & Schuster.
   ``During the winters in Crum the days were long, boring and
cold, and during the summers the days were long, boring and hot,''
Maynard wrote. ``In Crum, only the temperature changed.''
   Maynard, 52, said he intended much of the 189-page book to be
funny, but it was based on fact. ``There's a kernel of truth in
every page, in every paragraph,'' said Maynard, who was known as
Amos Lee when he lived in the town.
   Residents disagree, especially about the salty language
Maynard's characters use.
   ``We didn't use language like that. That was shocking,'' said
one resident, who asked not to be named in deference to Maynard's
parents who moved to Kenova, about 30 miles away, when Maynard was
14.
   ``I really had a high regard for him,'' said one upset resident.
``Amos Lee was a very All-American type. It didn't sound like the
Amos Lee I knew.''
   The story follows a nameless protagonist through four seasons of
his high school senior year during the 1950s. He's not the fastest,
smartest or strongest boy in his gang.
   He's just the one who wants out of Crum the most.
   ``I tried for years to figure out how our gang worked and I
guess it was sort of like a stew,'' the protagonist writes. ``The
boys were tasteless chunks of things floating around in the pot,
mostly unidentifiable, but sort of gristly if you bit into them,
with the girls as the spices and the heat.''
   ``Living in Crum made such an impact on me,'' Maynard said. ``To
this day I don't know if the impact was good or bad. I had such a
desire to leave. It was a weight on my shoulders.''
   Ralph Dawson, the principal of Crum Elementary School who was a
year or two behind Maynard in school, said he remembers Crum
differently from the author.
   ``It was a very active community,'' he said.
   Maynard, who now lives in Sante Fe, N.M., has been back only
once.
   ``I drove in, had a cup of coffee and got in my car and drove
away. I got very tense while I was in there,'' he said. ``Have you
been to Crum? It's a strange place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
