<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopExecution     06-10 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop Execution,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Final Plea For Mercy, Bishop Meets Lethal Injection Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Shona and Graeme in 15th graf are cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT OF THE MOUNTAIN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Condemned serial child-killer
Arthur Gary Bishop went to his execution Friday begging
forgiveness, but the families of his victims say it won't come from
them.
   ``I know he (was) sick, but to forgive him? I can't forgive him
for taking my son's life. I just don't understand why he couldn't
have let him go,'' said Debbie Fisher Robinson, whose son, Alonzo
Daniels, 4, Bishop killed in 1979.
   Bishop, 36, was the 99th inmate executed in the United States
since a 1976 U.S. Supreme Court ruling ended a nationwide
moratorium on capital punishment.
   He was pronounced dead at 12:16 a.m., about eight minutes after
two executioners at Utah State Prison injected him with deadly
chemicals.
   ``Give my apologies to the families of the victims,'' were
Bishop's last words, said Warden Gerald Cook.
   A former Eagle Scout, excommunicated Mormon missionary and a
bookkeeper by profession, Bishop ended all further appeals after
the Utah Supreme Court in February rejected his arguments against
the death penalty.
   He was convicted in 1984 of kidnapping five Salt Lake County
boys between 1979 and 1983. The victims, ages 4 to 13, were
variously shot, bludgeoned, strangled and drowned because Bishop
feared exposure as a child molester.
   A homosexual pedophile, Bishop confessed to police he was glad
he had been caught because he couldn't control his lust for young
boys and would likely have killed again.
   In a hand-written statement released after his execution, Bishop
said he had allowed himself ``to be misled by Satan, and as a
result, my life has been marked by wicked, perverse and depraved
actions.''
   He said that by ending his appeals, he was not trying to be
heroic, but ``accepting my just punishment. ... Though perhaps too
little too late, I am doing the right thing now,'' he wrote.
   Bishop also used his final statement to deny ``pernicious
rumors'' that he was guilty of other slayings than the five for
which he was convicted, and that he was sexually abused as a child.
   Reaction from the families of Bishop's victims was laced with
bitterness.
   Claude and Lora-Lee Petersen said they are struggling to prevent
their pain and anger over Bishop's 1980 slaying of their
11-year-old son, Kim, from consuming them. The Petersens said the
execution offered them no relief.
   ``It's still a form of violence, and we don't want to focus on
that at all,'' they said.
   Shona Cunningham, whose 13-year-old son, Graeme, was Bishop's
last victim, said she could not bring herself to grant Bishop's
plea for forgiveness contained in a February letter to her and
other victim's relatives.
   ``I told him it's not my jurisdiction,'' she said of her written
response, the only one Bishop received from victims' families. ``I
told him he was right, there can't be a happy ending to this one.''
   Hours before Bishop's execution, about 70 people gathered on a
hill overlooking the prison to hold a candlelight vigil protesting
capital punishment. The vigil was sponsored jointly by Amnesty
International and the Utah Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty.
   A handful of people favoring the execution stood nearby and
shouted ``Justice has been served.''
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
