<DOCNO> AP880610-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--MassDems-Dukakis     06-10 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Mass Dems-Dukakis,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homestate Democratic Convention To Embrace Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Democrats gather in Boston Garden on
Saturday for a state convention that will be little more than a
political rally for the presidential candidacy of native son
Michael S. Dukakis.
   The setting for the convention is a meaningful one _ the last
political event held at Boston Garden was the election eve speech
delivered by John F. Kennedy to the people of Massachusetts in 1960.
   ``It's a moment in history, a chance to reflect when we go to
the Garden ... to sort of reflect back on a grand and glorious
political tradition in Massachusetts,'' said Rep. Chester Atkins,
chairman of the Democratic State Committee.
   ``It's also a time to anticipate a very exciting future in
Massachusetts politics,'' Atkins said.
   Massachusetts is entitled to bring 109 delegates to the
Democratic National Convention in Atlanta next month. Eleven are
``super delegates,'' who are automatically included by virture of
their roles in the party.
   Gov. Dukakis won 79 of the pledged delegates in the state's
presidential primary in March, while presidential hopeful Jesse
Jackson won 19.
