<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Peron     06-10 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Peron,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forgotten Bank Vaults Yield Peron's Sports Car, Evita's Dresses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sports car with an armored
roof, 350 dresses and rugs made from wild animal skins were among a
host of newly discovered items that belonged to the late President
Juan Peron and his wife, Eva, officials disclosed Friday.
   Peron, Argentina's most popular leader of the 20th century, died
in 1974. Mrs. Peron, the vivacious blonde who was the inspiration
for the stage musical ``Evita,'' died of uterine cancer at age 33
in 1952.
   Among the 5,000 items discovered was a white ermine cape worn by
Mrs. Peron when she visited Pope Pius XII at the Vatican. The
sports car, a 1951 Institec with a Porcshe engine, was driven once
by her husband.
   Other items included about 350 dresses; 20 animal-skin capes and
jackets; a kimono given to the first lady by the Japanese
government; rugs, some made from wild animal skins; a double-barrel
Spanish shotgun and three French rifles.
   The long-forgotten items were stored in four city bank vaults
and storage sites shortly after Peron was toppled by a coup in
1955. They came to officials' attention three months ago through an
anonymous tip, Buenos Aires City Councilman Juan Carlos Suardi said.
   Suardi said plans call for transferring the belongings to a
museum being built in the small pampas town of Los Toldos where Eva
Peron was born, about 250 miles west of Buenos Aires. Eva was
Peron's second wife.
   Peron ruled from 1946 until the military coup, when he went into
exile for 18 years. He returned to a tumultuous welcome in 1973,
was elected president but died at age 78 the next year.
   Suardi said Peron apparently made no attempt to get the items
out of storage upon his return.
   The councilman said the Peron goods will be sent to Los Toldos
within 90 days unless Peron's third wife, Isabel Peron, objects.
Isabel Peron, who lives in Madrid, Spain, succeeded Peron as
president on his death but was ousted in a 1976 coup.
   Also in the Peron collection were pieces of silver and gold,
some jewelry, and dozens of pairs of shoes, socks, ties, pants and
handkerchiefs. Suardi said the total value of the items was not
known.
   Eva Peron's birthplace was declared a historic monument last
month by the governor of Buenos Aires Province, Antonio Cafiero,
leader of the labor-backed Peronist Party named for Peron and now
the main opposition party in Argentina.
   One year ago, grave-robbers broke into the tomb containing
Peron's remains, sawed off the hands and demanded an $8 million
ransom for their return. The ransom never was paid and the hands
remain missing.
   Police say the case remains unsolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
