<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Honors 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Honors, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0741,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Queen Bestows Peerages, Knighthoods and Medals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: EMBARGOED for release at 7:01 p.m. EDT. SUBS 3rd graf pvs to
note that Saturday is official birthday, not queen's actual birth
date; ADDS two grafs on difference between official and actual
birthday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY C. WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Nobel Prize laureates, novelist William
Golding and biologist Aaron Klug, received knighthoods Saturday
while other honors went to a snooker star and the man in charge of
sweeping the streets around Parliament.
   They were among 679 Britons whose works were rewarded by Queen
Elizabeth II in the twice-yearly ritual known as the honors list.
   
   The latest list, celebrating the monarch's official birthday,
also honored a doctor, a nurse and a hospital porter who helped the
injured in an Irish Republican Army bombing that killed 12 people
in Enniskillen, Northern Ireland in November.
   
   An OBE, or Officer of the Order of the British Empire, went to
surgeon Andrew McKibbin who headed the teams of doctors treating
the injured.
   Emergency nurse Jane Packham became a Member of the Order of the
British Empire for her work in the disaster and porter Patrick
Curry received a British Empire Medal for getting the injured to
hospitals.
   Golding, who wrote the ``Lord of the Flies,'' won the 1983 Nobel
Prize in literature. Klug received the 1982 prize for his work in
molecular biology.
   The knighthoods mean that after a ceremony at Buckingham Palace
later this year, they may call themselves Sir William and Sir Aaron.
   Other knighthoods went to composer Harrison Birtwhistle, veteran
Liberal Party lawmaker Cyril Smith and Police Commissioner Peter
Imbert, head of Scotland Yard.
   Shakespearean actor Michael Bryant became a CBE, or Commander of
the Order of the British Empire, and snooker ace Steve Davis
received an MBE. Sgt. Ronald Lewis, baggage master to Prince
Charles, became a member of the Royal Victorian Order.
   The Victorian order is the monarch's personal gift, unlike the
majority of the honors which are chosen by the prime minister. Some
honors are for political loyalty, but most recognize achievement in
the arts, business, industry, civil service, sports, science,
charity and heroism.
   Many honors reflect the days when Britain ran an empire covering
one-fifth of the globe.
   A British Empire Medal went to Peter Codd, who manages the
street sweepers around the Houses of Parliament and Downing Street,
where the prime minister lives.
   The highest award, a life peerage, went to Sir William
Rees-Mogg, former editor of The Times of London and chairman of a
new Broadcasting Standards Council established to clean up sex and
violence on television.
   It entitles him to join about 1,200 members of the House of
Lords, the unelected upper legislative house. Unlike members of the
elected House of Commons, the peers are members for life. They
cannot make laws but can amend legislation on non-financial matters.
   Lord Carrington, outgoing secretary general of NATO, was made
Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St. Michael and St George.
   The queen also gave personal honors to Sir William Heseltine,
her private secretary; Frederick Waite, head gardener at her
Sandringham estate with Membership in the Victorian Order, and
William Oswald, her chief horse-breeder.
   The monarch's official birthday is the second Saturday in June
and came this year on June 11. Queen Elizabeth's actual birthday is
April 21. She is 62.
   The official birthday, held when the chances for good weather
are better than in April, also is celebrated with the military
parade of the Trooping the Color.
</TEXT>
