<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Children     06-10 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Children,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Tells Kids: Quiet Please, While We Discuss Disarmament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children from more than 50 nations filled
the visitor's lobby of the United Nations with songs of peace on
Friday, and U.N. delegates in the General Assembly heard them and
sent a message.
   The message: Quiet down, please, we're discussing disarmament.
   Some 100 youngsters in the lobby accepted the admonition in good
cheer. A ripple of laughter passed through the crowd after a U.N.
official asked for more restraint in calling for world peace.
   A 6-year-old organization called ``Perhaps ... Kids Meeting Kids
Can Make a Difference'' organized what it called a ``children's
summit.'' The week-long gathering coincides with the 159-member
General Assembly's special session on disarmament.
   For the past two weeks presidents, foreign ministers, prime
ministers and U.N. delegates have been addressing the General
Assembly with calls for disarmament.
   On Friday, the children ranging in age from 6 through 14 met in
the lobby to give a representative of Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar a statement after five days of discussions on
peace.
   ``We are happy that countries are now meeting and beginning to
destroy weapons in their nuclear arsenals,'' said part of their
statement. ``We are also aware that new and more sophisticated
weapons are being built to replace them.
   ``We would like you to be aware that we know this and that it
doesn't make sense to us. People should settle their differences by
talking and not by fighting.'' The statement was read by a
sucession of children and then presented to Johan Nordenfelt from
the department of disarmament affairs.
   But before the meeting they sang peace songs and whooped and
clapped in a happy outburst that was heard in the General
Assembly's main hall a few dozen yards away from the lobby.
   ``I have a complaint from the General Assembly,'' said
Nordenfelt, glancing at a slip of paper. ``They hear your shouting
_ very well. Very good. You are the voice of the future. But please
don't shout.''
   ``Perhaps ... Kids Meeting Kids Can Make a Difference'' was
founded in 1982 to bring together Soviet and American children .
   This year the group expanded to include children from other
countries.
   In 1984 the organization began a pen-pal exchange between Soviet
and American children that has grown to include more than 350,000
correspondents, according to the group.
   About 140 children from more than 50 countries attended this
week's ``summit'' that ended Friday.
   Their expenses in New York were paid by the Kids Meeting Kids
organization. All or part of the travel expenses for some of the
younsters from foreign countries, including China and the Soviet
Union, were paid by their governments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     06-10 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Wins Majority in Provincial Council Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing United National Party
won 36 the 53 District Council seats in the southern province,
according to results released Friday by the Elections Department.
   The elections were marred by three days of terrorist attacks
that left at least 12 people dead. Most of the killings were blamed
on extremists of the Sinhalese ethnic majority, who opposed the
elections.
   Fifteen seats went to the United Socialist Alliance, a coalition
of leftist parties, and independents won the other two. The
election was held Thursday.
   The government party has won control of all seven District
Councils for which elections have been held. Those in the
Tamil-dominated northern and eastern regions have been delayed by
fighting between Indian peacekeeping troops and Tamil rebels, but
the government hopes to hold them next month.
   Council elections were required under the agreement Sri Lanka
and India signed last July in an attempt to end the Tamil
separatist war, which has taken more than 8,000 lives since it
began in 1983.
   Guerrillas of the Tamil ethnic minority, who want a separate
homeland in the north and east to be called Eelam, were to lay down
their arms in exchange for more autonomy in those regions.
   The largest group refused, however, and India has more than
50,000 soldiers in Sri Lanka trying to stop the rebellion.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of the
island's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the majority
Sinhalese, a predominantly Buddhist ethnic group that controls the
government and army.
   Sinhalese extremists contend the peace agreement made too many
concessions to Tamils and said they would kill anyone who supports
the accord. They were blamed for outbreaks of pre-election violence.
</TEXT>
