<DOCNO> AP880610-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britian-Videos     06-10 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britian-Videos,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Law Restricting Home Video Taping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britons who make videotapes of television programs
would be forced to erase or destroy such tapes within 28 days under
a law proposed by the Conservative Party government.
   The measure, which could become law this summer, is aimed at
preventing viewers from building up home libraries with videotapes
of television shows and films, depriving copyright holders of
royalties.
   Opposition leaders have called the proposal unenforceable.
   ``How is it going to be policed?'' asked Austin Mitchell, the
Labor Party's trade and industry spokesman. ``Are we going to start
marketing tapes that automatically explode 28 days after they have
been used for the first time?''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government made the proposal
as an amendment to the Copyright, Designs and Patents Bill of 1956.
   A House of Commons committee approved the amendment by a vote of
11-7 Thursday.
   Susie Hughes, a spokeswoman for the Department of Trade and
Industry, said Friday the amendment relaxes retrictions on
``time-shifting,'' the taping of programs to be watched later,
because it gives viewers a ``28-day grace period.''
   Time-shifting is illegal under the international Berne
Convention on Copyrights, which Britain signed, but the restriction
is rarely enforced.
   Ms. Hughes said the measure would make time-shifting a civil
crime, clearing the way for copyright holders to sue for damages to
be determined by a court.
   Bob Montgomery, chairman of the Mechanical Copyright Protection
Society, complained that the measure did not go far enough.
   Mrs. Thatcher's consumer affairs minister, Francis Maude, said
the government was trying to balance the interests of viewers and
copyright owners.
   He was asked in a BBC-TV interview how the government would
enforce the measure and he said he thought viewers would comply
voluntarily.
   ``We are not going to set up a force of tape police breaking
into people's homes to investigate their video libraries _ that is
obviously absurd,'' he said.
   Ms. Hughes said the copyright bill probably would complete the
committee stage in a few weeks and then go for a vote of the full
House of Commons.
   It then will go back to the House of Lords, where it originated,
for final approval, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
