<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Iran     06-10 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iran,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain, Iran Agree on Compensation for Damaged Embassies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office said Britain and Iran reached
agreement Friday on a compensation deal for damage inflicted on
their embassies in violent incidents.
   Iran is expected to net about $1.6 million as a result of the
deal, reached after three days of talks in London between British
and Iranian officials.
   ``Broad agreement has been reached on the basis of the proposals
put forward by the British government in May 1987,'' said a Foreign
Office statement.
   Under those proposals, Iran will pay Britain for damage
inflicted by mobs on the British Embassy and associated buildings
in Tehran in the late 1970s, and Britain will pay a larger sum for
the burning of the Iranian Embassy in London during a 1980 hostage
siege and rescue.
   The Iranian Embassy declined comment on the talks.
   British newspapers and politicians of the governing Conservative
Party have welcomed the negotiations. They say the negotiations may
lead to improved relations with Iran and better chances of freeing
Western hostages _ at least two of whom are British _ held by
pro-Iranian kidnappers in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
