<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeaponsProtest     06-10 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weapons Protest,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Naval Weapons Station Protest A Year Old</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marines in riot gear helped arrest 14
anti-war protesters Friday at the Concord Naval Weapons Station a
few hours after a gathering marked a year of almost daily peace
demonstrations at the base.
   Those arrested were expected to be booked for investigation of
misdemeanor trespassing, said Lt. J.D. Sizemore, a Contra Costa
County sheriff's deputy.
   The confrontation involving the Marines occurred without
violence at a base gate near what the demonstrators say is a bunker
containing nuclear weapons. Base officials do not comment on
whether nuclear material is present.
   The demonstrators marched to the gate after a morning gathering
at which they were addressed by S. Brian Willson, who lost his legs
Sept. 1 when he was hit by a train at the base while protesting
weapons shipments to Central America.
   Willson and other speakers spoke to about 200 people as a fabric
dove of peace flapped above in a gentle breeze. A banner nearby
read, ``Stopping The War Starts Here.''
   ``I feel great,'' Willson told a reporter. ``With all these
people here, how can I not feel good?''
   He bristled when asked what he felt he had accomplished.
   ``I don't base expressions of conscience on what I'm
accomplishing. I'm expressing what I feel and sharing it with the
rest of these people here.
   ``I'm more committed than ever to wage unconditional peace.''
   In his speech, Willson said, ``It gives me great joy to be here
with you all who have made this place so sacred and empowered.
   ``The human spirit and the truth cannot be squashed,'' he said.
``The spirit of Gandhi and King and Jesus and Buddha cannot be
squashed, no matter how many bombs and weapons are manufactured and
unleased in incredible diabolical policies on this earth.''
   The Willson incident and the year-long vigil have spawned
lawsuits, including several charging sheriff's deputies with using
excessive force while arresting demonstrators blocking train tracks.
   Protesters won an injunction barring a county plan to remove
tables and other material from the side of the highway after
complaints and petitions bearing 800 signatures from residents of
the nearby town of Clyde.
   Willson also is suing, seeking damages for the loss of both legs
at the knee when he was struck by a train hauling 2.8 tons of
munitions to the military reservation.
   The train crew has countersued, charging Willson and others
planned to be hit to halt the train and claiming they suffered
mental anguish after the incident.
   House investigators said in March that Willson and base
officials shared equal blame for the accident.
   Willson, a Vietnam veteran, law school graduate and unsuccessful
candidate for sheriff in Chautauqua, N.Y., won praise in Soviet
newspapers and a hero's welcome when he and other activists visited
Nicaragua in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
