<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0798 06-10 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0798,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Denies `Mud-Slinging' Charge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf pvs bgng, `Bob Dole,' to
UPDATE with comments by Robertson, Dole and Kemp; DELETES bottom 8
grafs to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush said Friday that Democratic
rival Michael Dukakis resorted to ``the oldest ploy in the game''
by accusing Bush of using dirty campaign tactics.
   ``Already, we're hearing charges of `mudslinging' from the other
side,'' Bush told a unity gathering featuring four of his
vanquished GOP rivals as well as Republican officials and activists
from Western states.
   Earlier, Bush told reporters he had shifted his campaign into a
more aggressive attack on the Massachusetts governor after
``getting hit for six months'' by the Democrats. ``This is going to
be a fun campaign,'' the vice president said.
   In his speech, Bush said, ``I look forward to the next two
months, because this is the defining time. This is the time when
the American people will begin to focus on who we are and what we
stand for, not compared to others of our party, but compared to
each other.''
   ``Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, Pete du Pont, Al Haig ... they're all
good men and tough competitors,'' Bush said. ``I never liked the
strain of finding differences with my fellow Republicans.''
   Before Bush spoke, he was praised by Dole, Kemp, du Pont and
Haig. And television evangelist Pat Robertson sent a letter saying
he couldn't make the event because of a scheduling conflict, but
that Bush had ``earned and deserves'' the support of conservatives.
   ``You've got to have experience, and George Bush has it all over
Michael Dukakis, day after day after day,'' Dole said.
   Kemp said Bush is ``our nominee, and very frankly, I look
forward to working with Bob and Al and Pete and Pat to make sure we
have a Republican in 1988.''
   Bush said his new campaign strategy, beginning with a Thursday
speech in which he cited many differences with Dukakis on specific
issues, ``represented a turning point.''
   ``It's my job now not just to say what I'm for, but to give the
American people the facts about Governor Dukakis,'' he said. Bush
said Dukakis should understand that.
   ``Governor Dukakis is a tough campaigner _ just ask (onetime GOP
gubernatorial rival) Ed King _ and I expect the same from him,'' he
said. ``I am not going to be deterred from telling the truth.''
   Earlier, Bush had said he wasn't surprised that the Dukakis camp
protested his charge of Thursday _ that the Massachusetts governor
is a liberal posing as a moderate.
   But in a chat with reporters aboard Air Force Two en route to
Denver for the unity gathering with some of his defeated Republican
opponents, the certain GOP nominee said Democrats are trying to
hide Dukakis' record.
   At the same time, Bush, a late 1940s Yale graduate, offered no
apology for labeling Dukakis a political figure born of ``Harvard
Yard's boutique,'' saying it was meant as a statement about the
governor's supposed intellectual elitism, rather than as a
statement about class.
   Shortly after Bush attacked Dukakis on a broad range of foreign
policy and domestic issues on Thursday, the governor's press
secretary issued a statement saying Bush was panicked by his
relatively low standing in the polls and was resorting to
``mudslinging and tearing down.''
   Standing on a tarmac at Denver's Stapleton Airport, Bush said
Friday he thought it curious that the Dukakis campaign
``immediately sallied forth'' with the accusation of dirty politics.
   ``You're looking at a guy who's been getting hit for six months,
guilt by association, and all kinds of personal attacks,'' the vice
president said. ``What happens now, they raise the mudslinging
thing,'' he said. ``This is going to be a fun campaign.''
   Aboard the vice presidential jet, Bush noted a statement that
Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., had released Thursday night in defense
of Dukakis' views.
   ``There's this whole concept that he's a conservative and all,''
Bush said. ``It's a game plan by the Democrats to protect him from
his record.''
   Bush said that with Jesse Jackson's long-haul Democratic primary
race, ``I think he's (Dukakis) done a good job during the primary
season of being shoved to the center'' of the political spectrum.
</TEXT>
