<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Food     06-10 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Food,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good Harvest Reported In Food-Short Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam said Friday a good rice crop
has eased critical food shortages in some areas but that the nation
still needs assistance.
   The communist government has appealed for international aid,
especially for the northern regions. Natural disasters ravaged last
year's winter and spring rice crops.
   ``With the harvest having begun, here and there the food
situation in the food-deficient provinces in the north has eased
visibly, but much remains to be done to bring about a durable and
all-around solution,'' the official Vietnam News Agency said.
   The report said the recent harvest in the Mekong River delta of
the south, Vietnam's main rice-producing area, was estimated at
240,000 to 300,000 tons more than last year.
   Farmers in the north's Red River delta are preparing for the
harvest, which usually comes a month after the southern harvest,
VNA said.
   This year's output is estimated at 6,160-6,600 pounds of rice
per hectare, up from 4,840 pounds last year, the ageny reported. A
hectare is 2.47 acres.
   The agency added, however, that the increase ``is barely enough
to make up for the heavy losses caused by natural calamities in
last year's crop.''
   Twenty percent of Vietnam's people live in the Red River delta
but it accounts for only 5 percent of the cultivated area.
</TEXT>
