<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     06-10 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>El Salvador Rebels Talk With U.S. Congressmen, Rightists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   El Salvador's leftist rebels said Friday that
the illness of President Jose Napoleon Duarte has worsened the
political and military crisis in their country.
   A rebel spokesman said the insurgents are preparing for possible
major upheaval in El Salvador and have made new contacts with U.S.
congressmen and El Salvador's right-wing Arena Party.
   ``We're more than sure that the situation in El Salvador will
probably change a lot in the coming months,'' Salvador Samayoa told
a news conference.
   ``It will probably become the most complicated and difficult in
Central America. We think it is dangerous if the United States
doesn't have any options.''
   Doctors revealed last week that Duarte, the United States'
closest ally in Central America, has terminal cancer. Duarte, 62,
is in the last year of his five-year term.
   Samayoa said the rebel alliance has had ``some exploratory talks
with the offices of some senators and congressmen aimed at opening
a dialogue ... so that the new (U.S.) administration, be it
Republican or Democratic, will have options and not dead-end
policies like that of the administration that is ending.''
   The Reagan administration has poured huge amounts of aid into El
Salvador during Duarte's presidency, but failed to help him end the
more than 8-year-old civil war or to shore up Duarte's Christian
Democratic Party.
   Samayoa refused to identify the American legislators or give
details of the talks, which he said were ``preliminary'' and
``exploratory.'' He said both Republicans and Democrats were
approached.
   He said the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the
guerrilla alliance, also has had exploratory talks with Arena,
which badly defeated the Christian Democrats in National Assembly
and municipal elections in March.
   Coup rumors began circulating in El Salvador after the elections.
   Samayoa said Duarte's illness is deepening El Salvador's
political and military crisis.
   ``I don't know if any of the political parties, if the armed
forces, if the government, if the North Americans see a way out of
the crisis,'' he said.
   The spokesman said the rebels have no formal talks scheduled
with U.S. officials.
   He said the Farabundo Marti alliance also hopes to make contact
with the Honduran armed forces in hopes of defusing tensions along
the border. He accused the Hondurans of cooperating closely with
the Salvadoran armed forces in the Salvadorans' battle with the
rebels.
</TEXT>
