<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Tarradellas     06-10 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Tarradellas,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catalonian Leader Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Josep Tarradellas, one of the few
remaining figures of Spain's 1936-39 Second Republic and former
head of the autonomous Catalonian government, died Friday. He was
89.
   Tarradellas was taken to Barcelona's Quiron Clinic Friday
suffering from a chronic lung ailment and died three hours after
admission, according to a medical bulletin.
   His wife, Antonio Macia, was at his side when he died, clinic
officials said.
   Tarradellas was the last major Republican exile to return to
Spain following the death of dictator Gen. Francisco Franco in
November 1975. He came back in 1977.
   Under Spain's 1978 constitution that restored democracy,
Catalonia recovered its autonomous status lost when Franco's forces
emerged victorious in the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War.
   King Juan Carlos named Tarradellas head of the Catalonian
autonomous government of Generalitat in 1979.
   When he fled Spain in 1939, Tarradellas vowed never to set foot
in the country until Catalonian autonomy had been restored.
   During the first years of his exile in France, Tarradellas was
arrested at least 14 times by the Nazi Gestapo and the French
police.
   In 1941 Franco requested his extradition from Nazi-occupied
France, but because of a bureaucratic error Tarradellas managed to
cross the French border into Switzerland.
   He was interned in Switzerland and later freed under the
protection of the Mexican Embassy until the end of World War II.
   A son, Josep, was born during Tarradellas' Swiss exile and is
now a professor at the University of Lausanne.
   Tarradellas was elected head of the Generalitat-in-exile by
Catalonian deputies gathered in the Mexican Embassy in Bern after
Generalitat President Lluis Campanys was returned to Spain from his
French exile and executed in 1946.
   Tarradellas and his family moved to St. Martin Le Beau nears
Tours, France, in 1956 and remained there until 1977.
   Upon his triumphal return to Barcelona Oct. 20, 1977,
Tarradellas stood on the balcony of the Generalitat assembly
building and shouted in the Catalonian language ``Ja, soc aqui!''
Now I`m here!
   Tarradellas retired from politics in 1980.
   The funeral is scheduled for Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
