<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Children'sHome     06-10 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Scatter As State Takes Over Baptist Boarding Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 140 children fled a Baptist boarding
home Friday and scattered in a nearby town after allegations of
child abuse at the home prompted a judge to put them temporarily in
state custody, authorities said.
   ``Prior to the time we arrived at the Bethel campus, the
children had scattered,'' state Welfare Commissioner Thomas
Brittain said of the Bethel Home for Children in the southeast
Misssissippi town of Lucedale.
   ``We were told they were allowed, if not encouraged, to leave
the campus, and some of the children said they were told to run,''
he said.
   The youngsters were found in private homes, restaurants and
walking the streets of Lucedale, said state police and George
County sheriff's deputies.
   By Friday night, about 60 children, mostly teen-agers, had been
bused to quarters at the Mississippi State Hospital at Whitfield,
Brittain said. He said they were undergoing physical examinations.
   Brittain estimated 80 youths remained missing and that officers
would be searching for them through the weekend.
   It wasn't known exactly how many children had been at the home
because its operator, the Rev. Herman Fountain, was released Friday
after two days in jail for refusing to give authorities with a list
of the children in his care.
   Brittain said Fountain was at the home when Welfare Department
officials arrived. ``We did not encounter any cooperation from him
there. In fact, it was just the opposite,'' Brittain said. He would
not elaborate.
   The welfare Department workers arrived at the home minutes after
Youth Court Judge Robert Oswald of Pascagoula ruled there was
probable cause to suspect physical and mental child abuse at the
independent Baptist institution.
   A hearing in the case is scheduled for 9:30 a.m. Monday in
Lucedale.
   Fountain, and several other ministers who flocked from
Louisiana, Georgia and Texas to support him, claim such boarding
homes are protected from any state regulation because of the
constitutional separation of church and state.
   Oswald ruled that the children were being held in detention
according to the state Youth Act. Detention facilities are required
to notify the state of children placed in their custody.
   Fountain was freed Friday without providing the information when
he agreed there would be an orderly transfer of the children to
state custody.
   Brittain said he wasn't sure what action may be taken against
Fountain.
   The court order gives the state 48-hour temporary custody of the
children, not including Saturday and Sunday.
   Brittain said welfare officials would attempt to locate and
return the children to their parents within that time period. But
he expected it might take longer to find all of the children.
   ``We have information that some folks are trying to help the
kids escape out of state,'' he said.
   Based on experience with the Bethesda Home for Girls near
Hattiesburg, where about 100 residents were taken into state
custody in September 1986, Brittain said the children's parents may
be scattered across the nation.
   Oswald's order Friday followed a week-long hearing on a request
for such action by George County authorities. The hearing also
concerned the legal status of a child who ran away from the Bethel
Home For Children.
</TEXT>
