<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WashingtonDescendants     06-10 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Washington Descendants,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First President's Progeny Descend On Philadelphia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Washington is called the father of
his country, but he is also called uncle and cousin to ancestors of
hundreds of members of a group in Philadelphia to celebrate their
relation to the first president.
   Members of the National Society of Washington Family Descendants
are holding their annual meeting here this weekend because, they
say, Philadelphia is second only to the commonwealth of Virginia in
importance to Washington's destiny.
   ``He was appointed general here, served in the first Continental
Congress, he was appointed chairman of that (Constitutional)
convention and served most of his presidency in this town,'' said
Elmer E. Lybrand, president general of the society.
   Lybrand said he is Washington's
great-great-great-great-great-nephew.
   The society includes many other nephews several generations
removed _ and nieces and cousins _ some 700 people who trace their
bloodline to Washington's parents, Augustine Washington and Mary
Ball.
   ``They have to turn in their papers and prove each and every
generation _ we have a genealogist that checks it out,'' Lybrand
said.
   Proof is usually established through marriage records, wills and
birth and death certificates.
   The society was formed in 1954 and has met every year since.
This year's meeting in Philadelphia drew 37 members Friday and will
continue through the weekend.
   Participants on Friday went to the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier
of the Revolutionary War for a wreath-laying ceremony attended by
the Marquis Jean Pierre deChambrun, the great-great-great-grandson
of French soldier and Revolutionary War hero Marquis de Lafayette.
   Lybrand, 64, a real-estate businessman from Pine Bluff, Ark.,
said the society gathers ``just to visit historical places, hear
speeches, and visit with other relatives.''
   ``We promote the history and memory of General George Washington
and we also learn a great deal ourselves too, which gives us
pleasure,'' Lybrand said.
   The society is important to him and the older people who make up
a majority of the group's membership for other reasons.
   ``I think a feeling of your place in history _ you know that you
are continuous _ that someone came before you and someone else came
after _ it becomes more important as you grow older.''
</TEXT>
