<HEAD>Rescue Teams Search for Final Missing Miner in Borken Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of two more bodies in
the Borken coal mine left only one man missing Friday from the
worst mining disaster in West Germany in 26 years, officials
reported.
   Peter-Carl Ruehland, a spokesman for the Preussen Elektra mine
owner, said search teams were working with ``undiminished
intensity'' to find the missing man.
   Officials have said there is no chance he could have survived
the June 1 gas explosion that ripped through the Stolzenbach mine
in Borken, 72 miles northeast of Frankfurt.
   The confirmed death count with the recovery of two more bodies
is 50. Six miners were rescued June 4 after spending 65 hours
trapped up to 500 feet underground.
   Klaus-Peter Moeller, chairman of the Hesse state legislature's
interior committee, told reporters Thursday that officials believe
a ``thorough and comprehensive investigation'' of the explosion
would take about a year.
   A local prosecutor has opened an investigation to determine if
an ``open flame'' may have caused the explosion. Mine officials
have said smoking was strictly forbidden inside the mine.
