<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Transplants     06-10 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transplants,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Shows One In 10 Hearts, Livers Unused</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Kelle is cq in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least one out of 10 hearts and livers
removed from donors for transplanting never reaches a dying patient
and is discarded, the national network for organ sharing said
Friday.
   ``We'll never have a perfect system. But we're sure working
toward one,'' said Kelle Straw, a spokeswman for the United Network
for Organ Sharing.
   Organs often have gone unused because they could not be matched
immediately with a patient, and because of insufficient numbers of
transplant surgeons and inadequate hospital space, she said.
   The UNOS study included all hearts and livers recovered from
brain-dead patients from Oct. 1, when a national transplant
registry became active, through May 15.
   During the 7{-month period, 905 hearts and 831 livers were
recovered and reported to the network, Ms. Straw said.
   Nearly 85 percent of the hearts, or 769, and almost 90 percent
of the livers, or 744, were transplanted, she said. The rest were
used for research or thrown away.
   The study, done by computer analysis of the registry, was
prompted by last week's report by the University of Rochester Organ
Procurement Program that up to half of all suitable livers and
hearts donated to the New York program were going to waste.
   The unused organs cited by the Rochester group were not removed
from the donors' bodies. The UNOS study cited organs that were
removed in anticipation of transplant surgery. The difference
accounted for at least part of the large disparity in the
percentage of donor organs used, said officials at both groups.
   UNOS, meanwhile, is tracking the number of all hearts and livers
that were donated for transplantation but were never removed. The
data is expected in about a week, said Ms. Straw.
   ``We had potential donors, with the emphasis on potential, that
we couldn't realize because we couldn't find a recipient for the
organ,'' the University of Rochester's Dr. John Ricotta said Friday.
   Ricotta told the American Society of Transplant Surgeons on June
3 in Chicago that a leading obstacle to matching donor organs with
recipients is outdated patient lists, including insufficient
information about patients' blood type and body size.
   Some organs were turned away because transplant teams were too
busy or too tired and hospital space was limited, Ricotta said.
Some hospitals preferred waiting for a local donor, while still
others said they didn't think the organs suited their needs.
   ``There are a lot of reasons why an organ might not be used,''
Ms. Straw explained. ``We're doing the best that we can here, and
we're looking into different areas to make it fair and equitable
and to improve transplantation.''
   Procedures in compiling the patient waiting lists are evolving,
and Ricotta said it's too early to know whether the Rochester
center is making better use of the hearts and livers offered to it.
   The Virginia-based UNOS has a federal contract to run the
national Organ Procurement and Transplantation Network, which links
by computer all transplant centers and organ procurement agencies.
   ``UNOS maintains the national computer system, however, it is
the responsiblity of the transplant center to see that data of its
recipients is accurate and current,'' said Gene Pierce, the
network's executive director
</TEXT>
