<HEAD>Local Workers To Take Over Red Cross Relief In North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The local Red Cross will take over relief efforts
for victims of drought in northern Ethiopia after foreign relief
workers were ordered to leave because of rebel insurgencies, the
world Red Cross body said Friday.
   The revived relief program is to provide food aid for at least
500,000 people in Tigre, Eritrea and Gondar provinces, the League
of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies said in a statement.
   An estimated 3.2 million people face starvation in Eritrea and
Tigre, where secessionist wars rage.
   Ethiopian authorities have said no major foreign aid worker
presence in the north will be allowed until the rebellions in
Eritrea and Tigre are ended. It accused the all-Swiss International
Committee of the Red Cross of running covert operations in the
region and of supporting the guerrillas.
   The Committee says it is pledged to strict neutrality.
   The Ethiopian Red Cross has agreed to run the operation under
supervision of the League, the Geneva-based worldwide Red Cross
coordinating body, spokeswoman Ann Naef said.
   The League said it will appoint a special coordinator for the
program.
   The accord will replace the International Committee of the Red
Cross in northern Ethiopia. The Committee on Tuesday announced
formal suspension of its aid effort after the government ordered
its delegates and other foreign aid workers out of the region in
April, citing security reasons.
   Ethiopian authorities later pressed the International Committee
to turn over relief supplies locked up in northern Ethiopia.
   The agency is now asking permission from donors to turn over
those supplies to the League ``so aid can resume without further
delay,'' the League said.
   ICRC stocks in Ethiopia include 36,000 tons, mostly grain, worth
$15 million. The agency has 208 vehicles, including 91 trucks.
</TEXT>
