<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosions Knock Out Power In Parts Of Peru</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials blamed leftist rebels for explosions
Friday night that caused temporary power blackouts across central
Peru, including sections of Lima.
   There were conflicting reports about possible sites of the
explosions.
   Police in Ayacucho, 235 miles southeast of Lima, reported three
explosions and said they were investigating.
   Radio Programas, a news station, quoted officials of the state
utility firm Electro Sur-Medio as saying rebels had sabotaged
transmission equipment near Huancayo, 130 miles east of Lima.
   The station, carrying reports from correspondents in several
cities, said the blackout began at 6:40 p.m. (7:40 p.m. EDT) in
about half of Lima and in a 600-mile zone reaching from the coast
into the central highlands.
   It said power was restored in most areas within a half hour.
   Peru's utility network has been a frequent rebel target, causing
widespread blackouts.
   Thursday night, guerrillas fired three 60-mm mortar rounds at
the U.S. Ambassador Alexander Watson's residence but police said
there were no injuries and there was only minor damage to the roof
of the two-story building.
   Shortly before midnight Thursday rebels threw explosives at four
Lima automobile firms, according to police who reported no injuries.
   Officials blamed Thursday's attacks on guerrillas of the
pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement.
   Peru has a shortage of auto-truck replacement parts, mainly
because of a lack of foreign currency. Critics have accused the
government of mismanangement and also claim distributors have been
speculating in spare parts.
   Tupac Amaru guerrillas have been active since 1984, but most of
their attacks have been made against targets and during hours when
few casualties would be inflicted.
   The Maoist Shining Path guerrilla movement emerged in 1980 and
has waged a bloody campaign of bombings and assassinations to
overthrow the government.
</TEXT>
