<HEAD>Town Outraged, Divided over Cop's Fatal Shooting of Hispanic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with agreement between
negotiators, quiet streets; picks up 6th graf: `Hispanic leaders .
..; edits below to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PERTH AMBOY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials and Hispanic leaders on
Friday agreed to work together to ease tensions triggered by the
fatal shooting of a Hispanic man by an off-duty police officer.
   For the first time in three nights, the streets of Perth Amboy
were quiet. On Wednesday and Thursday nights rock-throwing rioters
broke windows, looted and toppled a car in a display reminiscent of
the 1960s.
   Some said the rioting was the work of opportunist troublemakers
using the recent shooting as an excuse to wreak havoc in this
normally quiet industrial community evenly divided between whites
and Hispanics.
   The breakthrough in easing tensions came in a three-hour meeting
of Hispanic community leaders with Middlesex County Prosecutor Alan
Rockoff, Mayor George J. Otlowski and police officials.
   After the meeting Rockoff said that his office will investigate
the shooting and present the case to a county grand jury.
   ``I think the people are satisfied with the response of the
authorities, especially the prosecutor's office,'' said the Rev.
Richard Todd of Our Lady of Fatima Roman Catholic Church.
   The church held a funeral Mass for the slain man Thursday night
that was attended by more than 1,000 people.
   The two sides also agreed to form a commission to investigate
bias in the city and to form a community council to hear grievances
against the police, Rockoff said.
   Otlowski decided Friday against a curfew or closing bars and
liquor stores, saying that would only increase tensions. He said
Hispanic leaders should work with members of their community to
restore calm.
   Hispanic leaders responded by calling for the ouster of the
police chief.
   The violence was touched off when off-duty narcotics officer
Allen C. Fuller shot and killed Carmen Coria and critically wounded
Coria's brother, Matteo, outside a bar early Monday.
   Authorities are still investigating the case, but Fuller has
said he fired at the men because he believed his life was
threatened by Carmen Coria, who he said approached him holding a
bottle. Fuller was suspended with pay pending the outcome of the
investigation.
   Rockoff said his office will present its findings to a grand
jury.
   On Wednesday, small bands of people leaving a city council
meeting threw rocks through store windows and burned out trash cans.
   The problems worsened Thursday night when 1,000 marchers at a
funeral for Coria confronted police, who wore riot gear in
anticipation of trouble. Small bands of people also dispersed
through the business district, smashing store windows with
rock-filled plastic bags and toppling at least one car.
   Police arrested 20 people and some officers were hospitalized
after being hit with rocks.
   Hispanic leaders called for a special prosecutor to investigate
the shooting, but Otlowski said the county prosecutor could handle
the case.
   Members of the Hispanic community interviewed Friday said
Coria's shooting brought to a head tensions between the police
department and Hispanics.
   ``This is just the result of years of abuse,'' said Sam Cruz, a
member of the Hispanic Community Ad Hoc Committee and one of
Thursday night's marchers. ``We couldn't control them in the
streets. We don't want no violence.''
   Eddie Rodriguez, a lawyer for the Coria family, called for
police Chief Edward Mullen to step aside, blaming Mullen for
Thursday night's clash.
   ``We have communicated to the mayor the desire of the community
to end all real or perceived police overaction or inaction in many
instances where our people have been mistreated,'' Rodriguez said.
   On a street corner near the riot scene, a Hispanic man
identifying himself only as Manny said police officers frequently
abuse suspects by pushing them roughly, using bad language and in
some cases punching and kicking them.
   ``They should have a little moderation. They should have a
little more justification when they're throwing a guy around.
That's all. Be a little more moderate,'' said Manny.
   The mayor declined to comment further on Fuller, but said the
109-member police force had at least 12 allegations of brutality in
recent years and ``three or four'' officers had been fired or
resigned because of such allegations.
   Otlowski and police officers who spoke on condition they not be
identified said most of the rioters were people commonly in trouble
with the law, taking their frustrations out against the city for
reasons that have nothing to do with racial tension.
   ``Some of these guys last night I see every day,'' said one
officer who asked his name not be used. ``Some of them don't even
live here.''
   In August 1966, an anti-loitering ordinance appeared to set off
four nights of violence after a Hispanic man was arrested.
Hispanics said the ordinance violated their custom of visiting with
friends on the street. They also complained then of rough treatment
by police and of being ignored by the community.
</TEXT>
