<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0805,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dry Day Follows Record Morning Lows</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Fla. twister, hail; picks
up 5th graf: `Thunderstorms developed ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dry weather prevailed across much of the nation Friday as a
large high pressure system responsible for record low temperatures
pushed moisture that had been over the eastern half of the nation
out to sea.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued along the southern Atlantic
Coast, generating a tornado that ripped off the roofs of two houses
in Orange Park in north Florida.
   A wind gust to 39 mph and small hail were reported at
Jacksonville, Fla., and pea-size hail fell at Fernandina Beach, Fla.
   Thunderstorms developed Friday afternoon in the central and
southern Rockies and in the Del Rio, Texas, area.
   Showers continued in parts of Washington state, with a half-inch
of rain at Bellingham and around a quarter-inch at Tacoma and
Seattle in the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Scattered frost and freezing temperatures were expected Saturday
morning in some of the valleys of the northern and central
Appalachians.
   Afternoon temperatures were in the 60s and 70s over a large part
of the nation. Readings were only in the lower 60s along the
Carolina coast because of low clouds and occasional rain.
   The northern and central Appalachians and the Washington and
Oregon coast registered some 50s while North Dakota and eastern
Montana had readings well into the 90s. Williston, N.D., reached
102 degrees, tying a record for the date.
   Record low temperatures for the date included Allentown, Pa.,
43; Asheville, N.C., 44; Beckley, W.Va., 38; Birmingham, Ala., 50;
Calico Rock, Ark., 42; Columbus, Ohio, 41; Elkins, W.Va. 33;
Evansville, Ind., 48; Fayetteville, Ark., 47; Huntsville, Ala., 51;
Jonesboro, Ark., 51; Kansas City, Mo., 47; Lexington, Ky., 43;
Mansfield, Ohio, 39; Nashville, 50; Paducah, Ky., 51; Parkersburg,
W.Va. 40; Peoria, Ill. 42; Philadelphia, 47; Roanoke, Va., 44;
Rochester, N.Y., 37; Syracuse, N.Y. 37; Topeka, Kan., 43; Wilkes
Barre-Scranton, Pa. 37; and Wilmington, Del., 46.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at Pullman, Wash., and Mullan, Idaho, to 101 degrees at
Miles City, Mont. The nation's low Friday morning was 27 degrees at
Franklinville, N.Y.
   Saturday's forecast called for thunderstorms scattered over the
Rocky Mountain states and southwest Texas, showers over parts of
Washington and Oregon, and scattered to numerous showers and
thunderstorms in central and southern Florida.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s or 80s across most of
the nation, except 60s in parts of the Appalachians, along the New
England coast, in the Pacific Northwest and in northwest Montana;
in the 90s in northwest Minnesota and the western Plains; near 100
degrees in eastern Montana and 105 degrees in the Big Bend area of
southwest Texas; and 90s to near 105 degrees in the desert
Southwest.
</TEXT>
