</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS education is paying off, with more than
two-thirds of adults recently surveyed saying children with AIDS
should be allowed to attend school with other youngsters, the
American Medical Association said today.
   In addition, 80 percent of 1,500 adults surveyed in February
said they knew ``a lot'' about AIDS, compared with only 69 percent
who said they knew ``a lot'' or ``a fair amount'' in a similar
survey last year.
   ``It is gratifying to see that the AIDS education efforts of the
past year have helped,'' said Dr. James H. Sammons, AMA executive
vice president, in a statement accompanying results of the survey.
   ``Although we are encouraged by the progress, the AMA will
continue to work toward having 100 percent of the public confident
in their knowledge about AIDS,'' he added in the statement in the
organization's weekly newspaper, American Medical News.
   The February survey found that 68 percent of adults said
children with AIDS should be allowed to attend regular class; 18
percent said they should not; and 14 percent were unsure.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>POINT OF THE MOUNTAIN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Eagle Scout who
sought his own execution for the sex-related murders of five boys
went calmly to his death today, saying, ``Though perhaps too little
too late, I am doing the right thing now.''
   Arthur Gary Bishop, a 36-year-old former bookkeeper and
excommunicated Mormon, was pronounced dead by injection at Utah
State Prison at 12:16 a.m., said Myron March, Department of
Corrections director of field operations.
   ``He went peacefully to the execution chamber,'' March said.
Three drugs in succession _ sodium pentothal, the muscle relaxant
Pavulon and potassium chloride _ were dripped intravenously into
Bishop's right arm.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sex for sale at Harrods? Prince Charles's polo
manager in a massage parlor? Sex frolics in a parliamentary shower
room? England's cricket captain fired for having female company in
his hotel room?
   Recent weeks have yielded an unusually rich harvest of lurid
tales for London's anything-goes tabloid newspapers. With the
firing of captain Michael Gatting on Thursday, it seems that not
even the genteel world of cricket is being spared.
   Gatting, 31, was summoned by the team selectors to answer
newspaper allegations that two of his players had sex on a lawn
outside their hotel Sunday night, and that he took a woman to his
room for sex.
   The alleged offense, as far as the selectors were concerned, was
that it happened while a five-day game, or test, was in progress
against the West Indies in Nottinghamshire.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OAK PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He used to sit forlornly in his wheelchair
while other children were swinging and sliding. But 11-year-old
David Hyde won't be an outsider in the new ``Playground for All
Children.''
   The 75-by-140 foot playground, to be dedicated today at Holmes
Elementary School in this Chicago suburb, is designed to be fully
accessible to children confined to wheelchairs _ as well as to kids
who aren't disabled.
   ``I'm excited to play in it because it looks fun and
interesting,'' said David, a 6th-grader who suffers from muscular
dystrophy. ``Before, I would just sit around and watch. There was
nothing else to do.''
