<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy smokers tend to snack more than
non-smokers, and men who smoke heavily are more likely to be
overweight, says a government study that seems to run counter to
the perception that tobacco helps hold weight down.
   While much medical and media attention in recent years has
focused on the dangers of smoking itself, the new report observes
that people who smoke also tend to have other bad health habits.
   Smokers are more likely than non-smokers to sleep less than six
hours daily, to skip breakfast, to be physically inactive and to be
heavier drinkers, according to the National Center for Health
Statistics.
