<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Highway-StarWars Adv20   06-10 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway-Star Wars, Adv 20,0846</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientific Questions Remain About Star Wars Technology</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nuclear Highway I</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guided by the longest list of computer
instructions ever written, it would destroy Soviet missiles with
laser beams and projectiles as small as a coffee can.
   But five years after President Reagan called for the Strategic
Defense Initiative, popularly called ``Star Wars,'' some scientists
still challenge it as a fantastical system unlikely to do the job.
   The problems are more complex than those conquered in putting an
astronaut on the moon, they say, because SDI must deal with future
strategies of an opponent determined to foil it.
   As a result, ``it's difficult to say if we can build a system
that will work well against the offense which might exist 10 or 15
years from now,'' said Kumar Patel of AT&T Bell Laboratories.
   Other experts inside and outside the Pentagon express confidence
the problems can be overcome, providing a system effective enough
to discourage the Soviets from attacking.
   Dozens of SDI projects are on drawing boards and in test
laboratories up and down a single stretch of interstate that links
New Mexico, Colorado and Wyoming. The scientists and military
experts working on Star Wars along I-25, America's Nuclear Highway,
are enthusiastic. They say this is their generation's Manhattan
Project _ this generation's chance to make a startling change in
the nation's defense.
   The best-known candidates for SDI weapons are ``directed
energy'' devices such as the laser, which would burn a foot-wide
hole in a missile in less than few seconds.
   But current devices would need so much more development to
become SDI weapons that it might take eight years or more before
scientists know if they would be feasible, said Harvard physicist
Nicolaas Bloembergen, co-chairman of a recent study of such weapons
for the American Physical Society.
   The weapons would have to be much more powerful than current
versions, he said, and in building them bigger ``new fundamental
problems can crop up,'' he said.
   One problem involves the fact that fluctuations in the
atmosphere can throw a laser beam out of focus. Researchers can
overcome that with low-power beams, Bloembergen said, but nobody
has shown such an ability with beams as strong as SDI would need.
   ``Fundamentally, we don't know how to take care of large
distortions,'' and it is difficult to predict when that problem may
be solved, said AT&T's Patel, who co-chaired the physical society
study with Bloembergen.
   But Gregory Canavan, assistant physics division leader at Los
Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico, believes it will take
only a few years to show lasers can work as part of the SDI system.
   ``I can't tell you feasibility is established. What I can tell
you is there don't appear to be any established barriers to
demonstrating feasibility,'' Canavan said.
   SDI lasers would be teamed with kinetic energy weapons, which
would fire projectiles to create high-speed collisions.
   Kinetic weapons are feasible in principle, but ``what you don't
know is whether you can build them small enough (to launch) and
cheap enough, and whether it will work well enough to make it an
interesting system,'' said John Pike, associate director for space
policy of the Federation of American Scientists.
   Projectiles launched from space would need to be about the size
of a coffee can, while those shot from Earth would be as big as a
6-foot human. But the projectiles tested so far have been about as
big as a Volkswagen, Pike said.
   They also cost far more than is feasible and don't have the
maneuverability needed for an effective weapon, he said.
   Col. Raymond Ross, director of the Kinetic Energy Office at the
Pentagon's Strategic Defense Initiative Organization, said current
projectiles are only for demonstrating the technology. Smaller ones
will be available for actual weapons design, he said.
   Smaller projectiles save money by using smaller rockets to
launch them, he said. Nobody knows what the cost of the actual
weapons would be because the figure depends on results of current
testing, he said.
   As for manueverability against Soviet missiles, ``we are
proceeding on the correct path to accomplish that,'' Ross said.
   SDI would also include software and instructions to tell
computers how to spot and track targets, coordinate the firing of
weapons, and do other tasks.
   Large software packages must be tested to see how well they
work. ``The fundamental problem with the SDI is you can't really do
that kind of full-scale operational testing without having a
nuclear war,'' said software researcher David Redell of Digital
Equipment Corp.
   Capt. John Donegan, program manager for the planned first phase
of SDI, replied that military systems are now tested with a
combination of physical and computer-generated targets. A similar
approach could effectively test early SDI software and probably the
versions to follow, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 20</NOTE>
