<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Highway II, Adv 21-2 Takes,0965</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>America's Nuclear Highway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part II: Nuclear Economy _ Boomtowns and Visions of Future Dollars</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserLogo
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Up and down Interstate 25 an economic boom is
underway, not because of gold or oil but because of a military and
technology explosion. It has brought billions of dollars to towns
big and small in New Mexico, Colorado and Wyoming. And even if
``Star Wars'' funding is cut, businessmen, scientists and
economists say the laboratories are here to stay, the science still
to be pursued. The second story in a four-part series, ``America's
Nuclear Highway,'' looks at the economic impact.
   ___</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With an office here and one in Denver,
Tony Montoya's small high-tech firm designs electronic circuit
boards and provides scientific expertise for local customers.
   Business is booming, you might say, because along America's
Nuclear Highway, Interstate 25, the local customers are not your
average computer or stereo shops.
   Montoya's customers create nuclear weapons.
   ``There have been some real odd shapes _ real compact,'' Montoya
said with a chuckle. ``We don't always know what they do with our
boards. But we have an idea.''
   The son of a New Mexico rancher has seen his enterprise, L&M
Technologies, triple its number of employees in three years, and
sales have risen four-fold to $3.6 million in 1987.
   L&M, which also designs components for satellites and the space
shuttle, is just one small part of the economic boom along I-25,
which links wide open rangeland around from Las Cruces, N.M., to
the Bighorn Mountains near Buffalo, Wyo.
   This decade, between the Reagan administration's military
buildup and the promise of ``Star Wars,'' known formally as the
Strategic Defense Initiative, billions of dollars have poured into
the corridor that connects Albuquerque and Denver, creating rapid
growth and some economic shelter from hard times in oil and farming.
   ``Our work is speckled all the way through _ all the way up and
down I-25,'' Montoya said. ``I'd rather be here than anywhere
else.''
   Last year, about $30 of every $1,000 the United States spent on
defense and energy was spent along I-25 _ more than $8.4 billion in
all. Per capita military spending in New Mexico is twice the
national average, and Colorado's per capita figure is one-third
higher. Wyoming, its role in I-25's military might largely confined
to the care and keeping of 200 missiles, receives less.
   In New Mexico, the largest employers are Los Alamos National
Laboratory, Sandia National Laboratories and Kirtland Air Force
Base _ all involved in nuclear weapons and Star Wars.
   As military appropriations rise and fall in Washington, so, too,
does the economy of this state.
   ``The federal government is the major industry in New Mexico. It
accounts for 15 percent of all jobs in the state,'' said Brian
McDonald, director of the Bureau of Business and Economic Research
at the University of New Mexico.
   ``Since 1976, we've had explosive growth,'' McDonald said.
Federal spending in the state, adjusted for inflation, has
increased 50 percent, he said.
   Spending has grown steadily over the decade, officials said,
because much of the SDI groundwork was done here _ even before
there was an SDI.
   The money tap ``didn't get turned on when the president
(introduced Star Wars) in 1983. There was $1 billion being spent
already on research,'' said Sidney Singer, associate director for
defense research and applications at Los Alamos.
   And entrepreneurs like Montoya, who did electronics work at
White Sands Missile Range near Las Cruces, N.M., before striking
out on his own, eagerly took advantage of all the government-funded
research and development.
   Sandia National Labs, where scientists design the devices to arm
nuclear bombs and conduct research into a host of weapons and
energy projects, spent $575 million in the ``commercial community''
in the last fiscal year, according to Jon Bedingfield, director of
procurement.
   Some $280 million of that came to the Albuquerque area, a
portion to Montoya's company.
   To help spread the greenbacks in the state, New Mexico
established research groups to aid ``technology transfer'' from
government to private business and set up a computer network that
links research projects all over the state.
   The idea was ``using the national labs for economic
development,'' said Martha Buddecke, one of the founders of
Technet, which enables a researcher at Las Cruces to use
supercomputers at Los Alamos hundreds of miles away.
   The spending spigot has not enriched every town and business
along I-25.
   Some cuts have been made in Star Wars programs, resulting in
more modest timetables, even layoffs. Other weapons research, of
course, continues regardless of decisions on SDI, merely the latest
project to capture the research spotlight.
   But government largesse on SDI and other defense projects helps
soften the blow to economies such as Colorado's, where the plunge
in petroleum and farm prices has been sorely felt.
   ``Our economy is still somewhat flat, but we feel we've bottomed
out on the no-growth of the past few years,'' said Curt Wiedeman,
assistant director of state planning and budgeting.
   Unlike New Mexico, where federal megalabs drive the economic
engine, Colorado relies heavily on civilian manufacturing and
business as well as mining and oil.
   But military installations in Denver and Colorado Springs, as
well as a growing high-tech alley paralleling I-25 along the Front
Range, play an increasingly important role in the state's overall
economy.
   Just as oil and farm prices began to drop, SDI spending kicked
in, keeping the state economy healthier than it might have been.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
