<DOCNO> AP880610-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-NuclearHighwayII Adv21-1stAdd   06-10 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Highway II, Adv 21-1st Add,0927</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>ALBUQUERQUE: have been.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A recent Census Bureau analysis shows federal spending in
Colorado has grown 64 percent since President Reagan took office.
Most of that increase has been military _ in Colorado, it jumped
from about $2 billion in 1981 to $4.3 billion last year.
   Colorado Springs, a prime beneficiary, is one of the fastest
growing metropolitan areas in the country. Due to a half-dozen
military installations and more than 100 aerospace, computer and
scientific research firms, the city has increased its population to
more than 350,000 people from 236,000 in 1970 and has been adding
about 6,000 jobs a year.
   ``When we saw we were running out of telephone numbers in the
303 code area, we decided to put the new area code, 719, in
southern Colorado,'' said Abel Chavez of Mountain Bell
Telephone.``We see a lot of things happening there.''
   The military is building a $100 million SDI complex in Colorado
Springs that will eventually house $1 billion worth of computer
wizardry to test Star Wars. The National Test Facility at Falcon
Air Force Station, also home to the Consolidated Space Operations
Center, is expected to employ up to 2,000 people by the end of 1992.
   In all, more than $2 billion in SDI contracts have been
earmarked for I-25's three states, estimates the Federation of
American Scientists, based in Washington, D.C.
   The federation, gathering information from a variety of sources,
including the Strategic Defense Initiative Office and Department of
Defense publications, has compiled a computerized data bank on SDI
contracts. It says its figures are current to March 1.
   By far the region's biggest recipient of Star Wars dollars is
New Mexico, said federation spokesman David Bourns. The federation
estimates contracts worth $1.59 billion have been awarded within
the state since SDI research and development began, with $773
million already spent.
   In Colorado, the federation said contracts totaling $751 million
have been assigned, with $191.8 million of that spent.
   Wyoming's SDI work, by comparison, is miniscule. Just $1 million
in contracts have been assigned there, with $34,500 spent so far on
research at the University of Wyoming in Laramie.
   In terms of military dollars coming into Wyoming, which has been
seriously crippled by energy and agriculture slumps and a steady
loss of population, F.E. Warren Air Force Base accounts for less
than 2.4 percent of state revenue.
   The anticipated installation of 100 MX missiles around Cheyenne,
along with resultant increases in personnel, construction and
services, was expected to produce a windfall for the region. When
Reagan's request was cut in half and just 50 MXs were scheduled,
the four-year project produced only $1.38 million in tax benefits.
   In addition, ``a lot of dollars that come into that base are
never making it off base,'' said Dick O'Gara, director of the
Center for Economic and Business Data in Cheyenne. ``(It) has its
own medical facilities, food, housing and recreation facilities.''
   For New Mexico, the driving force in its economy was created
quite by accident. The laboratory at Los Alamos was established by
J. Robert Oppenheimer, father of the atomic bomb, as his base for
the Manhattan Project.
   It was an area Oppenheimer knew from summer vacations to the
mountains near Santa Fe. And when he needed a secluded spot for
secret research, Oppenheimer came to New Mexico. The lab at Los
Alamos grew and now has nearly 9,000 employees _ the largest single
payroll in the state.
   About 160 miles away, the spot where the atomic bomb was tested
became White Sands Missile Range, where most conventional weapons,
missiles and SDI gizmos come to be tried out. White Sands has more
than 6,000 employees and, like the other labs, has Star Wars
construction under way.
   Sandia Labs found a home near Los Alamos and the air force base
used to service the area.
   Albuquerque, near both Los Alamos and Sandia, was chosen for the
Air Force Weapons Lab, which has a $342 million annual budget (60
percent of it for Star Wars), 1,000 employees and a mission to
explore ``any kind of energy source that would ruin the other guy's
day,'' according to spokesman Rich Garcia.
   And the pattern continues today. Six years ago, when the Air
Force established a Space Technology Center, it chose Albuquerque.
Add $197 million each year.
   ``This is where Sandia and Los Alamos were, and they do the
nuclear work. So it made sense for us to be located with them,''
said Garcia.
   Montoya would say much the same.
   ``Everything starts from that _ the first atomic bomb. The
high-tech movement here started way back in those early times. And
the Department of Defense and the Department of Energy grew into
this area,'' he said.
   About 90 percent of L&M's business is tied to Defense Department
money.
   ``We're bursting at the seams, and we're attempting to expand,''
he said.
   Those in business here could see SDI on the horizon and gear up
for the boom, he said. ``Certain tests were accomplished in the
late '60s that I was involved in _ like the first airborne laser
tests. I could see it coming.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus is the AP Mountain States regional
reporter, based in Denver. Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest
regional reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
