<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Highway-SDIGizmos Adv21   06-10 1050</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway-SDI Gizmos, Adv 21,1098</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 21, and Thereafter
^Buck Rogers Move Over; Star Wars Is Underway</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Nuclear Highway II</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the major Strategic Defense Initiative projects
underway along Interstate 25, America's nuclear highway.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NPB _ Neutral Particle Beam</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Different from traditional laser beams, a neutral particle beam
has one big advantage for SDI use, scientists say: It can penetrate
objects and discriminate between real missiles and decoys.
   Theoretically, it can also destroy objects as fast as 10 per
second in space.
   The initial concept actually came from the Soviets in the 1970s.
It was picked up at Los Alamos National Laboratory and carried much
further.
   ``We don't think the opposition has anything like this,'' said
Stan Schriber, project director. ``This technology wasn't
understood theoretically until two years ago. It had been a mystery
in the scientific community for 10 years.''
   In a neutral particle beam, a stream of charged hydrogen
particles receives an added electron then is accelerated to great
speeds. Before release, the extra electron is stripped out,
creating a neutral beam, one unaffected by magnetic fields.
   A Ground Test Facility for an NPB is under construction outside
Schriber's office. It will be a prototype for a weapons system.
   ``If the funding stays, this could be deployed by the year
2000,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BEAR _ Beam Experiment Aboard a Rocket</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   BEAR, a small neutral particle beam machine on a rocket, will be
here next year.
   Already under contruction at Los Alamos, the 44-inch-diameter
machine will be loaded onto an Aries rocket, launched from the
White Sands Missile Range on a sub-orbital flight and fired.
   ``The primary goal is to take one of these complicated things
into space _ it's never been done before,'' said Kenneth McKenna,
deputy project manager. ``We have to know we can operate in space.''
   The SDI command has accelerated BEAR's timetable so decisions
can be made on the most promising technologies, McKenna said. His
team is already working nights and weekends.
   While Schriber works to make a bigger NPB machine, to prove it
can be made powerful enough to destroy missiles, McKenna tries to
make it smaller _ to prove it can work in space. The technologies
would later be merged.
   ``I am very confident it will work when we get it up there,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PHASER _ Phased Array Experiment</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   At the Air Force Weapons Lab, researchers have combined laser
beams in a phased array. And instead of getting the sum of the
power of the individual lasers, they get much more.
   What they envision is a set of seven lasers in space that, when
combined, give the power of 49 lasers.
   ``We can make a small laser act as a big one and shoot down
missiles,'' said Air Force Lt. Dave Russell, electro-optics
engineer. ``You can't manufacture something great big and put it in
space. But you can put up a whole bunch of little ones.''
   In just four years of SDI work, the Air Force has combined three
lasers, produced the power of nine, and moved the beam from target
to target.
   ``We've got the basic idea in hand,'' Russell said. ``It's just
a matter of time before someone makes a decision to deploy or not.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PBFA II _ Particle Beam Fusion Accelerator II</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PBFA II is a merry-go-round-like contraption 108 feet wide with
36 arms arranged around a circular center. The Sandia National
Laboratories machine is designed to fire an ion beam at a target
pellet and ignite a nuclear fusion _ but it has yet to be done.
   By creating small nuclear explosions in the laboratory,
scientists say they'll be on the road to making fusion energy
available for commercial use and being able to test nuclear weapons
and materials in the laboratory instead of with underground
explosions.
   Fusion, combining two atoms, is the power of nuclear warheads.
Fission, splitting an atom, is the power of old atomic weapons and
of today's nuclear power plants. Fusion, if ever harnessed in the
laboratory, could yield almost limitless energy without as much
hazardous waste.
   At PBFA II, controllers sit in a small room fashioned after a
ship's bridge, with operators at screens labeled ``Commander
Spock,'' ``Capt. James Kirk,'' and ``Lt. Sulu.''
   ``We get closer to fusion every day,'' said senior technical
aide Guy Donovan.
   At full power, PBFA II's output would be 50 times the world's
existing electrical generating capacity for the extremely short
time it would be fired, billionths of a second.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GBFEL _ Ground-Based Free Electron Laser</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eighty acres of New Mexico desert have been cleared of sage and
brush for construction of a free electron laser, a machine capable
of firing a beam at the speed of light into space. Once up there,
the beam would be bounced off orbiting mirrors to intercept Soviet
missiles within minutes of launch.
   ``The technology is available today. The problem is getting it
to this level and this size,'' said Air Force Lt. Col. Lloyd Young,
the assistant project manager.
   By 1995, the military hopes to conduct an experiment in space
with the GBFEL, but this year's funds were cut and work has been
delayed.
   Two kinds of free electron lasers are competing _ one at Los
Alamos, tied in with Boeing, and one at Los Alamos' sister
laboratory, Lawrence Livermore in California, which is working with
TRW.
   A choice will be made next year, Young said, on which beam to go
with.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>R2P2 _ Rapid Retargeting Precision Pointing Simulator</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Already in operation at the Martin Marietta Astronautics Group
facility at Denver, R2P2 is a ground-based simulator that measures
how fast a space-based laser could retarget an object.
   The SDI contract, worth $20.9 million, specifies Martin Marietta
operate R2P2 for all ongoing Star Wars experiments for the next
three years.
   President Reagan toured the R2P2 simulator laboatory last
November.
   ``R2P2 is designed to duplicate the extreme precision needed to
track objects in space, a vibration-free environment,'' said
program manager Robert Sampsell. ``It is built on the most
seismically stable base on the North American continent, a rock
formation 28 miles long, 8 miles deep and a half-mile wide.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, June 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880610-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Highway-RockyFlats Adv21   06-10 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway-Rocky Flats, Adv 21,0909</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Attitudes Toward Nuclear Weapons Plant Change With the Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nuclear Highway II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT C. UNRUH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Red Scare, the Cold War and the
arms race were on in the 1950s, residents here enthusiastically
embraced the idea of a defense program coming to a rocky expanse
east of the Flatiron Mountains.
   It was there, between Golden and Boulder, that the government
built a nuclear weapons plant, and residents saw security and
opportunity in the news, not danger.
   It's a different story now.
   The Rocky Flats plant, which makes weapons components from
plutonium, has become the target of safety and environmental
concerns over the years. There have been fires, lawsuit settlements
and studies showing higher cancer rates and plutonium contamination.
   Suburbs have stretched out toward plant gates over the years,
bringing the population closer to potential danger.
   And even though the plant has grown to a $500 million-a-year
operation affecting 20,000 jobs, some residents wish the facility,
once so warmly welcomed, would just go away.
   ``The people who live near and who work inside these facilities
have the right to be free of fear,'' said U.S. Rep. David Skaggs, a
Democrat whose district includes Rocky Flats.
   Rocky Flats is an example of the dilemma faced along America's
Nuclear Highway, Interstate 25. With the work on nuclear weapons
and even ``Star Wars' research come not only jobs and growth, but
also danger and health hazards.
   The plant spawned its own boom. A planned community, Broomfield,
sprouted in nearby fields. Superhighways like I-25 and U.S. 36 _
the Denver-Boulder Turnpike _ were under construction nearby, and
the plant's responsibilities grew along with the nation's nuclear
arsenal.
   Even accidents like a 1957 fire that blew through more than 600
air purifying filters to release a plutonium-laced cloud of smoke
did not cause much concern, only worry that the plant's work might
be interrupted.
   A 1969 fire did millions of dollars in damage, but again the
reports stressed the potential production delay. A fireman exposed
to plutonium was interviewed several days after the blaze and was
reported doing fine.
   But concern about plant safety did grow, and plant officials
began regular briefings with municipal and government officials.
They also upgraded the plant to keep plutonium, which ignites when
exposed to air, in an inert atmosphere to prevent fire.
   A series of studies by Carl Johnson, then director of the
Jefferson County Health Department, showed plutonium contamination
on land and water downwind from Rocky Flats, a higher incidence of
cancer than average in the region and serious problems with
contaminated land and water from the residue of the plutonium
processing at Rocky Flats.
   The operation, originally under Dow Chemical but now run by
Rockwell International under contract to the Department of Energy,
rebutted Johnson's findings, but people began to worry about their
neighbor.
   As the 1980s arrived, with homes built close enough for
homeowners to stand in their backyards and see the rows of
prison-type yardlights illuminating Rocky Flats at night, the
demand for scrutiny and oversight of the plant grew to a clamor.
   In a precedent-setting decision in 1986, Rockwell and DOE agreed
that the Colorado Department of Health could review and regulate
hazardous wastes at the plant.
   At the same time, work-related lawsuits by former employees
began cropping up in court. Two employees won settlements after
claiming that prolonged exposure to radioactive materials had
caused their cancer.
   A lawsuit over traces of radioactive materials in neighboring
fields triggered a decade-long battle that ended with a $10 million
settlement.
   Skaggs and U.S. Rep. Patricia Schroeder, a Denver Democrat, have
suggested creation of an independent panel to regulate
environmental, health and safety concerns.
   ``DOE wants to say these are the levels (of emissions) that are
safe and we don't have those levels, therefore we are safe,''
Schroeder said. ``That's the crux of the whole debate. (I've) never
gotten what I would call independent data.''
   Rocky Flats management cays it's working toward that goal.
   ``We're happy about it (more attention),'' said Rockwell
spokesman Pat Etchard. ``We can't release everything for obvious
reasons. (But) putting things up for public debate usually clears
things up and gets issues out front.''
   Meanwhile, communities near Rocky Flats are trying to grapple
with the dilemma of depending on jobs while fearing the hazards.
   Arvada's compromise was to call for a shutdown of plutonium
operations, but to add workers for cleanup duties. Broomfield
officials endorsed the plant's safety efforts after meeting with
plant officials.
   Because of the long time span estimated needed for a move _ 20
years _ local governments are concerned but not worried about the
potential loss of jobs. The required cleanup operations at the site
if it were closed would keep workers busy for many years.
   But the price tag of a move _ put at around $4 billion by
Rockwell _ is a major obstacle.
   Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo., has suggested delaying $380 million in
scheduled improvements at Rocky Flats until its future is pinned
down.
   ``We should not be embarking on an expensive program ... without
having a thorough plan for the future of the nuclear weapons
complex,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, June 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
