<DOCNO> AP880610-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-NuclearHighwayIII Adv22-2Takes   06-10 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Highway III, Adv 22-2 Takes,0941</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, June 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>America's Nuclear Highway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part III: People Along the Highway _ Ordinary and Extraordinary</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos, LaserLogo
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ For those who live along Interstate 25, being a
part of America's nuclear highway can mean opportunity, challenge
or conflict. For years, everyone from four-star generals to
retirees, scientists to sandwich-sellers have had their lives
entwined with The Bomb; now it's ``Star Wars.'' The third story in
a four-part series looks at the people, ordinary and extraordinary,
along ``America's Nuclear Highway.''
   ___</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the migrations of aboriginal
Indians to the days of Buffalo Bill and Calamity Jane, the path
that became Interstate 25 has attracted more than its share of
explorers and warriors.
   So it is today. I-25, America's Nuclear Highway, bustles with
modern man's search for defense and his reach for the stars.
   The 3 million people for whom I-25 is Main Street are finding
their neighborhood now includes super-secret research, deadly
weapons, transplanted scientists and technological wonders.
   The locals, even the sandwich shop owners and auto salesmen,
follow budgetary debates in Washington, knowing some of the
trillions will trickle down to their cash registers.
   Some who come to this slice of the country seek science, some
fortune. Some work for peace, others prepare for war.
   They are people like the anti-nuclear activist who works without
pay for a cause, or the general who must inform the president of a
nuclear attack, or the Old World glassblower whose talent carries
high-tech research to new frontiers.
   Some, like the owner of the ``The Star Wars Deli'' or the new
Air Force officer with a vision of working in a space station, see
their future here.
   Others, like the retired couple living with a stockpile of
nuclear weapons literally in their backyard or the scientist who
spent a decade building warheads and now toils to find ways to
shoot them down, find calm amid what others might find dangerous.
   These are the stories of some of the people who live beside The
Nuclear Highway:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Exit 142 _ COMMANDER IN CHIEF, NORTH AMERICAN AEROSPACE DEFENSE
COMMAND and U.S. SPACE COMMAND, GEN. JOHN PIOTROWSKI, 54, of
Colorado Springs, holds two of the nation's highest military posts.
One command tracks everything in space. Under the other, it's his
job to inform the president if the United States comes under enemy
attack.
   ``Last year there were just under 700 space and missile launches
of all types. The Soviet Union conducted just under 600 of those,''
he said. ``The sensors detect a launch and (our) people go into
action immediately to determine ... is it headed toward North
America? Could it reach North America?
   ``Those that evidence a threat to North America must be
evaluated by myself or my Canadian deputy. ... I would say that was
well over 100 (in 1987). ...
   ``I get involved in taking into account everything that's going
on in the intelligence situation. ... Is the Soviet Union or the
United States in a confrontation somewhere in the world? Is there a
crisis brewing? Is there any correlation with this potential threat
that would indicate it's real? ... One takes the entire world
environment into account when one makes that assessment.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Exit 278 _ ENTREPRENEUR KEN RENEGAR, 50, of Organ, N.M., makes
sandwiches. But people come to his ``Star Wars Deli,'' located
between entrances to the White Sands Missile Range and a NASA
testing facility, expecting a lot more.
   ``I came up with the Star Wars Deli idea to take advantage of
the area _ that's the hot thing going on here. I deliver to NASA
and the missile range at lunchtime, and a lot of those guys are
working on Star Wars. They're different from the locals. They're
engineers mostly, and their favorite sandwich is turkey and
avocado. ..
   ``It turns out I'm the only thing in the phone book that says
Star Wars. So I get calls all the time from engineers asking for
jobs. I ask them if they can make sandwiches, and they usually are
a little taken aback. ...
   ``This place follows the budget in Washington. That's what
affects this area. What we've got going for us is defense. We don't
have a lot of other industry. And most of the people around here
are for SDI because we benefit from it.
   ``I have had people come in after they see the Star Wars sign
and tell me they find it offensive. They act like I'm some kind of
warmonger making sandwiches up here.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Exit 222 _ RETIREES RICHARD and MARY CARTER of Albuquerque,
N.M., live in the Four Hills section that abuts the Manzano
Mountains. Dotted with concrete bunkers and huge doorways, the
mountains are said to hold the largest single stockpile of nuclear
weapons in the country. The Air Force will neither confirm nor deny
the existence of such a cache, but the Carters and their neighbors
assume the barb-wire fences in their backyards mean only one thing.
   ``Sometimes at night a whole flood of lights will come on out
there, and you wonder what's going on,'' Mrs. Carter said. ``We
heard mention of the weapons when we bought this house. ... Maybe
if we were younger we would have thought about it more before we
bought, but at our time in life, it's not a factor for us.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
