<DOCNO> AP880610-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-NuclearHighwayIII Adv22-1stAdd   06-10 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Highway III, Adv 22-1st Add,0951</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, June 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>COLORADO SPRINGS: for us.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``If it's there, you have to believe it's safe,'' said Carter,
an anesthesiologist from Schenectady, N.Y. ``And it's OK with me.
Someday, they might need it.
   ``The good thing about it _ and this was a factor when we bought
the house _ is that there is so much clear area behind the house.
And you know that nobody is going to build up against us. You can
be sure of that.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   believes the
nuclear weapons plant threatens the health and welfare of 1.5
million people.
   ``I grew up in the '50s when we had air raid drills. In the
sixth grade we had to hide in the school basement or duck under our
desks, cover our heads and wait for the bomb. Those drills had an
enormous impact on this generation, but nobody talks about it. We'd
probably all go crazy if we really thought about the nuclear age.
...
   ``My grandparents lived in southwestern Utah. One night in 1955
I was visiting when the sky lit up and my bed shook. We all rushed
outside. The government was testing bombs in Nevada. Later, the
sheep died. ...
   ``I got an English degree from Mount Holyoke College, became a
Quaker, went to Southeast Asia on a tourist visa to find out about
the Vietnam War, came home, read a story about leukemia in children
following atmospheric nuclear testing, and decided to get involved.
...
   ``I'm a lay person, not a scientist, but it helps to have been
able to spend two full years on this. Politicians and agency
officials give me appointments now. Intellectually it's the most
challenging work I've ever done.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Exit 278 _ LOS ALAMOS NATIONAL LABORATORY SCIENTIST LARRY
WARNER, 56, of Los Alamos, N.M., manages a project to design a free
electron laser that could destroy enemy missiles in space. With a
Ph.D. in nuclear physics, he joined the project after two decades
working on nuclear weapons here and at the Pentagon.
   ``There's no conflict going from weapons work to SDI work. The
fact that it may look like I switched sides is not important. It's
the scientific challenge that's important. ...
   ``Often people around here do get into ethical discussions.
There are some people at the lab who do feel very strongly against
nuclear weapons, and they obviously don't work on weapons programs.
Some people just come here for the science. But a lot of people are
here because they think they can help the defense of the nation. ...
   ``I worked on nuclear weapons because I felt it was important to
insure international stability. ... The ethics is not nearly so
tricky in SDI _ I think for the people involved in SDI, this is a
lot like the Manhattan Project. SDI has some of that same spirit.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Exit 156 _ AIR FORCE ACADEMY GRADUATE KAREN GOONAN, 21, of
Wheaton, Ill., a new second lieutenant with an astronautical
engineering degree, will report for duty at the Air Force Ballistic
Missile Office at Norton AFB, Calif.
   ``I'd like to get involved in building a permanent space
station. Manned flight really excites me; it's a lot more thrilling
thinking you can get up in space than just shooting up a rocket. ...
   ``We have differing opinions on the Strategic Defense Initiative
right here at the Academy. ... There are enough people here that
everybody has their own views. ...
   ``I'm leaving here with book knowledge. I know that by
practicing the integrity and honest lifestyle we practice here it's
going to be hard for me to deal with people on the outside, who've
been in the business for 15-20 years. But I know the right and
wrong things to do.
   ``I didn't spend four very tough years here to have a good time.
I did it for my future.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Exit 222 _ GLASS TECHNOLOGIST CZESLAW DEMINET, 67, of
Albuquerque, originally from Poland, is a master glassblower whose
Old World talent has been married to Star Wars research. With 10
patents to his credit, Deminet creates glass tubes and chambers for
lasers and other projects. One recent day, he was fashioning a
piece to expose krypton to liquid hydrogen in a vacuum and produce
liquid krypton _ for SDI, not Superman.
   ``There's no way you can make this by machine. It's technology
that's 400 years old, and today, without glassblowers, you wouldn't
have lasers. ... I like working in SDI. It's very interesting work.
I'm having so much fun I can't retire. ...
   ``Over here is where I weld with a laser. This is the only place
in the country where this is done. For SDI instruments, we have no
other way. ...
   ``During the war I spent time in Russian prison and German
prison. I worked in the Polish underground in Germany, and I did
glassblowing there, too. With explosives. I was in Canada when
Sputnik went up. I said I have to go to the United States _ I have
to go where the action is. ...
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus is the AP Mountain States regional
reporter, based in Denver. Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest
regional reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEXT: Two Families _ Living With the Bomb, Torn by the Bomb</HEAD>
