<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, June 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lawn Care: Doing it Right or Getting Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having a well-groomed lawn can be a suburban
status symbol, but it's a goal often achieved at high cost in time,
effort and money.
   So why bother?
   Well, a thick green lawn makes the home more appealing, prevents
soil erosion, provides a cooling effect in hot weather and even
reduces noise pollution.
   Getting those benefits means raising a crop of turf grass, a
basically simple plant that will thrive if properly mowed, watered
and fertilized.
   But those endeavors must be done regularly. Erratic watering and
mowing can harm the lawn, according to grass experts.
   The Council of Better Business Bureaus has compiled some
research on lawn care _ both suggestions on doing it yourself and
on what to look for in a professional.
   ``Tips on Lawn Care and Lawn Care Services'' is available for $1
plus a long, self-addressed, stamped envelope. Write to the CBBB,
1515 Wilson Blvd., Arlington, Va. 22209.
   Watering and mowing, seemingly the simplest of tasks, can have a
great effect if not done properly, the booklet warns.
   Once you start watering, keep it on a regular schedule, the
council urges.
   ``Irregular watering can be harmful, as it might train the roots
to grow too close to the surface, leaving them more vulnerable to
the scorching sun,'' the booklet states.
   Watering at night tends encourage insects and diseases which
perfer a dark, damp environment. Daytime watering is better.
   Turning to mowing, the booklet notes that while the best height
varies according to the type of grass, ``cutting grass too short is
extremely harmful and can encourage certain varieties of weeds.''
   Often people cut grass short to avoid mowing it as often, the
booklet says. But longer grass is better able to withstand the hot
sun and trampling feet, and also can choke out many weeds as they
sprout.
   Keep the blade sharp on the lawn mover, the booklet goes on.
Grass sliced evenly suffers the least damage, while chopping or
shredding the tips of blades leaves them more prone to damage by
the sun, insects and disease.
   ``Grass should be cut in dry weather and in the early evening.
If it is too wet from rain, dew or fog, the grass has a tendency to
clump and not cut evenly. The clippings will also stick together,
suffocating sections of the lawn.
   ``Last, grass suffers the least amount of damage when mowed
during the cooler parts of the day,'' the booklet reports.
   Soil conditioning and fertilization needs vary from area to
area, the booklet points out, suggesting having the soil tested by
local cooperative extension agents. Those offices can also offer
advice on what type of pest control may be needed, and how to do it
safely.
   For some people, hiring a professional lawn care service proves
to be the answer, saving them time and work. Some customers have
complained to local BBB offices about billing problems with these
services, however, as well as companies that did work without
permission and then charged for it.
   When choosing the company, ask about the qualifications of the
workers, particularly the professionals in charge. Make sure they
have proper business licenses and any certificates needed to apply
chemicals.
   Get estimates from several firms, but remember cheapest isn't
always best.
   Ask for references from other customers, check with the local
Better Business Bureau and consumer affairs office for complaints
from past customers and find out if the firm is a member of a
professional lawn care association with a code of ethics.
   Ask for a written agreement from the firm you finally choose.
Check to see if it renews automatically each year or if you have a
choice. If renewal is automatic, make sure you know how to cancel
it, should that become necessary.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, June 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
