<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Summit-Expectations Adv12-1stadd   06-10 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Expectations, Adv 12-1st add,0453</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: of pollution.</HEAD>
<HEAD>JAPAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita wants to focus
attention on his country's contributions to the international
community.
   Takeshita also will stress that Japan has contributed to the
improvement in the global economy through its macroeconomic
performance. A new economic plan has forecast a growth in the
country's gross national product of 3.75 percent.
   ``Our economy is in very good shape. The external imbalance ...
is now being adjusted and Japan is contributing to better
management of the world economy,'' a government official said at a
news conference Thursday. He said imports of manufactured goods
were rising, the country's markets were opening and the
distribution systems were changing.
   The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, said
Takeshita and Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno ``will take concrete
action to advance the Uruguay Round at the Toronto summit.''
   Japan will also urge other summit participants to put out a
``strong message'' against the rising trend in protectionism.
   To demonstrate its growing role as a bridge between Asia and the
West, it will argue on behalf of the newly industrialized economies
(NIEs) of South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong and Singapore.
   ``We have to admit that the NIEs have positively contributed to
the advancement of the world economy ... that they are the hopes
for the developing world,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said before the meeting that
he expects the summit to produce a ``clear signal toward achieving
stability and trust of the markets.''
   He said he will press the United States to reduce its budget
deficit and Japan to open further its markets.
   Kohl said West Germany would intensify efforts to boost its
domestic demand in an effort to reduce trade imbalances.
   He said he will propose a series of measures to further reduce
the debt burden of the world's poorest nations at the summit.
   West Germany this month announced that it was forgiving 86
million marks ($50.5 million) of debts owed by some of the world's
poorest nations.
   A senior government official said West Germany expected the
summit to be ``one of relative harmony,'' focusing on long-term
ways to solve major world economic problems.
   Kohl is also expected to urge caution in the cutting of European
agricultural subsidies.
   On agricultural subsidies, West Germany is more cautious than,
say, the British. Kohl has warned that cuts agreed by the 12-nation
European Economic Community decision in February to cut
overproduction ``will not be easy to implement.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
