<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-10 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0528</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's huge trade deficits are
improving but not as quickly as previously believed, the government
says.
   The Commerce Department released new statistics Thursday that
adjust the monthly trade numbers for normal seasonal changes in
shipping patterns.
   With seasonal adjustment, the trade deficit for March turned out
to be $11.9 billion, 22 percent higher than the previously reported
$9.7 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses enjoying a boom in export sales
plan to modernize and expand at the fastest rate in four years, the
government said. The Commerce Department said Thursday a survey
completed in May showed U.S. companies plan to spend $435.2 billion
on capital projects, an 11.9 percent increase over last year's
spending of $388.8 billion.
   If realized, it would be the biggest gain in plant and equipment
spending since 1984, when spending shot up 16.6 percent as
businesses recovered from the 1981-82 recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is talking to members of
Congress about a new trade bill as the White House expressed
concern over a parliamentary move in the wake of the Senate vote
sustaining his veto of a previous version.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., a strong supporter
of the trade bill, voted against the bill at the last minute
Wednesday in a maneuver that could later allow him to ask for
reconsideration of the 1,000-page bill.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday Byrd's
action ``does complicate it ... we would like to see it proceed as
quickly as possible.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus fell 21 percent to $5.05
billion in May, the 13th straight month the surplus has decreased
from its level of a year earlier, the Finance Ministry said.
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States fell 25.6 percent
to $3.30 billion from $4.44 billion in May 1987. It was also down
from $4.13 billion the previous month, the agency said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge in Delaware has deferred until
today a ruling on Texas investor Robert M. Bass's attempt to block
a financial restructuring by Macmillan Inc., the publishing giant
Bass offered to acquire for $1.9 billion.
   Jack B. Jacobs, a judge in Chancery Court in Wilmington,
presided over the eleventh-hour hearing Thursday, one day before
Macmillan was scheduled to implement the first stage of its
controversial restructuring _ the payment of a $52.35-a-share
special dividend to shareholders.
   Bass sought a temporary restraining order to block the payout on
grounds that the Macmillan board breached its fiducuary duty by
failing to get the best price for its shareholders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo said the
company is studying ways to restructure its troubled Eastern
Airlines subsidiary but has no plans to sell the operation.
   He did not offer any specifics at the company's annual meeting
Thursday of what changes might be in store for Eastern, which is
saddled with bitter labor relations and recently passed a two-month
government safety investigation.
</TEXT>
