<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0493</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group's accusation that the sporty
Suzuki Samurai is prone to roll over is ``inaccurate and
defamatory,'' the automaker says.
   Last week, the influential Consumers Union said the Samurai was
so prone to roll over that it cannot be modified to be safe. It
recommended a recall of all 120,000 or more Samurais sold in
America and a complete refund to owners.
   ``If the magazine had acted responsibly and reviewed the
available information it would have been aware that the Samurai has
one of the best records on file,'' Doug Mazza, an American Suzuki
Motor Corp. executive, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp.'s elimination of thousands of jobs
at Federated Department Stores Inc. will result in a more
cost-effective organization, Wall Street analysts say. But they
also expect the cuts to affect the merchandise the stores offer.
   Separately, Campeau announced Thursday it had agreed to sell the
Filene's Basement division of Federated Department Stores Inc. to
an investor group led by Filene's management.
   Terms of the deal, which includes the sale of 22 women's
clothing stores in the Northeast, were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pay increases should average about 5 percent
this year and next for the nation's salaried workforce, narrowly
outpacing expected inflation, according to a survey.
   The Conference Board, a private business-information group,
reported Thursday that salaries of workers who were covered by
overtime and other labor law provisions, such as clerical workers,
would rise an average of 4.8 percent this year.
   Salaries of exempt workers, such as management and
professionals, would rise an average of 5 percent, while executive
salary increases would average 5.4 percent, the group reported.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Low- and moderate-income families would
receive tax-free interest on savings bonds used to pay for college
under a bill proposed by the Reagan administration.
   The College Savings Bond Act of 1988 was sent to Capitol Hill on
Thursday by Education Secretary William J. Bennett and Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl C. Icahn sought to bolster his
takeover offer for Texaco Inc. by raising to $300 million the money
he would forfeit if he failed to raise the necessary financing.
   Icahn also added a new twist Thursday, pledging that the
guarantee money would be divided among all Texaco stockholders
rather than go into the general treasury of the White Plains,
N.Y.-based oil company.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pulled back Thursday, as the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials slipped 9.60 to 2,093.35.
   Bond prices slipped. The dollar lost ground against all major
currencies in fairly active domestic trading after rising overseas.
   Pork futures prices plummeted, but soybean and oat futures
soared, precious metals advanmced and energy and stock-index
futures retreated.
</TEXT>
