<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0028EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Icahn-Texaco Bjt   06-10 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Icahn-Texaco, Bjt,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Raises Financial Guarantee to $300 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl C. Icahn has tripled to $300
million the money he would forfeit if he failed to raise the
necessary financing for his takeover offer for Texaco Inc.
   Texaco's largest shareholder also pledged in a statement on
Thursday that the money would go to Texaco stockholders, rather
than the company's general treasury.
   Icahn's bid of $60 a share, which values Texaco at $14.6
billion, has failed to impress Wall Street. Since it was announced
last month, shares of the White Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant have
traded $9 to $10 below his offer.
   In nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues
Thursday, Texaco closed at $51.37{, down 12{ cents a share.
   Texaco's board rejected Icahn's bid for the 85.2 percent of the
company's shares he does not already own. It also refused to put
the matter up for a vote by stockholders at the annual meeting June
17.
   On Thursday, a company statement said Icahn's latest move
``changes exactly nothing.''
   ``And nothing is exactly what he is offering the Texaco
shareholder,'' it added. ``Because he has attached such a jungle of
strings, conditions and red tape to his so-called guarantee, it
doesn't matter what number he attaches to it _ he's never put up a
dime and we are convinced he would never have to.''
   Icahn's proposal includes provisions that the money would not be
forfeited if another bid in excess of $60 per share materialized,
or if the Internal Revenue Service failed to approve his proposal.
   Those provisions duplicate others in his original bid, except
that in that case, Icahn only offered to put $100 million into
escrow and said it would be forfeited to the company if he could
not finance the offer.
   On Thursday Icahn said he would triple that amount _ but changed
the potential recipient of the money to Texaco's shareholders,
instead of the company.
   ``The guarantee is $1.50 in cash per share to all Texaco
stockholders of record for a special stockholder meeting we are
seeking,'' Icahn said in a statement.
   Icahn is joining four colleagues in running for five board seats
up for election at the company's annual meeting.
   He says he wants the seats on the 14-member board to pressure
the board to put his takeover proposal before the company's
approximately 211,000 shareholders.
   Both sides have been waging intense efforts to woo the
shareholders' support in the proxy battle.
   Since Monday, the company has announced several developments in
its plan to sell $5 billion worth of assets, including the sale of
its West German subsidiary for $1.2 billion and a pledge to
distribute a third of the proceeds from all of the sales to
shareholders.
   The company was vague about exactly how those proceeds would be
spread, saying it would come in cash, some form of security or in a
stock buyback plan. But it promised shareholders would see their
third of the proceeds by the end of the year.
   On Thursday, Icahn said he was sending letters to Texaco
shareholders telling them they had everything to gain and nothing
to lose with his proposal.
   ``Even if for some reason you do not want Icahn on the Texaco
board for the long term, you have nothing to lose by voting for us,
because either you will get $60 or better or he will be off the
board,'' Icahn wrote.
   He was referring to an earlier pledge that the slate would
resign if his bid is rejected in a subsequent shareholder vote.
   In his announcement on the $300 million guarantee, Icahn took
another swipe at management, saying his side had ``absolutely no
confidence that (it) would or could use the funds in a manner
beneficial to stockholders.''
   ``Management has shown us that they are unable to generate an
acceptable rate of return on assets,'' he said.
   Texaco, in its response, characterized the financier's recent
moves as ``desperate ploys,'' saying that ``in contrast, Texaco has
already taken real action to build real value for all its
shareholders.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
