<DOCNO> AP880610-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-10 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have slipped lower, as
traders remain apathetic in a market devoid of any price-supporting
news.
   In trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
fell 26 cents per barrel to finish at $17.07 on Thursday.
   Among refined products, contracts for July delivery of wholesale
unleaded gasoline settled down 0.64 cent at 49.70 cents a gallon,
and wholesale heating oil closed at 44.90 cents a gallon, down 1.03
cents.
   ``Most of the declines have been on relatively light volume,''
said John O'Connell of the commodities firm Refco Inc. ``There's
just no buyers.''
   Bob Baker of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. said the selloff
in crude accelerated late in the session when prices dipped below
technical support levels, and speculators began liquidating
positions.
   Prices were depressed by a lack of developments deemed
supportive of prices, and by perceptions that OPEC producers still
had not unified over production controls that could help boost
prices, according to market analysts. Oil ministers of the
13-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will begin
talks in Vienna, Austria, on Saturday.
   They are expected to discuss possible production cuts to defend
the official price target of $18 a barrel.
   Deepening the underlying bearish sentiment was the lack of any
agreement about production quotas during meetings of six Arab
members of OPEC oil-producing nations in Algiers. The meetings,
which took place during a three-day Arab summit, broke up Thursday.
</TEXT>
