<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-10 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly against major currencies
in quiet European trading early today, and gold prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said traders were cautiously looking
ahead to Tuesday's release of U.S. trade figures for April.
   ``People aren't willing to open big positions ahead of the
figures, unless they have a strong opinion,'' said one dealer at a
large West German bank in Frankfurt.
   Some said the figures were causing particular trepidation
because, for the first time, they would be issued on a seasonally
adjusted basis, as well as an unadjusted basis.
   Mid-morning rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7150 West German marks, down from 1.7230; 1.4305
Swiss francs, down from 1.4370; 5.7905 French francs, down from
5.8155; 1.9259 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9330; 1,275.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,280.50; and 1.2175 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2211.
   The British pound rose to $1.82 from $1.81.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 124.85 Japanese yen, down from
125.43 yen. In London trading later today, the dollar held steady
at 124.85 yen.
   London's main bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
mid-morning of $457.10 a troy ounce, up from $455.25 late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold traded at a bid of $456.90, up from $455.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $457.99, up
from $456.59.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $7.14 a troy ounce,
up from $7.08.
</TEXT>
