<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-10 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices and the dollar fell in Tokyo trading
today after an overnight drop on Wall Street.
   The dollar finished the week at 124.85 yen, down 0.58 yen from
Thursday's close.
   After opening at 124.72 yen, the U.S. currency dipped farther
and briefly touched 124.60, its low today, in early morning
trading. The dollar recovered the loss in the afternoon, peaking at
124.95 yen.
   The dollar was stronger than expected throughout the day, said
Hiroaki Shukuzawa of Sumitomo Bank. He said Japanese trust banks
actively bought the dollar to sustain the level, but profit-taking
kept it from reaching the 125-yen level.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected
issues, the exchange's main barometer, plunged 151.66 points, or
0.50 percent, from Thursday's close to end the week at 27,920.36.
   ``Investors were tiring of continuous record highs and seemed to
have set up a new position,'' said a broker at a major securities
firm. ``There was also profit-taking. But large shares, like steel
and heavy electric shares, are still doing well,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Volume was a heavy 2.2 billion shares.
</TEXT>
