<HEAD>Jury Resumes Deliberations In Cigarette Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to UPDATE with deliberations resuming today.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury began its fourth day of
deliberations today in the trial of three cigarette makers sued
over the lung-cancer death of a woman who smoked their brands over
40 years.
   The six-member panel asked no questions Thursday during about
seven hours of talks over the claims of Antonio Cipollone.
Deliberations, which began Tuesday, were scheduled to continue
today.
   Cipollone is seeking damages for the 1984 death of his
58-year-old wife, Rose. He claims Liggett Group Inc., Philip Morris
Inc. and Lorillard Inc. misled the public and his wife about the
dangers of smoking cigarettes.
   The companies say she made her own decision to smoke, knowing
the risks. They also say smoking is not a proven cause of cancer,
and that in any case, her cancer was not linked to the type usually
associated with cigarettes.
   On Wednesday, the jurors asked to see a copy of Mrs. Cipollone's
testimony to lawyers before she died.
