<DOCNO> AP880610-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-CleanGrain Adv12   06-10 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Clean Grain, Adv 12,0923</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday June 12 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>An Effort to Make American Grain As Clean as the Competitors'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for Weekly Farm.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If a group of farm-state lawmakers has its
way, the government will soon start paying more for less _ less
dirt in grain, that is.
   Legislation approved by the House last month would establish a
pilot project to pay some farmers a higher price for cleaner grain.
The idea is to keep grain free of dust, broken kernels, chaff and
foreign materials such as weed seeds. The Senate Agriculture
Committee endorsed a similar proposal last Wednesday.
   ``I just think we need to build incentives into our whole grain
delivery system that encourage farmers to deliver a cleaner product
and encourage the handlers of grain to keep the product clean once
it's delivered to them clean,'' says Rep. Jim Slattery, D-Kan., a
sponsor of the measure.
   He and others contend that the United States needs to improve
the cleanliness of grain it offers to foreign buyers. Canada and
Australia, two major wheat exporters, have established reputations
for selling high-quality, clean grain.
   ``The global grain market is going to become increasingly
competitive in the 1990s and I don't want to see American farmers
lose the sale of one bushel of grain because cleaner grain was
available someplace else,'' says Slattery.
   Wheat delivered to Japan between 1983 and 1987 from the United
States contained almost twice as much foreign material and
``dockage'' as that arriving from Canada and nearly 2.5 times as
much as from Australia, according to information from U.S. Wheat
Associates and the Japan Food Agency.
   Under the current U.S. system, federal standards call for
discounts on dirty grain but allow for a certain amount of foreign
material in shipments of grain.
   To take advantage of the system, the industry blends clean grain
with dirtier grain, which is purchased at lower prices, to form
average shipments selling at market prices. In fact, it is through
this blending of grain that the industry largely earns its profit,
critics say.
   Gary Gilbert, a Clay Center, Kan. elevator operator, is an
outspoken advocate of cleaner grain, which he says is cheaper to
store and transport.
   The grain takes up less space. Drying and aeration costs less.
Clean grain also is safer to handle because there is less of a
hazard from explosive dust. Cleaning grain also reduces insect
damage. Insects feed on and live in the fine trashy materials at
issue in the clean grain controversy.
   From his county elevator perspective, Gilbert sees the solution
as a system that removes the profit-making incentives for grain
blending and instead provides premiums for the delivery of clean
grain by producers and in keeping it clean all the way to export
terminals.
   ``We have to have an incentive program there that everytime we
handle it we want it to be the very best,'' says Gilbert.
   Under the House legislation, higher prices would be paid to
farmers in some areas for clean wheat, corn and soybeans placed
into the government price support loan program, which allows
farmers to forfeit their grain to the Commodity Credit Corporation
and keep the federal loan monies.
   A pilot project would be established for the 1989 crop year in
at least three multi-county areas: one in a wheat-growing region;
one in corn country and one in a soybean-producing region. The
Senate proposal by Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., calls for six
experimental zones, two in each commodity.
   The House proposal provides for the secretary of the agriculture
Department to determine the areas, the amount of the premiums and
the grain cleanliness standard. The measure does not provide for
additional discounts for dirty or average grain. It also would not
apply to grain sold in commercial markets.
   Slattery's original bill called for a nationwide system of
higher prices for exceptionally clean CCC-stored grain, but that
was scaled back in order to build support.
   ``If the pilot project proves successful and if we can work the
kinks out of the concept, I hope that we can make this part of the
farm bill in 1990,'' says Slattery.
   Not everyone in the grain industry is sold on the legislation.
   ``I have some doubts on how helpful it might really be,'' says
Bob Petersen, president of the National Grain Trade Council. ``It's
probably a noble idea but looks to be incredibly complicated to
administer.''
   Under current grain standards, he maintains, foreign buyers can
specify extremely clean grain if they want to pay for it. Petersen
also says that the number of complaints about U.S. grain quality
has dropped this year.
   ``In a down market foreign complaints tend to assume a lot more
visibility than they do in a seller's market,'' he says.
   David Frey of the Kansas Wheat Commission says the success of
the proposal will depend upon the premiums fixed by USDA. He
worries that the experiment is too limited and will not provide
enough information to lawmakers on whether a price-incentive system
will work nationwide.
   ``The concept is excellent. I'm sorry that it's going to be just
in certain areas because I'd like to see it go across the
country,'' says Frey. ``There is the potential for it to very
significantly affect the way grain is physically handled in the
U.S.''
  
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday June 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
