<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned upward today, bidding to
revive its recent rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.93 to 2,100.28 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 2 to 1 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 600 up, 326 down and
466 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.99 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before the market opened the Labor Department reported that the
producer price index of finished goods rose 0.5 percent in May.
   While the figure tended to confirm expectations that
inflationary pressures have increased slightly of late, it also
came in about where analysts had expected it to be.
   Brokers said there was quite possibly a feeling of relief among
investors that the news wasn't worse.
   In the bond market, which is especially sensitive to changes in
inflation expectations, interest rates were steady to slightly
lower in early trading.
   Payless Cashways rose 1[ to 25|. Faced with takeover overtures
from a group led by investor Asher Edelman, the company said its
top executives are considering a leveraged buyout.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .47 to 152.83. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .35 at 308.97.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 9.60 points
to 2,093.35.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 10 to 9 on the
NYSE, with 800 up, 721 down and 448 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 235.16 million shares, against 310.03 million in the
previous session.
