<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC-Arabs     06-10 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC-Arabs,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Oil Ministers Fail to Agree on Production Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab oil ministers failed this week to
agree on production cuts called for in discussions with several
non-OPEC oil-exporting countries, officials said Friday.
   The Arab oil exporters remained divided between a
Western-oriented group resisting a 5 percent cut by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and a group led by
Algeria and Libya that supported it.
   The ministers met during this week's Arab Summit here.
   At a meeting in April, seven non-OPEC nations agreed to reduce
their exports by 183,000 barrels per day _ a 5 percent cut _ if
OPEC would implement a matching 5 percent cut.
   The OPEC countries, which have a current overall production
ceiling of 15.06 million barrels per day, offered to match the
proposed non-OPEC cut barrel-per-barrel, but could not agree on an
overall 5 percent cut that would have lowered their ceiling by
about 750,000 barrels per day.
   Algeria and Libya advocate production cuts while Saudi Arabia
and the Gulf emirates have defended their production levels.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
ministers expressed the hope their differences could be overcome at
the meeting scheduled to open in Vienna on Saturday between OPEC
and non-OPEC producers.
   The Algerian News Agency distributed a statement that the Arab
oil ministers had reached an agreement ``on the need for all OPEC
member countries to adhere to their undertaking to respect their
production quotas and their defense of oil prices.''
   The statement appeared to be an attempt to present an appearance
of unanimity.
   The non-OPEC members involved in the dialogue with OPEC are
Angola, China, Colombia, Egypt, Mexico, Oman and Malaysia. Norway
is attending the meeting as observer, while Britain is not
represented.
   The oil ministers attending the Arab Summit, which closed
Thursday, were those of Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, the United
Arab Emirates, Libya and Algeria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
