<2ND_LINE>BC-Chrysler Layoffs,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Layoffs of 1,200 Chrysler workers planned at Kenosha for four
weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-week layoff for 1,200 Chrysler Corp.
production workers in Kenosha will start Aug. 1 because of shortage
of steel and other materials.
   Doug Nicoll, Chrysler's manager of manufacturing public
relations, said Thursday the shortage resulted from a switch in
plans for building Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in Kenosha.
   Chrysler had announced in January it would halt such production
in mid-July, putting 5,500 employees out of work.
   ``We advised our suppliers accordingly,'' Nicoll said.
   But the automaker decided in late April to contine building the
L-body cars in Kenosha through the end of the year.
   ``We again advised our suppliers,'' Nicoll said. ``But our
suppliers had to get back on board and gear up their production.''
   There will be about a four-week time lag, he said.
</TEXT>
