<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-10 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
sharply higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with new buying
prompted by forecasts for hot, dry weather in the Midwest through
at least the middle of next week.
   Oat futures advanced their 10-cents-a-bushel daily limit,
soybean meal touched limit-up at the opening, and even wheat
futures advanced despite a bearish harvest projection issued
Thursday by the Agriculture Department.
   The USDA reduced its 1988 winter wheat production estimate by 3
percent to 1.57 billion bushels, but most analysts had expected a
lower number.
   Soybean contracts were up more than 20 cents in early trading
and the near-month contract, for July delivery, hit $9 a bushel for
the first time since late 1983.
   Corn futures also jumped but not as high as soybeans. Analysts
said soybeans, with a 30-cents-a-bushl daily price limit, tend to
attract more speculators than corn, which is restricted to moves of
10 cents a day.
   ``When people say `I want to buy something that's going up,'
they buy the beans,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst with
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   In early trading, wheat was 4{ cents to 6\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.78 a bushel; corn was 3 cents
to 7} cents higher with July at $2.61 a bushel; oats were 5 cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $2.60 a bushel; soybeans were 7{
cents to 24{ cents higher with July at $9.07 cents a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .37 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June at
72.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .28 cent
higher with August at 74.90 cents a pound; hogs were .13 cent to
.35 cent higher with June at 51.35 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .67 cent lower to 1 cent higher with July at 50.20
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mostly lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
