<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ZZZZBest     06-10 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ZZZZ Best,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former ZZZZ Best Vice President Pleads Guilty To Tax Fraud,
Conspiracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former executive of Barry Minkow's ZZZZ
Best Co. carpet-cleaning company pleaded guilty to four counts of
tax fraud, insider trading and conspiracy, saying he wants to make
amends for his crimes.
   Jack N. Polevoi, a former ZZZZ Best vice president, also
admitted in court Thursday he maintained a $200,000 slush fund for
Minkow's personal use and gambled away $42,000 in a frenzied
attempt to launder cash through Las Vegas casinos as the
once-mighty company crumbled.
   ``For several months, I convinced myself that I didn't do
anything wrong, but I tell you now, I know I did,'' an emotional
Polevoi told U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian. ``I want to pay
my dues. I want to get on with my life.''
   Polevoi was among 12 original defendants indicted on bank fraud,
securities fraud and racketeering charges in connection with ZZZZ
Best's sudden fall from a hot Wall Street commodity to bankruptcy.
   On the insider-trading charge, Polevoi said he and his brother,
Jerry, made $225,000 by selling 54,200 shares of ZZZZ Best stock
after they learned Minkow intended to resign because the company
was falling apart.
   Several company employees have admitted they helped Minkow carry
out a scheme that made it look like ZZZZ Best's earnings were
strong enough to qualify for millions of dollars in bank loans.
   Minkow, 22, the so-called ``whiz-kid'' who started the business
at age 15 in his parents' San Fernando Valley garage in California,
was forced to stage the fraud by organized crime figures, his
attorney said Thursday.
   Unable to post $1.5 million bail, Minkow is jailed at Terminal
Island, awaiting his Aug. 23 trial.
   Polevoi told the court that on Minkow's orders he kept a fund
prosecutors have estimated at more than $200,000 from which Minkow
allegedly bought cars, jewelry and, on occasion, concert tickets
for as many as 50 people.
   During ZZZZ Best's final days, Minkow asked Polevoi to take
$712,000 in cashiers' checks from corporate accounts and bank
drafts and convert them to cash in Las Vegas, Polevoi said.
   He told the court he briefly questioned the source of the money,
but ``When I heard Las Vegas, sparks just started flying. I didn't
care,'' Polevoi said.
   Sentencing was scheduled for Oct. 17. Polevoi faces a maximum of
16 years in prison and a $1 million fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
