<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading activity; No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose on the London Stock Exchange
Friday for a second straight day, led higher late in the session by
a strong start on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 8.3
points, or 0.45 percent, higher at 1849.8.
   In New York, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up
12.27 points at 2105.62 when London trading closed.
   London dealers said share prices were boosted by the
announcement that the U.S. producer price index for May rose a
modest 0.5 percent, slightly higher than April's 0.4 percent gain
and in line with most market expectations.
   ``The market reacted very well to some potentially bad news in
the PPI, which is a clear change of sentiment from the recent past
of taking good news and turning it around,'' said one British
analyst.
   ``People's estimates of PPI had been creeping up over the past
couple of days, so over time, it wasn't unanticipated,'' said Bob
Semple, an equities strategist at County Natwest WoodMac Ltd.
   Several dealers saw encouraging signs that Wall Street did not
lose the gains chalked up over the past week. ``People have been
loathe recently to take big positions but we're seeing a bit more
interest after this week's successful period of consolidation,''
one analyst said.
   ``There was some trepidation that Wall Street would erase
Wednesday's 50-point rise Thursday, and when that didn't happen, we
all breathed a sigh of relief,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
