<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0312</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market revived its recent rally with a
broad advance today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 21.16 points to
2,114.51 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 956 up, 452
down and 483 unchanged.
   Before the market opened the Labor Department reported that the
producer price index of finished goods rose 0.5 percent in May.
   While the figure tended to confirm expectations that
inflationary pressures have increased slightly of late, it also
came in about where analysts had expected it to be.
   Brokers said there was quite possibly a feeling of relief among
investors that the news wasn't worse.
   In the bond market, which is especially sensitive to changes in
inflation expectations, interest rates were steady to lower.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up | at 46; Ford
Motor, up | at 52\; General Electric, up ] at 43{, and
International Business Machines, up 1~ at 117\.
   Payless Cashways rose 1] to 25~. Faced with takeover overtures
from a group led by investor Asher Edelman, the company said its
top executives are considering a leveraged buyout.
   AGS Computers climbed 1} to 27[ on word of an agreement for
Nynex to acquire AGS's professional services and software products
businesses. In the deal, AGS holders are to get $21 a share in cash
and shares of the company's Microamerica Inc. subsidiary.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.34 to 153.70. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 1.01 at 309.63.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 113.68 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
