<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Macmillan Bjt   06-10 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Macmillan, Bjt,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Restructuring Halted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be updated with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas investor Robert M. Bass succeeded in
derailing Macmillan Inc.'s restructuring plan Friday when a state
judge in Delaware ordered the publishing giant to refrain from
paying a special dividend.
   Jack B. Jacobs, a judge in Chancery Court in Wilmington, Del.,
issued a temporary restraining order preventing Macmillan from
paying the $52.35-a-share dividend, which was to be the first phase
in a restructuring plan that also included splitting the company in
two.
   The move put pressure on the Macmillan board to either seriously
consider Bass's $1.9 billon buyout offer or to top it in some other
fashion. Earlier this week the board rejected Bass's offer as
inadequate.
   Analysts had expected some form of delay and said Macmillan was
now on the defensive.
   Macmillan stock, which had fallen $2.25 a share Thursday, jumped
$2.37{ a share to $75.87{ in afternoon trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   ``The market is saying that this is going to go back and forth a
few times yet,'' said Bruce Thorp, an analyst at Provident National
Bank in Philadelphia.
   Macmillan spokesman David Jackson said: ``I have no comment.
There's nothing to say.''
   Jacobs, who heard arguments at a crowded hearing for several
hours late Thursday, issued his decision the day Macmillan planned
to begin paying the dividend. The order will be in effect until a
hearing is held on whether a preliminary injunction should be
issued.
   Macmillan put a value of $64 a share on its restructuring, which
called for the special dividend and dividing the company's
publishing and information services operations into separate
publicly held concerns.
   Under the plan, Macmillan management would control 39 percent of
the new information company and would be provided lucrative
financial protections against losing their jobs after any takeover.
   Bass has offered to acquire Macmillan for $73 a share in cash,
or, alternatively, to pay a $58-a-share dividend in his own
restructuring. He already owns 9.1 percent of the company's 26
million shares outstanding.
   His attorneys argued that Macmillan's board breached its
fiduciary duties by failing to get the best price for its
shareholders.
   According to lawyers present at the hearing, Jacobs said
Macmillan shareholders could be harmed if the restructuring went
through.
   Coniston Partners, which controls 4.9 percent of Macmillan and
supported Bass's legal efforts, expressed pleasure at the judge's
decision.
   ``We're happy about it, but it was pretty patently obvious,''
said Coniston general partner Paul E. Tierney Jr. ``There's still a
law against stealing, and management was attempting a
recapitalization that transfered control to them without their
paying.''
   Principals of the aggressive New York investment firm value
Macmillan at between $85 and $100 a share and have said they are
seeking a ``full auction'' for the company.
   Analysts said the next move was Macmillan's. ``The whole point
of the injunction is to force Macmillan to respond to Bass's
offer,'' Thorp said.
   Both Bass and Coniston are likely to ``wait and see what
Macmillan comes back with'' before taking any further action, he
said.
   ``We have built our investment on the theory that ultimately the
shareholders'' will win out, Tierney said. ``We are vigilant
observers but have no comment on any action on our part.''
   Macmillan has its own legal action pending in federal court in
New York, where it has charged Bass and his affiliates with
violating securities laws, repeatedly filing and disseminating
false information and engaging in a ``creeping tenders.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
