<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 1542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WesternUnion-Mole     06-10 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Western Union-Mole,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Union Accuses Former Executive of Setting Up Spy Network</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top Western Union Corp. executive
set up a network of ``double agents'' to establish a rival to the
troubled telecommunications company and used his position to steal
Latin American business from it, Western Union charges.
   But a lawyer for the executive, John Lanzelotti of Port Reading,
N.J., said Friday the suit was in retaliation for fee and expense
claims by Latin American agent companies, and denied the charges.
   Some of the defendants, who include former Western Union South
American sales agents and an Israeli company, illegally tried to
supply helicopters and other equipment to armed forces in Peru and
Ecuador and other countries, said the suit, filed Wednesday in
federal court in Newark.
   The suit also charges that defendants bribed communications
authorities in Latin American nations including Ecuador, Bolivia
and Suriname, to gain their business.
   Western Union claims that Lanzelotti, who left the company Feb.
12 after six years, worked on behalf of the alleged
``racketeering'' enterprise while he was Western Union's regional
vice president for the Western Hemisphere.
   ``It is our allegation that while Mr. Lanzelotti was a Western
Union employee, we are certain ... that he had put into place a
number of agents in Latin America that were truly double agents,''
said Western Union lawyer Susan Littman.
   The defendants had ``worldwide aspirations'' to set up a rival
telecommunications company to supply telex and electronic mail
services, she said. They used telex services Western Union provides
free to its employees to further their goals, even selling it to
others and keeping the money, the complaint said.
   The complaint provided little detail on the allegations about
helicopter sales, and Ms. Littman would not comment further.
   ``We know that (the defendants) were involved in these
activities as part of the conspiracy,'' she said.
   Lanzelotti, reached by telephone at his attorney's office in
Carteret, N.J., referred questions to his lawyer, Louis J.R. Kady.
Kady denied the claims but said he would not address them
specifically.
   ``Our position is that while he was working for Western Union,
(Lanzelotti) was working for Western Union, and did what he was
supposed to do for them,'' Kady said.
   He said the company was retaliating against firms that were
seeking expenses and fees from it.
   Lanzelotti had a ``substantial financial interest'' in
Woodbridge, N.J.-based Intelco International Inc. and related
companies in Panama and Venezuela, and ``announced'' he had become
Intelco's president on Feb. 11, the day he was fired, the suit said.
   Kady said Lanzelotti owns a third of Intelco's stock, but only
acquired it after leaving Western Union.
   He helped plan Western Union's strategies in dealing with Latin
American governments and communications authorities, and used his
position to steer business to Intelco and other defendants, the
suit said.
   When he learned last year that Western Union was bidding to
supply services to Brazil, Lanzelotti _ pretending to represent his
employer _ traveled there and tried to seize the opportunity for
himself and his alleged co-conspirators, the suit said.
   The defendants also tried to divert Western Union's business by
pretending Intelco was acting on its behalf, the complaint said.
   Western Union, based in Upper Saddle River, N.J., recently
reorganized to avoid having to file for bankruptcy protection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
