<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-10 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grains Higher, Soybeans Mixed At Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oat futures prices scored limit gains Friday on
the Chicago Board of Trade while most other grain futures advanced
only slightly and soybeans closed mixed.
   New forecasts for rain in the western Grain Belt late this
weekend and early next week prompted heavy profit-taking in most of
the agricultural futures contracts late in the session, analysts
said.
   ``But if it's hot and dry over the weekend, we'll probably be
limit-up on Monday,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research
Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Karlin said plummeting futures prices for silver and crude oil
on other exchanges encouraged the sell-off in soybeans, corn and
wheat, all of which had traded sharply higher for most of the
session.
   Oat futures refused to retreat, reflecting the damage done to
the U.S. oat crop by drought conditions in the upper Midwest. The
contracts for July and September delivery closed up the
10-cents-a-bushel daily limit.
   ``We stayed locked limit-up all day,'' said Jay Homan, an
independent oat trader. ``Some opening orders never even got
filled.''
   At the close, wheat was 8 cents lower to 2} cents higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.74 a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 3\ cents higher with July at $2.57 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 10 cents higher with July at $2.60 a bushel; soybeans
were 5 cents lower to 9{ cents higher with July at $8.82 a bushel.
</TEXT>
