<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cartel To Grapple With Oil Glut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, In trading ..., with one graf to UPDATE
with closing figure. Picks up 9th graf pvs, Oil prices ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers began arriving Friday
for their regular mid-year gathering, prepared to grapple again
with their biggest problem: how to deal with the world oil glut.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' 13 members
nations, most of whose delegations arrived a day before Saturday's
opening session, are deeply divided over ways to boost prices
through production cuts.
   The cartel is split over whether to change an existing agreement
among 12 of its members to limit daily production to 15.06 million
barrels. The pact, which was extended in December and is due to
expire June 30, was aimed at supporting oil prices at $18 a barrel,
but OPEC oil has been selling for about $1.50 below that.
   Iraq refused to sign because it wants a quota equal to that of
its enemy Iran.
   Oil experts predicted the cartel would be unable to reach a
consenus on how to tackle the problem and would end up extending
its existing agreement through the rest of the year.
   ``It will be a rollover of what they've got,'' said Harry
Neustein, a New York-based oil trader attending the OPEC meeting.
   The oil futures markets also showed little optimism Friday.
   In trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
closed down 34 cents a barrel to $16.73 on Friday.
   Oil prices have been weak amid reports that many OPEC members
have exceeded the daily production cap and as worldwide oil
reserves continue to rise.
   In addition, some non-OPEC oil nations, which produce around
23.2 million barrels a day, failed in late Arpil to get OPEC to
agree to jointly cut production. That was the first major effort to
form a worldwide alliance among oil producers to boost prices.
   These competing non-OPEC producers, which are producing more and
more of the world's oil and now account for 60 percent of output,
also have been making significant new oil discoveries.
   Meanwhile, rumors have been circulating _ particularly out of
the Arab summit in Algeria this week _ that Iran and Iraq might be
close to agreeing to end their 8-year-old Persian Gulf war. That
would result in a sharp increase in the two countries' oil ouput,
putting further pressure on oil prices, experts said.
   OPEC's other members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates
and Venezuela.
   Longer-term, all oil producers are being asked to meet less of
the world's energy needs in the face of competition from other
sources _ natural gas, nuclear energy, coal and others.
   Crude oil provides about 50 percent of the world's energy.
Consumption of crude oil in non-Communist nations has fallen to 50
million barrels a day from a peak of 57 million barrels a day in
1979.
   Even though oil demand is expected to increase in the second
half of the year, ``you're living in a wash of energy now, not a
shortage of energy,'' said Neustein.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
