<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MetalsFutures     06-10 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Metals Futures,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Futures to be Traded on Comex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's leading exchange for platinum
futures, faced with a shortage of elbow room, has accepted an offer
to move its platinum trading pit to the floor of the world's
leading gold and silver exchange, officials said Friday.
   The agreement between the Commodity Exchange, the premier market
for gold and silver futures, and the New York Mercantile Exchange
will require approval by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission,
officials said.
   The Comex and the Nymex, New York's two largest futures
exchanges, operate side-by-side along with three other futures
exchanges in the World Trade Center in lower Manhattan.
   Space is at a premium, but the Comex has found itself with an
empty trading pit or ``ring'' since the failure earlier this year
of a corporate-bond index contract, said Gina Greer, a Comex
spokeswoman.
   ``Since everyone is so crowded here, we thought we'd be nice
guys and offer them, at a price, that ring,'' she said.
   Nymex Chairman William M. Bradt said the Nymex board accepted
the proposal on Wednesday and was awaiting final approval from the
Comex board.
   Under the agreement, Comex members would be allowed to trade
platinum futures for their own accounts but not for clients, Bradt
said.
   In return for the use of its pit, Nymex would pay Comex half of
the annual platinum clearing fees or $1 million a year, whichever
is more.
   Bradt said the change would probably stimulate greater trading
volume in both platinum and gold futures.
   The Nymex board also voted to continue merger discussions with
Comex, he said.
</TEXT>
