trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 181.58 million shares.
   Before the market opened, the Labor Department reported that the
producer price index of finished goods rose 0.5 percent in May.
   While the figure tended to confirm expectations that
inflationary pressures have increased slightly of late, it also
came in about where analysts had expected it to be.
   Brokers said there was quite possibly a feeling of relief among
investors that the news wasn't worse.
   In the bond market, which is especially sensitive to changes in
inflation expectations, interest rates were steady to slightly
lower.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up { at 45~; Ford
Motor, up [ at 52; International Business Machines, up | at 116;
