<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Centel     06-10 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Centel,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Offer for Centel Still Stands Despite Rejection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor said Friday that his group's $2.8
billion cash bid to take over Centel Corp. still stands, despite
rejection by the company's chairman.
   The investment group led by Asher B. Edelman and George L.
Lindemann had set a June 10 deadline in a letter announcing their
bid late last month.
   Centel Chairman John P. Frazee Jr. dismissed the offer when it
was received May 31 after consulting the company's board of
directors and investment bankers, and has not reconsidered,
spokesman Bill White said Friday.
   ``The proposal was not a credible offer,'' White said. ``We said
at that time we believed that the offer ... was a tactical device
designed to affect the outcome of the proxy fight.''
   Edelman's group has proposed a three-man slate of directors to
fill slots on Centel's 11-member board. Shareholders will have a
chance to decide between those candidates and a three-man slate
nominated by Centel at the company's annual meeting on June 28,
White said.
   Edelman, a New York-based financier whose group holds 5.5
percent of Centel's stock, denied that the takeover bid was a
maneuver in the proxy fight.
   But he said in a telephone interview Friday, ``I think the
shareholders certainly will look hard at what we've done about our
position in our company.''
   Edelman said Frazee's ``unilateral turn-down of our offer ...
will show the shareholders exactly what type of person he is and
what he thinks of their interests.''
   In the initial letter to Centel management, Edelman and
Lindemann, chairman of a New York-based mobile phone business
called Metro Mobile CTS Inc., said their group was willing to pay
$65 a share for each of Centel's approximately 43 million shares
outstanding.
   But they conditioned the offer on Centel's canceling an
agreement to pay $763 million to buy United Telespectrum, the
cellular telephone subsidiary of United Telecommunications of
Kansas City. They said they would drop the bid to $60 a share if
Centel held to the deal, which was announced in late May.
   Frazee said at the time that the company's plan to acquire
United Telespectrum and its $9.5 million debt would provide a far
better return for investors than any short-term gain under the
Edelman group's proposal to sell off Centel assets to boost stock
values.
   Centel is going ahead with plans to acquire United Telespectrum,
White said.
   Edelman called the United Telespectrum deal ``overpriced'' and
said if it's completed, his group would tender its lower offer for
Centel.
</TEXT>
