<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AirForce-Eaton     06-10 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Force-Eaton,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Canceling Electronic Warfare Equipment Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force on Friday accused one of its
large contractors of defaulting on a key electronics contract,
saying it was canceling the order and would demand repayment of $39
million in progress payments.
   It also vowed to force the company, the Eaton Corp., to cover
any extra costs the government incurred in finding a new contractor
to perform the work.
   The Air Force said it was ``terminating for default'' an $81.5
million contract awarded four years ago to Eaton's AIL Division in
Deer Park, N.Y., for development of a new tactical jamming system
for its EF-111A jet aircraft.
   The EF-111A is an electronic warfare version of the F-111
bomber, meaning it is specially equipped to fool or jam enemy radar
and radio systems during bombing attacks. The Air Force had planned
to upgrade its fleet of 42 such planes after Eaton developed the
new jamming system.
   Eaton was selected for the development work in October 1984
after it won a bidding contest with the Grumman Corp.
   The Air Force said Friday it was terminating the contract
because Eaton was now estimating it would cost $153 million to
perform the work _ or an overrun of $71.5 million _ and an extra 30
months beyond the specified completion date of July 1987.
   ``The contractor was terminated for failure to make progress, so
as to endanger performance, and for failure to meet a required
delivery,'' the Air Force said in a statement.
   ``Alternatives to this contract are now being addressed by a
high-level steering group convened by the commander of the Air
Force Systems Command,'' the service added.
   Renald Romain, a spokesman for the Cleveland, Ohio-based Eaton,
declined comment beyond asserting: ``The the company believes it
has meritorious defenses against claims which the Air Force may
assert in connection with this termination.''
   Eaton has been attempting to sell its AIL Division since last
October, to date without success. That division had earlier come
under fire for technical deficiencies in producing similar
electronic warfare gear for the new B-1B bomber.
   According to Gerda Parr, an Air Force spokeswoman, Eaton AIL had
received progress payments totaling slightly more than $39 million
since winning the contract in 1984.
   As far as the Air Force is concerned, only $19,500 worth of work
was delivered ``and we will immediately demand repayment of the $39
million in progress payments,'' she said.
   ``The government's position also is that AIL is legally
responsible for any additional costs that the government may incur
as a result of reprocuring from another contractor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
