<DOCNO> AP880610-0330 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AutoTalks     06-10 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Talks,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Striking C&C In First Contract Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers and a Brighton car
customizing firm continued contract talks Friday aimed at ending a
650-worker strike that has halted production of the Ford Mustang
convertible and other vehicles.
   ``They're pretty close. We're still hoping we can get that thing
settled,'' said Stan Marshall, director of UAW Region IC, which
includes Brighton.
   Workers at C&C, which stands for Cars & Concepts, voted to be
represented by the UAW earlier this year but company protests
delayed certification of the union until April 1, Marshall said.
   When negotiations on C&C's first UAW contract bogged down,
leaders of newly formed UAW Local 4077 set a strike deadline for
midnight Tuesday, then extended it 10 a.m. Wednesday, when workers
walked out.
   Marshall said the two sides still had to settle differences over
wages, seniority rights, pensions and other benefits. Wages for
jobs in the same classification can range from $4 an hour to $11 an
hour.
   The UAW wants workers who do the same job to be paid the same
wage, Marshall said.
   C&C Inc., which also is modifying Chrysler Corp. models for
export to Europe and working on four-wheel-drive chassis for
General Motors Corp., is owned by Masco Industries Inc.
   The strike interrupted production of the Ford Mustang
convertible, which Ford spokesman Rod Seib said was the
best-selling convertible in the United States during 1987.
   Seib said the strike is costing Ford and its dealers about 160
Mustang convertibles a day during the height of the convertible
selling season. Ford sold 25,212 of the convertibles in 1987 and
has room to build about 33,000 in 1988.
   All Mustang models remain in short supply _ 35 days' worth
compared to the industry norm of 60-65 days' worth _ but the
convertibles are particularly scarce, Seib said.
   Chrysler spokesman Tom Houston said earlier that the strike
could force Chrysler to find another company to modify cars for its
re-entry into the European market, which began about six weeks ago.
Chrysler hopes to export 5,000 to 10,000 cars a year to Europe.
</TEXT>
