<DOCNO> AP880610-0334 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     06-10 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Department Provides Good News On Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has released more positive news on inflation,
reporting that prices on the wholesale level rose a modest 0.5
percent in May.
   On Wall Street, stock prices were helped by Friday's report. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed 8.36 points higher
Friday at 2,101.71. Brokers said there was a feeling of relief
among investors that the news wasn't worse.
   Bond prices were mixed while the dollar rose in domestic trading
after falling overseas. Gold prices plunged.
   The growth in the Labor Department's producer price index for
finished wholesale goods in May was halfway between a 0.4 percent
increase in April and a 0.6 percent jump in March.
   If it continued for 12 months, the annual rate of inflation
would amount to 5.8 percent, nearly triple the 2 percentage points
it has risen in the past year.
   Still, economists said Friday that concerns of runaway inflation
are unfounded.
   ``There clearly is some inflation in the system, but the fears
of an inflationary boom are overblown,'' said Larry Chimerine,
president of the WEFA Group, formerly Wharton Econometrics, an
economic forecasting consultant in Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
   The White House also took comfort from the May numbers.
``Inflation remains low and under control,'' said spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   Food replaced energy as the primary impetus behind higher
wholesale prices last month, according to the report. At the prices
paid by grocery stores, food rose 0.9 percent in May _ the biggest
increase since a 1.7 percent jump in January.
   Energy prices, which had surged 3.1 percent in April, rose only
0.2 percent in May, largely because of a 3.8 percent drop in
natural gas prices, the report said.
   In other economic developments Friday, oil futures prices fell
amid concerns about the upcoming OPEC meeting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, fell 34 cents a
barrel Friday to close at $16.73 a barrel.
   The market was jittery in advance of the 13-nation Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries' meeting that begins today in
Vienna, Austria. OPEC oil ministers are expected to discuss
possible production cuts to defend their official price target of
$18 a barrel, but chances for an agreement appeared to be slim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
