<DOCNO> AP880610-0335 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 2219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     06-10 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anxiety about the upcoming OPEC meeting coupled
with technical market factors have sent energy futures prices
skidding.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Friday, the July contract
for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, fell 34
cents per barrel to close at $16.73. On Thursday, the key contract
fell 26 cents.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange Friday, contracts
for July delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline settled 0.48 cent
lower at 49.22 cents a gallon, and wholesale heating oil closed at
44.25 cents a gallon, down 0.65 cent.
   ``Sellers completely dominated the market,'' said Madison
Galbraith, senior energy specialist with Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
   Technical factors were behind the decline, but the market was
also jittery in advance of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries' meeting that was opening today in Vienna,
Austria, Galbraith said.
   ``You can't take a position aganst the meeting unless you are
really gutsy,'' Galbraith said.
   OPEC oil ministers are expected to discuss possible production
cuts to defend their official target price of $18 a barrel, but
chances for an agreement appeared to be slim.
   During a meeting in April, the cartel was unable to agree on a
production-cutting proposal put forth by non-OPEC producers, and
Arab OPEC members who met this week in Algiers, Algeria, also were
unable to reach an agreeement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
